<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL-Chronology     12-06 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL-Chronology,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Long Road Of PTL Struggles Still To Come To An End</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-PTL, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of the major events at
PTL since Jim Bakker's resignation as head of the Fort Mill-based
ministry and its Heritage USA Christian theme park:
   March 19, 1987 _ Bakker resigns amid sex and money scandal
involving former New York church secretary Jessica Hahn. The Rev.
Jerry Falwell takes over as chairman of the board and Richard Dortch
becomes president of PTL.
   May 6 _ Assemblies of God leaders defrock Bakker and Dortch.
   June 12 _ PTL files for protection from creditors under Chapter
11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code.
   June 30 _ Reports surface that a federal grand jury will examine
possible wrongdoing by the Bakkers and their associates, including
whether money raised for charity was spent for the benefit of
private individuals.
   Oct. 8 _ Falwell, the PTL board of directors, the co-hosts of the
``PTL Show'' and other top executives resign from PTL during a
dispute over the bankruptcy reorganization plan and fears that
Bakker will be allowed to return. David Clark, a Christian
Broadcasting Network executive, becomes trustee.
   Dec. 22 _ U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds approves the
ministry's bankruptcy plan, which divides PTL into separate
ministerial and for-profit entities and involves a schedule for
repaying creditors. Reynolds orders PTL and the IRS to work out
their differences within 60 days.
   Jan. 31, 1988 _ PTL sues Bakker and his chief aide, David
Taggart, for $52 million for recovery of unwarranted compensation
and funds lost through mismanagement.
   April 15 _ PTL announces it will not be able to make a bankruptcy
payment and that it will lay off 125 full-time employees. Reynolds
orders Clark to draw up plan for selling assets.
   April 22 _ The IRS revokes PTL's tax-exempt status.
   May 13 _ Charlotte sports owner George Shinn announces intention
to buy PTL and build a baseball stadium on its undeveloped land.
   May 20 _ Clark resigns as PTL trustee to become president of
Heritage Ministries, the non-profit ministerial entity. Former
Winston-Salem, N.C., mayor M.C. Benton becomes the new trustee.
Clark later resigns as president of Heritage Ministries.
   June 7 _ Jim and Tammy Bakker return to York County from
California. They open an office for Jim and Tammy Ministries and
move into a condominium costing $1,000 a month that is paid for by
supporters.
   Aug. 5 _ Benton makes tentative agreement to sell Heritage USA to
Canadian businessman Peter Thomas.
   Aug. 31 _ Bakker and Benton agree on terms for Bakker to buy
Heritage USA, paving the way for Bakker's return as leader of PTL.
   Sept. 9 _ Bakker misses deadline for $3 million deposit. Benton
says he will no longer negotiate with Bakker.
   Oct. 3 _ Lawyers for Canadian businessman Stephen Mernick, an
Orthodox Jew, announce Benton will recommend Mernick as the buyer of
Heritage USA.
   Nov. 3 _ U.S. Attorney Charles Alexander notifies the Bakkers and
Taggart they are the subject of a grand jury investigation.
   Nov. 10 _ Reynolds rules that the Bakkers and Taggart must pay
$7.6 million in damages to PTL.
   Nov. 16-17 _ Reynolds outlines conditions that bidders must meet
to have sale approved. Neither Mernick nor Thomas meets conditions.
Reynolds orders Benton to establish list of guidelines for buyers to
meet. Reynolds orders auction for Dec. 12 and hearing for Dec. 13 to
decide on buyer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
