<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 0036EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Castro-Salinas     12-06 0864</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Castro-Salinas,0895</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salinas & Castro: Separated By Ideology, United By Backscratching</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari
and Cuban leader Fidel Castro are poles apart ideologically, but
they found a way to do each other some good last week.
   The occasion was Thursday's inauguration of Salinas, an economist
who believes in individual effort and a smaller government.
   All Castro, a fundamentalist of communism, had to do was show up.
   Salinas' opponents, who maintain that his ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party cheated to win the presidency, were quick to
note that the occasion marked the first time foreign heads of state
had been invited to a presidential inauguration.
   ``They're desperately searching for support outside the country
because they don't have any support inside the country,'' said
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the leftist Democratic Front leader, last week.
   The Salinas transition team said Latin American heads of state
were invited because those countries wanted to invite Mexican
presidents to their own inaugurations. They said the invitations
would encourage Latin American unity.
   Those in the leftist opposition were especially disappointed that
Castro and President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua decided to come.
   ``It's up to them if they want to lend support to an illegitimate
government,'' Cardenas said before the inauguration.
   While Salinas was able to undercut his opponents and bolster his
own image, Castro saw a larger geopolitical significance in the
invitation.
   The fact that he was sitting in the same gallery with other heads
of state and a galaxy of other dignitaries, including U.S. Secretary
of State George Shultz, was both a recognition of his nation and a
symbol of triumph, he said.
   ``The U.S. strategy of isolating Cuba has failed,'' he said at a
weekend news conference. ``We never came to an inauguration before
because they didn't invite us. But now Ecuador and Mexico have
invited us. U.S. policy is a total wreck, and Cuba's position is
being vindicated by Latin America. Thirty years have gone by, and
we're still here.''
   Castro's forces overthrew the dictatorship of Fulgencio Batista
almost exactly 30 years ago, on Jan. 1, 1959.
   Ironically, one of Castro's patrons when he was organizing his
revolution here was Lazaro Cardenas, Cuauhtemoc's father.
   Lazaro Cardenas, a former president, a leftist and a power in
Mexican politics, got Castro out of trouble when he was imprisoned
while training his little band of revolutionaries near Mexico City.
   Castro was treated like a conquering hero from the moment he
arrived at Mexico City's airport Wednesday night.
   At news conferences he received lengthy rounds of applause from
local reporters. On a walking tour of the city's central Alameda, he
kissed women and children and recovered an old man's windblown hat.
   One local columnist even complimented Castro's huge squad of
bodyguards for their ``backslapping friendliness.''
   Salinas made sure to introduce the attending heads of state
during his inaugural address Thursday, and Castro got by far the
biggest ovation. By that time Cardenas supporters already had walked
out.
   Castro stood and smiled, then sat back as Salinas made it plain
he would push Mexico toward the free market and further away from
state domination of the economy.
   ``Social well-being in a modern state is not identified with
paternalism that supplants effort or inhibits character,'' Salinas
said.
   Castro, by contrast, summed up a long news conference statement
on the evils of capitalism by saying: ``Socialism cannot be built
with capitalist tools.''
   The comment was an implicit criticism of the reforms of Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev. Castro will be receiving a visit
from Gorbachev later this week.
   One issue upon which Salinas and Castro agreed on is the need to
reduce Latin America's staggering foreign debt. Mexico's stands at
$102 billion.
   But while Castro called for Draconian measures of non-payment,
Salinas leaned toward negotiation and a sales job, telling bankers
the money Mexico saves will be used to drive economic growth in a
competitive economy.
   Salinas and U.S. President-elect George Bush met 10 days before
Salinas was inaugurated and hit it off. There was ``good
chemistry,'' said Shultz, ``and that is a very good sign.''
   Castro's assessment of Bush was cautious. He said he hoped Bush
was ``pragmatic'' enough to recognize new Latin American realities,
among them the failure of U.S. efforts to isolate Cuba.
   He said Cuba would consider rejoining the Organization of
American States as an active member if invited and if the OAS became
more of a venue for Latin American nations to act in concert about
their problems.
   Castro ended his trip with a nostalgic visit to Tuxpan, the port
from which he set sail to revolutionary victory 32 years ago.
   ``Mexico is like a second fatherland. Mexico was the only country
to refuse to submit to the orders of the United States. It was the
only one not to break relations with Cuba,'' he said, referring to
Mexico's refusal to join a U.S.-led diplomatic boycott of Cuba in
the 1960s.
   ``We need Mexico. We need the prestige of Mexico,'' Castro said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Herzfelder is The Associated Press' news
editor for Mexico and Central America.
</TEXT>
