<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-SouthernAfrica 1stLd-Writethru   12-06 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Southern Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Reportedly Will Sign Peace Solution</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with report of South Africa
assuring U.S. it will sign agreement, move up background on the goal
of the talks; PICKS UP penultimate graf pvs bgng, `South African'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa, which last week walked out of
U.S.-mediated talks seeking the withdrawal of foreign forces from
southwestern Africa, reportedly has assured the United States it
will sign the settlement.
   The Washington Post reported in Tuesday's editions that South
Africa has resolved an internal conflict over terms of the accord
and that U.S. officials expect at least that the protocol to the
settlement will be signed later this month and perhaps the full
document as well.
   ``It looks as though they have worked out what was bothering
them,'' the newspaper quoted an unidentified U.S. official as
saying. ``They will go ahead.''
   The walkout had prompted speculation that South Africa would not
sign the agreement but the Post said the delay appeared to be caused
by internal South African political dynamics and not terms of the
accord.
   The goal of the talks, which involve Cuba, Angola and South
Africa, is agreement on the withdrawal of Cuban forces from Angola
and on Namibian independence from South Africa. U.S. Assistant
Secretary of State Chester Crocker is serving as mediator for the
talks.
   Before the start of the talks in Brazzaville, the Congo, there
had been high hopes they would conclude with a signed agreement. But
the South African delegation walked out Saturday night, producing
speculation that the negotiations had been derailed.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Monday there was
``considerable progress'' last week and ``we still look forward
resolving the issues that remain and concluding a final settlement
as soon as possible.''
   He denied suggestions that a hitch had developed in the talks
over the process by which the withdrawal of Cuban troops would be
verified.
   ``Unless the parties change their basic decisions, the process
remains on track,'' Redman said.
   South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha also has denied that the
talks are at an impasse.
   ``The process is irreversible,'' Botha said Sunday. ``We continue
to progress step-by-step.'' He added that the talks could be resumed
within a few days.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
