<2ND_LINE>AM-Minister Pleads,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Accused of Murdering Girlfriend Pleads Guilty to
Manslaughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICKSBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vicksburg minister charged with
murdering his girlfriend just hours before preaching a Sunday sermon
pleaded guilty Monday to the reduced charge of manslaughter.
   The plea bargain was reached the day before the Rev. Jonathon
Hamlin's scheduled trial for the July 3 shooting death of
24-year-old Lula Sims. A Jan. 6 sentencing date was set by Circuit
Judge Rush Clements, said Otha Jones, chief deputy in the Warren
County Sheriff's Department.
   Hamlin, a 24-year-old married man with three children, had been
living with Sims, investigators said.
   Sheriff Paul Barrett has said Hamlin confessed to the killing of
Sims, a divorced mother of three. He said Hamlin led law enforcement
officers to a shallow grave in rural Jefferson County, about 40
miles southeast of Vicksburg, where Sims' body was found about a
week after she was reported missing.
   Hamlin had been pastor at the Zion Traveler Missionary Baptist
Church since Nov. 1987, and shocked church members had praised him
as a ``first-class minister'' even after learning of the murder
charge. He also was pastor of two other small churches in the
Vicksburg area.
   Police were unsuccessful in getting Hamlin's wife, Martha Hamlin,
to answer questions in the case. Under Mississippi law, one spouse
cannot be forced to testify against the other.
   Hamlin remains free until his sentencing on a $100,000 bond he
posted after his arrest July 3, Jones said.
   There is no telephone number listed for Hamlin, and no one
answered calls for comment Monday to the home and office of his
attorney, Travis Vance Jr. of Vicksburg.
</TEXT>
