<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSLawsuit 1stLd-Writethru a0781 12-06 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Lawsuit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0781,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Reverses $1.6 Million Award In AIDS Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Miles, based ..., to CORRECT state to Ind.,
sted Ill.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $1.6 million damage award won by a man who said
he got AIDS from a blood-based medicine he took for hemophilia, was
reversed Monday by a federal judge who ruled the evidence did not
support a jury's verdict.
   U.S. District Judge Orinda Evans said in a 14-page ruling that
the verdict, reached by a federal jury after two days of
deliberation in October, had no basis in law or fact. She reversed
the verdict in favor of Randy L. Jones, 35, and granted judgment for
Miles Laboratories.
   Miles, based in Elkhart, Ind., manufactures Koate, a blood-based
``Factor VIII'' clotting product which Jones took to control a mild
case of hemophilia after surgery at Clayton General Hospital in 1983.
   Jones who lives in the Atlanta area, was diagnosed in 1985 as
infected with the virus that causes AIDS. Two years later, he was
told by doctors he had developed the disease itself.
   In his lawsuit, Jones contended the drug he took had been
contaminated with the AIDS virus contracted by an unemployed Texas
man who allegedly sold plasma 40 times to a plasma center in Austin,
Texas, which in turn supplied Miles.
   The Texas man died of AIDS less than six weeks after his last
plasma sale in September 1983, the suit said.
   Jones contended in his suit that more than 60,000 vials of Koate
were contaminated with the AIDS virus because of the Texas man's
infection. He charged that Miles was negligent in acquiring and
using the infected plasma.
   Miles, in its appeal, denied any negligence.
   Bud Modersbach, the Berkeley, Calif., counsel for Cutter
Biologicals, the Miles division which manufactures Koate, said
Monday that the jury's decision was overruled because ``it was so
clear-cut.''
   Modersbach said the company had initiated a high-risk donor
screening program in February 1983, months before Jones took the
drug. And he said much less was known then about AIDS transmission
than is now known.
   He said the jury may have acted more on emotion than on the facts
in the trial.
   Judge Evans said in her ruling that Jones did not address Miles'
argument that he ``could just as well have gotten'' AIDS from other
blood factor products.
   George H. Connell Jr., Jones' attorney, said he planned to appeal
Judge Evans' ruling to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
Jones, he said, ``is a pretty strong man. He thinks he's right and
wants to pursue the appeal.''
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is an usually-fatal
disease that strikes the body's immune system. As of Thursday,
79,389 cases had been reported in the United States since 1981,
according to federal health officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881206-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 0109EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Gorbachev-PressPlane Bjt   12-06 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gorbachev-Press Plane, Bjt,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Not Quite The White House As Kremlin Press Plane Makes Debut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ilyushin-62M aircraft that arrived here
resembles the one used by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
Actually, it was the Kremlin's first ever press plane, dubbed by its
occupants, ``Glasnost One.''
   The Aeroflot charter touched down Monday at John F. Kennedy
International Airport, 24 hours ahead of the Soviet leader'
scheduled arrival. It will accompany Gorbachev throughout his trip
this week to New York, Havana and London.
   The caviar was black, Russian and better than the fare usually
found at 30,000 feet, but the inaugural flight of Glasnost One,
named after Gorbachev's policy of openness, had little else to
recommend it.
   The trip began at 6:30 a.m. Moscow time with dozens of
journalists shivering in the zero-degree darkness outside the Soviet
Foreign Ministry press center as they waited for the first of two
special buses to take them to the airport.
   It ended 20 hours later, at 6:30 p.m. EST, with 70 disgruntled
reporters, photographers and camera crews milling about outside the
United Nations, abandoned by their Soviet escorts with no passes to
enter the U.N. building, where Gorbachev is to address the General
Assembly on Wednesday.
   As might be expected on a first flight, Glasnost One had none of
the practiced perfection that has given the press corps that travels
aboard the White House press plane the reputation of a pampered
pack. There was no pocket-size printed schedule with every move
clocked to the minute, no ``spin doctors'' available to offer
precious background, no speech transcripts and, most important, no
accreditation, which the White House always arranges for those
traveling with it.
   Organized at the request of Moscow's foreign press corps, which
quickly discerned it could not keep up with Gorbachev by flying
commercial _ particularly since there is no direct service between
the United States and Cuba _ the flight offered the singular
advantage of speed.
   But with only one event, a news conference, scheduled for Monday,
the gang from Glasnost One missed it. Representatives of the
official Soviet press got there in plenty of time, however, by
taking the Pan Am nonstop two days before.
   For a fare of $4,880 _ foreign currency only, no rubles please _
the charter did provide relatively quick passage through the
notoriously slow-moving lines at Customs and Passport Control in
Moscow's Sheremetovo Airport.
   But the flight entailed a three-hour rest and refueling stop at
Gander, Newfoundland, and upon arrival at JFK, the plane taxied to a
remote revetment, where the passengers huddled beneath the belly of
the craft to claim each piece of luggage and camera gear before
loading their buses for the trip into Manhattan.
   With no schedule and none of their ``ministry minders''
disclosing any plans, no one realized until the buses crossed the
East River and turned north instead of south that they weren't
headed for the United Nations.
   As the buses pulled up not far from the Soviet Mission to the
United Nations, a tall thin Soviet escort who never gave his name
said he was going around the corner to get further instructions. He
returned several minutes later, saying he could find no one in
authority, everyone apparently having gone to the press conference
that was just about over blocks away at U.N. headquarters.
   He gave them a phone number to try later, then stepped off the
bus as it pulled away to take the weary mob to the United Nations,
which by then had closed.
   ``All the best!'' he said, and vanished into the night.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITORS' NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Putzel traveled for seven years with the
White House press corps during the presidencies of Jimmy Carter and
Ronald Reagan before being named chief of bureau in Moscow.

</TEXT>
