<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador-Attack     12-06 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Attack,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Attack Brigade Headquarters, Claim 28 Casualties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist insurgents attacked an
army brigade headquarters late Monday with mortars and assault
rifles and claimed to they killed or wounded 28 government soldiers.
   The attack occurred at the 3rd brigade's compound in the eastern
city of San Miguel. It was the third time this year that rebels have
struck a brigade headquarters.
   An officer reached by telephone at the brigade said a few mortar
rounds apparently fell inside the base perimeter but that damage
appeared slight. The officer, who refused to give his name, had no
information on possible casualties.
   The YSU radio station quoted military sources as saying two
mortar rounds fell inside brigade headquarters.
   The clandestine guerrilla Radio Venceremos said the attack killed
or wounded 28 soldiers from the 3rd brigade or from the elite Arce
Battalion, which is attached to the brigade.
   Guerrillas in recent months have tended to inflate their claims
of casualties inflicted on government forces.
   Authorities said the Marxist-led rebels, who have been at war
nine years with the U.S.-backed government, also destroyed with
incendiary bombs two stores in San Miguel, 85 miles east of the
capital.
   Army Col. Leon Linares, speaking by telephone with the YSU radio
station, said from San Miguel that three mortar rounds were fired at
the brigade and Arce sector. He did not indicate what damage they
may have caused.
   Linares said the 2{-hour attack was directed at civilian targets.
   Sporadic gunfire was heard in several parts of the city.
   The guerrillas, in their radio broadcast, said the attack was
part of an offensive dubbed ``Power and organization of the people
on its march toward insurrection.''
   The insurgents attacked the 6th brigade in Usulutan in February
and the 4th brigade in El Paraiso in September. Both those attacks
appeared to be larger than Monday's.
</TEXT>
