<HEAD>Honduran Parties Nominate Presidential Candidates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Liberal Party
announced that Carlos Flores Facuse, a newspaper editor and
industrial engineer, won its primary for the November 1989
presidential elections.
   ``I'm optimistic and ready to wage battle,'' Flores Facuse, 42,
said after Monday's announcement.
   Flores Facuse, editor of the newspaper La Tribuna, defeated three
opponents in nationwide balloting. He will face Rafael Callejas of
the conservative National Party, the only candidate in that party's
primary, which was also held Sunday.
   Callejas, 42, is an agricultural economist and previously served
as agriculture minister.
   Two smaller parties, the opposition Innovation and Christian
Democratic parties, plan to stage their own presidential primaries
on Feb. 5.
   Hondurans vote Nov. 26 to elect a president, three vice
presidents, 128 national legislators and 298 mayors.
   President Jose Azcona Hoyo, elected in 1985, is barred by the
Honduran constitution from running for a second term.
   The armed forces governed Honduras for nearly 20 years before a
return to civilian rule in 1982. The military still wields
considerable political power.
