<1ST_LINE>u w AM-RockyFlats 1stLd-Writethru a0416 12-06 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rocky Flats, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0416,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOE Hopes Rocky Flats Plant Will Reopen By Late January</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``The plant...'' to CORRECT
occupations of those exposed to radiation; picks up 7th graf pvs,
bgng: ``Ovvicials said...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plutonium processing could resume by late
January at the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant in Colorado, an
Energy Department spokesman said Monday.
   DOE shut down the main plutonium processing room at the plant
Oct. 8 because of a safety violation.
   Officials hope the plant's operator, Rockwell International
Corp., will have a startup plan by mid-January, said Rich Marquez, a
spokesman for the DOE's Albuquerque operations office, which
oversees the plant 16 miles northwest of Denver.
   The Energy Department then would review the plan and inspect the
plant, Marquez said, adding that the plutonium processing then could
be restarted by late January.
   ``It's critical to reopen the facility, but it's equally critical
that it be done right,'' Marquez said, adding that the Energy
Department has not had a specific schedule for reopening.
   The plant was shut down in response to a Sept. 29 incident in
which an Energy Department inspector and two Rockwell employees
entered a room in which workers were cleaning up radioactive
contamination, officials said.
   Officials said the workers in the room were wearing protective
clothing and masks, but the inspector and two Rockwell employees
were not because a warning sign was blocked from view. Energy
officials said two of them tested positive for contamination, but
the situation was not viewed as life-threatening.
   Marquez said Rockwell has been cleaning up the facility,
measuring the level of radiation in the building and working on any
needed modifications to procedures as part of its reopening plan.
   The reopening could be put off until February or March, he said,
adding, ``Up to now, things are progressing as they should.''
</TEXT>
