<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 0148EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     12-06 0846</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Sees No Major Trade Deal At Montreal Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This week's trade talks in Montreal are
unlikely to result in any major new agreement to reduce agriculture
subsidies around the world, says one farm lawmaker, and that could
lead Congress to take an even harder line when writing the next
generation of U.S. agriculture law.
   ``A major agriculture accord in Montreal ... is not going to
happen,'' said Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., chairman of the House
Agriculture grains subcommittee. Glickman spent two days in Montreal
talking with negotiators before the talks opened Monday.
   But unless the 12-nation European Community, the major U.S. foe
on the farm-subsidy issue, makes strides toward an eventual
elimination of subsidies, ``the 1990 farm bill will take an
assertive, aggressive and rather combative attitude,'' Glickman
predicted.
   Other farm lawmakers in Montreal to observe the talks, including
Senate Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., have
been pushing the same message.
   ``I got the clear feeling that the EC is not terribly interested
in negotiating away their unfair trade subsidies,'' he said. ``They
are going into the next two years with a very hard-line attitude.''
   The EC contends that its farm subsidies are not unfair to other
trading nations, and it has said it would be willing to scale back
such government assistance programs if proportional cutbacks also
were made by other major trading countries.
   Glickman said the dispute makes it important that the United
States continue to give strong emphasis to export subsidies _ many
of which were devised to counter similar subsidies by the EC _ and
not let them fall victim to the budget knife in the Congress that
convenes in January.
   ``Agriculture is going to have to share in these budget cuts,''
he said. ``But there are a variety of ways agriculture can cope''
with having less money. ``We have to protect (export subsidy)
spending, or the EC will eat our lunch.''
   The dispute over how to handle agricultural subsidies was at the
top of the agenda as the 96 signatory nations to the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade met in Montreal. Failure to reach an
accord on how to handle the subsidies issue threatened to stymie
progress in other trade areas.
   The United States is pressing for an end to all farm subsidies on
a definite timetable. That would be advantageous to the 2 million or
so U.S. commercial farmers because they are larger-scale and more
efficient producers.
   But for the EC, which has for years heavily subsidized its 11
million-plus farm producers, it would be politically impossible to
eliminate all farm support payments.
   The chief U.S. agriculture negotiator, Daniel Amstutz, said the
United States had moved away from setting a deadline of the year
2000 for elimination of subsidies. ``We're flexible,'' he said, but
``we'd rather not have any agreement than a bad one.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department released a new
outlook report indicating U.S. farm exports are expected to continue
to climb in the current fiscal year, growing by $1 billion to a
total of $36.5 billion.
   A $2.5 billion rise in grain and feed shipments will more than
offset declines in the value of cotton and oilseed exports, the
department projected.
   Agricultural imports, meanwhile, were expected to match the
fiscal 1988 record of $21 billion, meaning an overall increase of $1
billion in the U.S. farm trade surplus, to $15.5 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study by the International Monetary Fund has
strongly criticized the joint farm policies of the 12 governments in
the European Community.
   ``The basic mistake ... is the belief that stable and adequate
incomes for farmers can be achieved through agricultural price
support,'' the study said.
   ``As historical experience has vividly demonstrated, this
instrument is neither effective nor efficient.''
   It added that the system has brought windfall gains to efficient,
large-scale European farmers and has not given adequate income to
small ones.
   The study, ``The Common Agricultural Policy of the European
Community,'' was written by six experts of the Fund, which is owned
by 151 governments.
   European farmers get protection from foreign competition by a
system of variable levies on imports. These are customs duties that
rise and fall with world prices, payable by European importers so
that domestic products are cheaper to European consumers at any
given moment. Farmers also benefit from price supports to keep their
incomes relatively high. This system helped Western Europe become
self-sufficient in food after World War II, but in recent years it
has encouraged the creation of huge product surpluses.
   The community has a problem in exporting its surpluses and uses
European tax money to subsidize the sales and to pay the enormous
cost of storing the excess.
   The U.S. government also uses price supports to keep farmers'
incomes high, restricts imports and thus creates surpluses. It also
uses tax money to subsidize exports, but according to the fund's
figures the Europeans have increased their share of the world's
export trade in farm products in recent years.
</TEXT>
