<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HouseLeaders     12-06 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-House Leaders,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Leaders Put Focus On Campaign Reform For 1989</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WX7, WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Democratic and Republican leaders are
putting election campaign reform high on their 1989 agendas, but
they are disagreeing over whether House members need stricter ethics
standards.
   Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and Minority Leader Bob Michel,
R-Ill., both are calling for changes in a system that is successful
for incumbents: voters last month re-elected 402 of the 408 House
members seeking new terms.
   ``We'll pass clean elections legislation,'' Wright told his
Democratic colleagues Monday after they unanimously voted to give
him a second two-year term as the House's top official.
   The only specific change he mentioned, however, was a law setting
a simultaneous poll closing time around the nation, which advocates
see as a way of preventing voting in the West from being influenced
by results in the East.
   Michel, whose party has had difficulty cutting into the 260-175
Democratic bulge in the House, made no specific election proposals
as he called for Wright to join in forming a bipartisan task force
to ``fashion reforms of (House) ethics standards, outside income and
campaign practices.''
   Michel made the call as he was unanimously elected by the
Republicans to his fifth two-year term as their leader. His speech
put far more emphasis on ethics than on campaign reform, an issue
that Congress has grappled with unsuccessfully for a decade.
   ``The record of (ethics) enforcement in this House is a national
disgrace,'' said Michel, who referred to no specific cases. ``We
must more clearly define our ethics rules and then we have to
enforce them. ... The time for reform is here.''
   Wright, meeting with reporters later in the day, disagreed with
Michel's assessment on ethics but offered to discuss the issues with
him.
   ``For the most part, members of the House ... are decent,
responsible and ethical people,'' said Wright, whose personal
finances and possible divulging of government secrets are under
investigation by the House ethics committee. He has denied any
wrongdoing.
   In his acceptance speech, Wright said the House in the 101st
Congress would approve a new Clean Air Act and would work to ``clean
up those areas of our business practices where management needs
regulation.''
   He cited the disappearance of banks, corporations and farms in
economic reshufflings and leveraged buyouts that ``intensify and
concentrate economic wealth in fewer and fewer hands.''
   In the separate party meetings, two women House members lost bids
to crack the all-male top leadership ranks.
   On the Republican side, Rep. Lynn Martin of Illinois came up four
votes short of beating Rep. Jerry Lewis of California for chairman
of the House Republican Conference, the No. 3 GOP leadership post.
   Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, was defeated easily by Rep. William
Gray, D-Pa., for chairmanship of the House Democratic Caucus, the
No. 4 job in the Democratic hierarchy. He replaces Rep. Richard
Gephardt, D-Mo.
   Gray's election marked the first time a black House member had
advanced this high on a leadership ladder that traditionally has led
to the speaker's office. He earned high marks over the past four
years as Budget Committee chairman, a pivotal House post that
carries a two-term limit.
   Gray said he was proud of his racial heritage but was not elected
because of it.
   He said he hoped to be a role model to blacks ``to show them you
ought to strive, you ought to work, you ought to aim high. ... But
as chairman of the Democratic Caucus, I will represent the interests
of the entire Democratic party.''
   The rest of the leadership races were uncontested and were filled
by acclamation.
   Rep. Tom Foley, D-Wash., was given a second term as House
majority leader, while Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., won his second
two-year stint as majority whip, the No. 3 Democratic post.
   Rep. Dick Cheney, R-Wyo., moved into the No. 2 GOP job of
minority whip, succeeding Rep. Trent Lott, R-Miss., who was elected
to the Senate last month.
</TEXT>
