<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AlzheimerDrug     12-06 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alzheimer Drug,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nobel Winner Said to Regain Some Memory with Alzheimer Drug</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 78-year-old Nobel Prize-winning chemist, Archer
Martin, has regained some of his memory after taking an experimental
drug for Alzheimer's disease, his wife says.
   ``I get the feeling that I can think again,'' Martin was quoted
in a front-page report in the Sunday Times as saying.
   Professor Raymond Levy, in whose tests Martin participated,
cautioned that the drug treats the symptoms, not the disease, and is
``unlikely to be a cure in any sense.''
   Martin was one of the first volunteers when tests of the drug
tetrahydroaminoacridine, or THA, began at London's Institute of
Psychiatry in March, and his condition improved immediately, his
wife Judith said Monday.
   ``He responded, not miraculously, but there was certainly a
reduction in the deterioration which was immediately noticeable,''
she told British Broadcasting Corp. radio from the couple's
Cambridge home.
   ``He didn't have attacks or irritability nearly so often. It
certainly appeared encouraging from fairly early on.''
   Alzheimer's disease is a progressive, irreversible neurological
disease with no known cause or cure. Victims, mostly elderly people,
suffer gradual memory loss, disorientation and personality changes.
   Levy, who is conducting the trials, told The Associated Press
that THA is not a cure.
   ``It doesn't reverse the process and I think it's unlikely to be
a cure in any sense,'' he said. ``It's dealing with symptoms,
really, rather than the basic cause of the disease.''
   Levy, a professor of old-age psychiatry, said THA seems to
preserve a chemical messenger called acetylcholine that helps
control memory.
   However, brain cells die as Alzheimer's disease progresses and a
drug such as THA can work only as long as there are enough living
cells to produce sufficient levels of acetylcholine.
   Martin, a biochemist, won the Nobel Prize in 1952 for his work on
chromatography, a method of separating chemical substances. His
discoveries transformed chemistry and are still widely used in
medicine and industry.
   Mrs. Martin said her husband began losing his memory four years
ago and could not work because he forgot everything he read.
   THA has side-effects, including a risk of liver damage, but Mrs.
Martin said: ``As a scientist and as a scientist's wife, we are both
well-equipped to observe anything that might be going wrong.''
   Other side effects reported from THA experiments include nausea,
vomiting and allergic reactions.
   The drug hit the headlines in 1986 with a report of effectiveness
by a California investigator. But this year, the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration said it found ``numerous statements'' in the report
that appeared to be false, and that the investigator ``repeatedly or
deliberately'' violated regulations on proper conduct of testing
drugs.
   THA now is being studied in followup research in the United
States.
   Levy said 32 people are involved in his trials. He said the drug
produced ``staggering'' results in three of the first volunteers,
including a potter who was able to return to her craft. But it also
produced no results in three other early volunteers, he said.
   Martin declined to be interviewed Monday, but The Sunday Times
said he was able to give lengthy explanations of enzyme activity and
its relation to the release of energy for mental activity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881206-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 0143EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChemicalWeapons-Suit     12-06 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chemical Weapons-Suit,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environmental Group Seeks To Halt Chemical Warfare Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An environmental group's lawsuit to stop the
Defense Department's chemical and biological weapons research and
production accuses the Pentagon of ``recklessly endangering'' the
lives of military and civilian populations.
   A central assertion of the suit filed Monday in U.S. District
Court by the Foundation on Economic Trends is that the Pentagon has
greatly expanded the scope of such weapons programs without fully
studying their effects on people and communities.
   The production and storage of chemical agents ``present immediate
and potentially catastrophic environmental and human health hazards
to local communities and populations,'' and yet the Pentagon has
taken a cavalier attitude toward public safety, the suit charges.
   The suit requests preliminary and permanent injunctions until the
Pentagon and armed services conduct detailed environmental studies
of every phase of their chemical warfare programs.
   ``The dramatic increase in the Pentagon's chemical warfare
program has placed communities across the country at risk,'' charged
Jeremy Rifkin, the president of the Washington-based foundation.
   ``The Defense Department is recklessly endangering laboratory
workers, military personnel and the general public in communities
where chemical warfare laboratories and storage facilities are
located,'' the suit said.
   The service declined to comment Monday on the foundation's suit,
saying it still was studying the matter, but insisted in a statement
it was ``committed to both the environment and public safety.''
   To buttress its case, the foundation filed with the court a copy
of an Army inspector general's evaluation of chemical safety
procedures, completed this spring and first disclosed on Capitol
Hill this summer.
   The Army is by far the largest service when it comes to
responsibility for chemical and biological warfare research.
   The internal audit concluded the Army had not assigned enough
people to chemical safety programs, ``with expertise only `one deep'
in most instances.''
   It also found ``there is not an effective oversight program in
place for chemical safety; that chemical safety has slipped through
a crack.''
   The Army previously had responded to the inspector general's
audit by ordering improvements and a new study to ``evaluate
adequacy of staffing for chemical safety at all levels.''
   The Foundation on Economic Trends is an environmental group that
long has focused its attention on the dangers of biological research
and genetic engineering.
   The United States, citing production by the Soviet Union,
recently began making a new generation of toxic chemical weapons. On
the biological front _ using live, deadly organisms as a weapon _
the United States has committed itself by international treaty not
to develop new weapons, but still conducts research to develop
vaccines and antidotes, detection systems and defensive battlefield
gear.
   The foundation alleges that the Pentagon has so dramatically
increased the funding and scope of its chemical and biological
programs _ with appropriations rising 600 percent since fiscal 1980
to more than $271 million _ that it is required to study
environmental impacts even though the programs may be ongoing.
   ``Given the exponential growth in size and scope of the chemical
warfare program ... the defendants cannot validly exclude those
programs from the requirements of the National Environmental Policy
Act,'' the suit asserts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
