<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former LaRouche Aide Says Debts Had Quadrupled</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: trial resumes 10 a.m. EST; lead planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former finance officer for Lyndon H.
LaRouche Jr. says the political maverick's debts quadrupled to $40
million within one year because of heavy new borrowing on top of old
loans that weren't being repaid as promised.
   Wayne Hintz said he eventually quit his job of trying to ``crisis
manage'' LaRouche's fast-growing debt in 1986.
   Hintz testified Monday at the start of the third week of
LaRouche's mail and tax fraud conspiracy trial in U.S. District
Court.
   Prosecutors said they probably would complete their case against
LaRouche today. Lawyers for the perennial presidential candidate say
they haven't decided whether to summon LaRouche to testify in his
own defense.
   LaRouche and six associates are charged with mail fraud and
conspiracy for allegedly raising more than $30 million in loans with
no intention of repaying them.
   In addition, LaRouche was charged with conspiring to defraud the
Internal Revenue Service by having all his personal expenses paid by
various corporations he controls and not filing any income tax
returns since 1978.
   If convicted on all 13 counts against him, LaRouche would face a
maximum penalty of 65 years in prison and fines totaling $3.25
million.
   In a separate case scheduled for retrial in Boston on Jan. 3,
LaRouche is charged with conspiracy to obstruct justice in
connection with alleged unauthorized use of credit cards by 18 of
his followers to raise $1 million for his 1984 presidential campaign.
   Hintz told the federal trial jury here Monday that despite a
promise by higher-ups to allocate $80,000 a week to pay off old
loans, ``we had become increasingly behind in debt'' by the end of
1985.
   He estimated that the LaRouche organization's total debt early
that year was about $10 million owed to 2,000 lenders. But because
new loans were being made and old ones weren't being repaid, the
debt had swollen to $40 million by year's end.
   The promised $80,000 a week actually was allocated only once, he
said, and the average made available for retiring debt was less than
half that amount.
   He said it would have taken $69,000 a week just to pay the
interest on new loans.
   Steven Bardwell of Hastings on Hudson, N.Y., former editor of a
LaRouche magazine called Fusions, testified Monday that LaRouche
exhorted his followers to raise large sums to help him save humanity
from nuclear war.
   The first priority for spending money raised from loans and
contributions was to guarantee LaRouche's security against possible
assassination attempts, said Bardwell.
   He said LaRouche berated fund-raisers who failed to meet their
quotas by accusing them of suffering ``sexual impotence.''
   Bardwell said that after he quit the LaRouche organization in
1984 over a defense policy dispute with LaRouche, he hosted a
Halloween party for former LaRouche employees such as himself.
   One guest wore a pig snout, and another came dressed as the
Ayatollah Khomeini of Iran. But the party was less than a success,
Bardwell said.
   Bardwell suggested they play ``Pin the Rap on Lyndon.'' But he
said Monday that ``not many people thought that was funny.''
   Even worse, he said, a gate-crasher who still worked for LaRouche
came dressed as an AIDS virus, enjoyed the party and then tattled to
his superiors.
   ``I thought it was very rude to come to my party and drink my
liquor and eat my food and then go back and report on it,'' Bardwell
said.
</TEXT>
