<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-06 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Faintich paid $50 for a dollar bill, and
he may have snagged a bargain.
   The 1985 dollar bill that caught his eye during a transaction at
his coin shop in nearby Clayton is a rarity because it bears no
Treasury Department seal, no district seal and no serial number.
   A Bureau of Engraving and Printing spokesman in Washington, D.C.,
said Faintich, at the least, has a nice conversation piece.
   ``It doesn't happen all the time,'' said spokesman Ira Polikoff.
``On occasion, they get out. I wouldn't say it's going to make him a
rich man, but it's unique.''
   Polikoff said the Treasury prints between five and six billion
notes a year with an error rate of about 0.3 percent. Bills are
printed in sheets of 32, but it is possible only one bill failed to
receive the proper markings, he said.
   Faintich's bill is in nearly mint condition. He said he had heard
of bills of this sort being sold in the past for $150 to $200.
   ``It's a neat error,'' Faintich said. ``Nice funny money.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Santa had room on his lap for
grownups, he'd find they have more than visions of power
screwdrivers, driving gloves and dishwashers on their Christmas
lists.
   Adults still yearn for toys, just bigger. More expensive. Or more
elusive.
   Glenda Highland of nearby Millstadt has one item high on her list
_ he should be about 6-foot-3, with blond hair and blue eyes.
   But she's flexible.
   ``Or I'll take dark hair, dark eyes and an olive complexion,''
she told the Bellville News-Democrat last week in this southern
Illinois city.
   At the top of Laura Denning's list was one bigger-than-a-breadbox
item: a medium blue sports car with all the extras.
   Ron Edgar's list is short.
   ``A job,'' he said, laughing. ``A good-paying job.''
   Fran Huber of Collinsville is wishing for a worker _ but the job
likely won't fill the bill for Edgar.
   ``First, I'd like a baby sitter _ fulltime, live-in,'' said
Huber, two young daughters tugging at her as she took a break from
Christmas shopping in downtown Belleville.
   ``What the heck, add someone to do the cleaning, too,'' she said
as the girls raced off to look in a shop window. ``I'm not
particular, they can be the same person.''
   What would Huber do with all that free time?
   Following her daughters into the store, she turned and yelled,
``Go away somewhere quiet!''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willie B, the former couch potato gorilla, is
working himself into shape now that he has room to get out and do
some jogging.
   Zoo Atlanta's silverback gorilla, who has spent most of his 30
years in a cage, was released into a new outdoor habitat in April.
He had his first physical since that release last week.
   Willie weighs 440 pounds, down from 459 pounds, zoo veterinarian
Dr. Rita McManamon said.
   ``This is a good weight loss,'' she said. ``We feel it is due to
more psychological stimulation and physical activity in the outdoor
environment.''
   For most of his 30 years, Willie B, a member of a species being
wiped out in its native Africa by habitat destruction and poaching,
lived in a large cage built for chimpanzees in the zoo's primate
house.
   Bored stiff most of the time, Willie was given a television set
to help him pass the time.
</TEXT>
