<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     12-06 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Nikkei Rebounds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while share prices moderately rebounded on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 121.54 yen, up 0.01 yen from Monday's close
of 121.53 yen. Opening at 121.57 yen, the U.S. currency moved in a
tight range of 121.51-121.60 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 50.82-point
loser the previous day, regained 54.70 points or 0.18 percent to
close at 29,669.38. The index gained 140.05 points shortly after the
market opened but the gain gradually decreased.
   Dealers said news of Emperor Hirohito stabilizing brought out
active market participants who had taken to the sidelines Monday
after reports that the monarch had suffered massive hemorrhaging.
   ``There is no major economic factor that is responsible for the
gain this (Tuesday) morning, except for news that the emperor's
condition has stabilized,'' said one analyst with Nomura Securities,
Japan's largest brokerage.
   Other dealers said the surging Nikkei index reflected investor
feelings that the Tokyo market was less worried and even ready to
deal with possible higher U.S. interest rates.
   In foreign currency trading, dealers said activity was slow
mainly due to uncertainties over the outlook for U.S. interest rates
and Hirohito's condition.
   They said market players were inclined to remain on the sidelines
in the absence of major news affecting the market. But market
sentiment is still bearish for the dollar, dealers noted.
   On Monday, Hirohito discharged a substantial amount of blood and
his blood pressure plummeted to its lowest level since he fell ill
in September. His vital signs recovered to near normal levels after
massive blood transfusions.
</TEXT>
