<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 0248EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HiddenFaults     12-06 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hidden Faults,0726</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Concealed Quake Faults Pose Extensive Hazard Under Los Angeles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two concealed but active faults cut giant
swaths through the area and could cause a major earthquake in the
nation's second-largest city, says to a scientist, who recommends
that building codes be re-evaluated.
   The Elysian Park Fault, unknown until it caused the deadly Oct.
1, 1987, Whittier Narrows earthquake, is about 10 miles wide and 60
miles long.
   It runs from Santa Monica Bay east through Beverly Hills,
downtown Los Angeles and Monterey Park, then southeast to suburban
Whittier, Fullerton, Yorba Linda and Corona, said geophysicist Egill
Hauksson.
   While mapping the extent of that fault, University of Southern
California scientists also discovered the 40-by-10-mile
Torrance-Wilmington fault stretching from Santa Monica Bay southeast
through oil fields in Torrance and Los Angeles' Wilmington district,
the Palos Verdes Peninsula, Long Beach and offshore from Newport
Beach.
   Hauksson's study of the faults, known as thrust faults hidden by
giant folds in Earth's crust, was scheduled to be presented today at
the American Geophysical Union's fall meeting in San Francisco.
   ``There's growing evidence that there's a fairly extensive system
of those types of faults in the Los Angeles Basin,'' said Tom
Heaton, scientist in charge of the Pasadena office of the U.S.
Geological Survey, which financed Hauksson's study.
   Thrust faults have caused ``damaging and sometimes very large
earthquakes in other parts of the world,'' Heaton said.
   Hauksson said his study suggests the five segments of the Elysian
Park Fault break in separate earthquakes. So the largest jolts
possible likely would measure 6.6 on the Richter scale on a 15-mile
segment that runs under downtown Los Angeles and 6.8 on the segment
that runs from Yorba Linda northwest toward Whittier, he added.
   But Hauksson said researchers can't rule out the possibility the
entire fault could snap at once in a major 7.5-magnitude jolt that
would cause worse damage in Los Angeles than the long-feared
8-magnitude ``big one'' on the more distant San Andreas Fault.
   It took only a four-mile segment of the Elysian Park Fault to
trigger the magnitude 5.9 Whittier quake, which with its 5.3
aftershock, killed eight people, injured about 200 and caused $358
million in damage.
   The Torrance-Wilmington Fault could produce a quake with a
magnitude between 6.6 and 6.8 or so, Hauksson said.
   Seismologists still lack enough information to determine how
frequently moderate and large quakes occur on the Elysian Park and
Torrance-Wilmington faults, he added.
   He said the faults pose such a shaking hazard that building codes
should be re-evaluated.
   Downtown skyscrapers would suffer broken windows but survive a
6.6-magnitude quake, which ``would knock down a lot of old brick
buildings,'' Hauksson said.
   The faults are about 10 miles wide because thrust faults are like
giant subterranean ramps, in which ground on one side of the fault
moves upward at an angle over ground on the other side.
   For years, scientists mainly feared strike-slip faults such as
the San Andreas, where ground on one side jerks horizontally past
ground on the other side. Such a fault triggered Saturday's 5.0 jolt
that left 32 people with minor injuries.
   But Hauksson and Heaton said concealed thrust faults may pose a
greater danger than strike-slip faults.
   Hauksson mapped the Elysian Park Fault and discovered the
Torrance-Wilmington Fault by analyzing 200 quakes, mostly magnitude
2.5 to 4.0, that shook metropolitan Los Angeles from 1977 to 1988.
He found 40 percent of the quakes were centered on the two faults.
   A 1980 government study said the ``big one'' _ a magnitude 8
``great'' quake on the San Andreas some 60 miles from downtown Los
Angeles _ could kill up to 14,000 people, seriously injure 55,000
and cause $17 billion in damage.
   A 1981 federal study said a magnitude 7.5 quake on the Newport
Inglewood Fault _ the major strike-slip fault inside Los Angeles _
could kill up to 21,000 people, hospitalize 84,000 and leave 630,000
with less serious injuries.
   ``Before we knew about the thrust faults, we knew the Newport
Inglewood was there,'' Hauksson said. ``Now we've discovered two
fault structures, both of which are somewhat bigger than the
Newport-Inglewood. That tells you the earthquake potential has gone
up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
