<HEAD>Report Lists Progress Improving Control-Tower Operations at O'Hare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 102-step plan to improve operations at the
nation's busiest airport is 96 steps away from completion, according
to Federal Aviation Administration document.
   An FAA report released Monday by Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill.,
outlined progress on 42 of the proposals to reduce flight-handling
errors O'Hare International Airport in Chicago but listed only six
measures as completed.
   ``The key step was getting the action plan. The pace is picking
up, but the crisis at O'Hare isn't over,'' Simon said.
   Air traffic controllers at O'Hare committed 30 handling errors in
the first 10 months of 1988 compared with a dozen last year and
their previous high of 22 mistakes in 1986.
