<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 0258EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-IRA     12-06 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-IRA,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commons Approves Northern Ireland Anti-Violence Oath</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Commons has approved a bill that would
make all candidates for local and national elective office in
Northern Ireland sign a declaration disavowing violence.
   The measure, which passed the House by a 274-41 vote Monday
night, is seen as aimed mainly at Sinn Fein, the legal political arm
of the outlawed Irish Republican Army.
   A proposed amendment by the opposition Labor Party claiming the
bill would increase sectarian conflict in local councils in Northern
Ireland and thereby assist the cause of supporters of violence was
earlier voted down 291-195.
   Sinn Fein members elected to local councils in Northern Ireland
have repeatedly voiced support for what the IRA calls its armed
struggle _ its guerrilla war to end British rule in the province.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA wants to unite predominantly
Protestant Northern Ireland with the Republic of Ireland under
socialist rule.
   Sinn Fein commands about one-third of the Catholic vote in
Northern Ireland and captured about one-tenth of seats in 17 of the
province's 26 local councils in May 1985.
   The legislation, first announced by Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's Conservative government last year, will render elected
candidates who take the obligatory oath but then voice support for
violence liable to court prosecution by fellow council members or
members of the public. If this succeeds, they can then be
disqualified from office for five years.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King, the Cabinet member
responsible for the province, said during the Commons debate:
   ``We cannot tolerate a situation in which people will exploit to
the uttermost the freedoms and opportunities a democratic society
can provide, while at the same time reserving the right to kill,
maim and intimidate those who argue against them.''
   But Kevin McNamara, Labor's Northern Ireland spokesman, said Sinn
Fein was preparing cynically to sign the anti-violence oath.
   He added: ``Sinn Fein would be able to portray itself as the only
party that the government feels is a serious threat to its own rule
in Northern Ireland. This is a major moral and political boost to
that party.''
   Tony Benn, a leading Labor leftist and a former Cabinet member,
said there was a war going on in Northern Ireland, ``not crime in
the ordinary sense as it is presented.'' Benn said that like any
war, it would have to be brought to an end by negotiation.
   The bill now goes on to what is known as its third reading when a
Commons all-party committee examine it clause-by-clause.
   Because of the government's 100-seat majority over all other
parties combined in the 650-seat House, the bill is expected to pass
its remaining Commons stages without difficulty. It is expected to
become law in time for the next local council elections next May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
