<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     12-06 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Marginally, Stocks Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In trading lacking major market-affecting news, the
dollar rose marginally against the Japanese yen today, while share
prices moderately rebounded on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 121.54 yen, up 0.01 yen from Monday's close
of 121.53 yen. The currency, which opened slightly higher at 121.57
yen, moved in a narrow range of 121.51-121.60 yen.
   The currency market was very slow in the absence of major
market-affecting news, said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``The dollar-yen rate hardly moved in directionless trading
today,'' he said, adding that the concerns over higher U.S. interest
rates had kept market players from selling the dollar, which allowed
the currency to inch up.
   Meanwhile, Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said the dollar's
excessive fluctuation against the yen has been stabilized.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
recouped 54.70 points or 0.18 percent to finish trading at
29,669.38, a new closing high.
   Dealers attributed the Nikkei's 140.05-point rebound in early
trading to the overnight gain in the Dow Jones industrial average in
New York, but the gain in Tokyo gradually decreased afterwards.
   A dealer with a major securities firm said the index's uptrend
slackened as participants began to take profits after the gain in
the morning session.
   He said trading lacked incentives to keep the winning trend.
</TEXT>
