<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos Condo,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Marcoses Paid $2 Million For New Condo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand and Imelda Marcos have paid about $2
million for a penthouse condominium in a posh Montreal neighborhood,
a newspaper reported today.
   The Montreal Gazette quoted the condominium's builder, Angelo
Trimarchi, and sales representative Veronica Banco as saying the
penthouse was purchased through an intermediary in Italy.
   Ms. Banco was quoted as saying the Marcoses didn't come to see
the penthouse themselves.
   They said the building is still under construction in city's
Westmount neighborhood and should be completed in June, the
newspaper reported.
   It quoted Trimarchi as saying the Marcoses bought the second most
expensive unit in the building.
   The couple is charged in the United States with stealing $103
million from the Philippines during Ferdinand Marcos' 20-year reign
as president of that archipelago nation and with defrauding U.S.
banks of $165 million.
   Marcos and his family fled to exile in Hawaii in February 1986
after President Corazon Aquino took power in a military-civilian
uprising. They currently live in a house in Makiki Heights
overlooking Honolulu that is worth at least $1 million.
   Mrs. Marcos was recently reported having financial difficulties.
Her lawyers said her assets are tied up in legal proceedings.
   Tobacco heiress Doris Duke, a friend of Mrs. Marcos, posted $5
million bond for her last month after she appeared in New York to
answer the U.S. charges.
   ``I don't know if they plan to live here,'' Trimarchi was quoted
as saying. ``I don't think (the penthouse was purchased) as an
investment; if it was, they could have bought quite a few units.''
   Trimarchi and Banco were quoted as saying the penthouse was
bought by a Rome-based company after three women representing Mrs.
Marcos visited the sales office last week.
   The building, when completed, will have six two-story penthouse
suites, each with its own elevator and protected by an elaborate
security system. The Marcos penthouse has four bedrooms, three dens,
and two Roman baths, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
