<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 0532EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Rabbi-Gorbachev     12-06 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rabbi-Gorbachev,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Monitor of Soviet Religion Says Gorbachev Deserves Respect</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A longtime negotiator for religious freedom in
the Soviet Union says Mikhail S. Gorbachev deserves appreciation for
progress in that area and should be greeted with respect during his
visit here.
   ``He has recognized that the issue of human rights is an integral
component of international relations, and he has introduced numerous
changes affecting these rights, including the rights of believers,''
said Rabbi Arthur Schneier.
   ``I believe he will do more,'' said Schneier, president of the
Appeal of Conscience Foundation, an interfaith effort to expand
religious freedom around the world.
   Schneier, orthodox rabbi at Manhattan's Park East Synagogue, has
served as a point man for 25 years in seeking greater religious
freedom in various countries.
   He returned Friday from four days of meetings in Moscow with
Soviet officials about religious rights. On the basis of those
talks, he predicted ``a new liberalized code affecting religious
communities'' will be presented to the Supreme Soviet parliament in
April.
   He added, ``Our country and our Jewish community should encourage
President Gorbachev to continue in this vein.''
   Gorbachev will be staying at the U.N. Soviet Mission, across the
street from the Schneier's synagogue where a plaque reads in Hebrew
and Jewish: ``Hear the cry of the oppressed _ The Jewish community
in the Soviet Union.''
   The plaque was erected at a demonstration led by Schneier in 1965.
   But now, 23 years later, Schneier said New York Jews should greet
Gorbachev respectfully ``in recognition of the increased opportunity
for Jews in the Soviet Union to emigrate and practice their religion
and their culture at home.''
   This was made possible, Schneier said, by Gorbachev's reform
policies of perestroika, or restructuring.
   Schneier's Appeal of Conscience Foundation is a religious
coalition founded in 1965 and includes Protestant, Roman Catholic
and Eastern Orthodox leaders.
   Gorbachev also received praise Monday at a meeting of American
and Soviet religious leaders. Delegates to the U.S.-U.S.S.R.
Emerging Leaders Summit in Philadelphia were optimistic Soviet
clergy may be allowed to run for legislative offices.
   ``The message is coming through loud and clear that Gorbachev's
initiatives are spilling over and touching upon religious life,''
said Rabbi Gary Zola of Cincinnati, dean of admissions at Hebrew
Union College. ``There is new interest in religious thought and
religious life and the government is not only permitting it but also
is fostering it.''
   The weeklong meeting is sponsored by the Columbus, Ind.-based
American Center for International Leadership and the Soviet Union's
Committee of Youth Organizations.
   On the issue of religious freedom in their own country, the
Soviet delegates said Gorbachev's policy of openness is letting
church leaders speak out without fear of reprisal for the first time
in more than 50 years.
   ``We will have a constructive role in the secular society,
especially in terms of culture and self-determination,'' said Andrei
Rybin, 32, a priest in Moscow's Russian Orthodox Church.
   ``Religion will be more open. The Communist Party remains
atheistic in principle, but it now recognizes the role of the church
and that it had been neglecting it.''
</TEXT>
