<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TreeLighting     12-06 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tree Lighting,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rockefeller Center Tree Lighting Marks Its 56th Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They've been putting a Christmas tree in the
heart of Rockefeller Center for 56 years now, but the thrill remains
for tens of thousands who gather for the annual lighting ceremony.
   ``We came up just to see Christmas in New York _ and this IS
Christmas in New York,'' said Eileen Ross, 52, of Fort Lauderdale,
Fla..
   The 75-foot Norway spruce from Raritan Township, N.J., came back
to life, in a way, when the power was turned on Monday for its
20,000 colored lights and crowning star.
   The ``ooohs and aaahs'' were quickly drowned out by a piped-in
Hallelujah chorus from Handel's ``Messiah.''
   It was, officially, Christmastime in the city. And the city
sidewalks were indeed busy sidewalks _ an estimated 70,000 people
watched the spectacle from surrounding blocked-off streets and
skyscrapers in midtown Manhattan.
   ``Once in a lifetime you've gotta come down here and see it
live,'' said Thelma Calabrese of Huntington, N.Y., who admitted she
also wanted to see Tony Bennett, who hosted the prelighting show
with Maureen McGovern.
   The throng, some of whom had arrived at the plaza four hours
before the ceremony, huddled in a 40-degree chill but showed
generally good spirits.
   Bruce Pelletier, 35, of Old Bridge, N.J. said he and his wife,
Jeanette, were making memories for their sons, Justin, 3, and Brad,
8.
   ``We've seen it on TV, and figured it would be fun for the kids
to see it in real life,'' he said. ``The kids haven't made us regret
it yet.''
</TEXT>
