<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RaileyTrial     12-06 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Railey Trial,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Awards $16 Million To Minister's Critically Injured Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE COCHRAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former minister was ordered to pay $16 million to
relatives of his critically injured wife after another woman
testified about being his longtime lover.
   However, the plaintiff's lawyer deemed the judgment against
former Methodist minister Walker Railey a mostly symbolic victory
because Railey claims he's broke.
   Lucy Papillon, 46, testified at a civil hearing Monday that she
and Railey had discussed marriage during their two-year romance and
that he mentioned divorce.
   But Ms. Papillon, a Dallas psychologist, maintained the plan had
nothing to do with an attack on Peggy Railey.
   Mrs. Railey, 40, lies in a nursing home in what doctors describe
as a vegetative state from which she is not expected to recover. She
was attacked and nearly strangled in her garage April 21, 1987.
   Railey, who was not at Monday's hearing, has maintained he had
nothing to do with the attack and was at the Southern Methodist
University library when it occurred.
   In civil proceedings brought by Mrs. Railey's family, state
District Judge John Whittington ruled last April that Railey
``intentionally, knowingly, maliciously and brutally attempted to
strangle his wife'' and cover up his actions with a ``false alibi.''
   On Monday, Whittington heard testimony to determine the amount of
damages Railey would pay the family.
   ``We were very pleased with the judge's verdict,'' said Bill
Arnold, an attorney for Mrs. Railey's mother, Billie Jo Nicolai.
   He conceded that Railey's financial status likely would preclude
payment of the award, adding:
   ``I don't know how much money he has or how much money he will
have in the future ... but I'm going to do my very best to see that
whatever it is goes to Peggy Railey's medical expenses.''
   Railey, 41, the key figure in a case that was featured this year
on ABC-TV's ``20-20'' program, refused to respond to the lawsuit.
   Police and prosecutors said they have proof that Railey, former
senior pastor of the mainstream First United Methodist Church, lied
about his activities on the night of the attack but that no evidence
links him to the crime.
   Whittington ruled that Railey should pay roughly $8 million for
his wife's lost earnings, medical expenses, mental anguish and
physical suffering and disfigurement, and an equal amount as
punitive damages.
   A physician testified that Mrs. Railey will require an estimated
$4.3 million in medical treatment during the next 30 years. Mrs.
Railey's mother said her insurance policy expires in September 1989.
   ``We do not know what we'll do after that,'' she said.
   Railey reportedly is living in San Francisco and the status of
his affair with Ms. Papillon is unknown, despite rumors that the
romance has cooled.
   Ms. Papillon, daughter of a former Methodist bishop and once a
member of Railey's flock, confirmed reports leaked last year from a
grand jury appearance that she was tied romantically to Railey long
before and after the attack on Mrs. Railey.
   She said their affair began in June 1986 and that it accelerated
in the months before the assault.
   Ms. Papillon said she frequently accompanied Railey on his
travels. In the days immediately before the attack on Mrs. Railey,
Ms. Papillon said, she visited Railey at a Dallas area hotel three
or four times. But she denied that the intensified affair led up to
an attempt to dispose of Railey's wife.
   She indicated Railey's relationship with his wife was functional
at best and said that until their extramarital affair, ``He did not
know what he did not have.''
   Other witnesses portrayed Railey as cold and insensitive, while
describing his wife as vibrant, active, musically talented and a
wonderful mother of two young children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
