<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     12-06 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was stable at higher levels in quiet
European trading this morning. Gold prices were little changed.
   Currency dealers said some market participants withdrew from
trading in frustration over the U.S. currency's limited movement.
The only economic news capable of stirring the market from its
pre-Christmas doldrums is the U.S. October trade report due for
release Dec. 14, they said.
   ``There's very little interest in the dollar,'' said a dealer
with a major West German bank in Frankfurt. ``The market lacks the
incentive to trade.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.01 yen to a closing 121.54. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 121.50 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.7260 West German marks, up from 1.7225
   _1.4455 Swiss francs, up from 1.4420
   _5.8965 French francs, up from 5.8800
   _1.9552 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9425
   _1,275.85 Italian lire, up from 1,273.50
   _1.1875 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1851
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8675, compared with $1.8690
Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $428.50 a troy ounce,
down from $428.75 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $429.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was also $429.00, unchanged from late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 21 cents to close at a bid
$429.73.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.16 a troy ounce,
up from Monday's $6.14.
</TEXT>
