<DOCNO> AP881206-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 0814EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSLawsuit     12-06 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Lawsuit,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Reverses $1.6 Million Award in AIDS Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge, reversing a jury award of $1.6
million to a man who said he got AIDS from a hemophilia drug, said
the jurors may have relied more on their emotions than the facts in
the case.
   U.S. District Judge Orinda Evans on Monday reversed the October
ruling against Miles Laboratories, saying in her 14-page ruling that
AIDS victim Randy L. Jones did not present sufficient evidence of
negligence by the company.
   ``While the court understands fully and shares the jury's great
sympathy for the Jones' plight, it is the court's responsibility to
disallow a verdict which has no basis in law or fact,'' Evans said.
   An attorney for Jones said he would appeal to the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Jones, 35, of Douglasville, contended in a lawsuit that a drug he
took in 1983 made by a division of the Elkhart, Ind.-based Miles was
contaminated with the AIDS virus and caused him to develop the
disease.
   Miles manufactures Koate, a blood-based clotting product, which
Jones took to control a mild case of hemophilia after surgery at
Clayton General Hospital. Two years later, he was diagnosed as
infected with the AIDS virus, and in 1987 he was told by doctors
that he had developed the deadly disease itself.
   Jones contended the drug he took had been contaminated by the
plasma of an unemployed Texas man with AIDS. The man allegedly sold
plasma 40 times to a plasma center in Austin, Texas, which in turn
supplied Miles. The man died of AIDS less than six weeks after his
last plasma sale in September 1983, the suit said.
   Jones alleged that more than 60,000 vials of Koate were
contaminated with the AIDS virus because of the man and accused
Miles of negligence in acquiring and using the tainted plasma.
   Miles, which denied any negligence, argued that it had initiated
a high-risk donor screening program in February 1983, months before
Jones took the drug.
   Evans said there was a possibility that Jones could have gotten
the AIDS virus from other blood factor products he had taken.
   Duncan Barr, the San Francisco attorney who argued the case for
Miles, praised the judge's decision. ``The overwhelming tragedy of
this case obviously affected the jury's decision and (the) judge has
stepped forward to do the correct legal thing,'' he said.
   George H. Connell Jr., Jones' attorney, said he didn't understand
why Evans ruled as she did. ``To me, she's wrong. So you're asking
the wrong person,'' he said.Jones, he said, ``is a pretty strong
man. He thinks he's right and wants to pursue the appeal.''
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, cripples the body's
immune system, leaving a person prey to deadly cancers and other
infections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
