<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan-Evacuations     12-06 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan-Evacuations,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Families of Afghan Officials Reportedly Leaving Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families of Afghan officials have
begun moving out of Kabul because guerrillas are choking the flow of
essential supplies to the capital, Western diplomatic sources said
today.
   The diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
families appeared to be moving to Mazar-i-Sharif, capital of Balkh
province about 40 miles from the Soviet border.
   Various sources have reported major building activity in the
northern city in recent months.
   One diplomatic source said he had reliable information that over
the past four weeks the Afghan state security agency, known as KHAD,
removed the bulk of its files from Kabul.
   ``The Russians are presumably trying to protect all those who
have collaborated with KHAD over the years,'' the source said.
   Moscow agreed in a U.N.-brokered accord in the spring to withdraw
all of its more than 100,000 troops from Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
   Half those forces left by Aug. 15, but the pullout has since
stalled because the Soviets accuse Pakistan and the United States of
violating the pact by continuing their support for the guerrillas.
   The guerrillas have made major gains, especially in eastern
Afghanistan, since Red Army troops began leaving the area. Most
recently they have cut key supply routes to the capital, especially
the road running west from the Pakistan border.
   Western diplomats said bread and meat are in short supply in
Kabul and that there are long lines at fuel stations for diesel and
kerosene.
   Several communist officials have been sent to eastern Nangarhar
province with large amounts of money to try to buy the support of
local Shinwari tribesman, diplomats said.
   ``If successful, the tribesmen would be used to assist in
reopening the road from (the provincial capital of) Jalalabad to the
Pakistani border,'' said one source.
   Most observers predict the Afghan government will fall shortly
after the Soviets have left the country.
   Guerrilla leaders based in Pakistan have shunned numerous appeals
from President Najib to negotiate peace and have rejected all
suggestions of sharing power with the communists.
   The rebels held their first high-level meetings with Soviet
officials last weekend in Saudi Arabia. Western diplomats said it
was a sign Moscow had abandoned hope of keeping its Afghan clients
in power.
   According to statements distributed through the Saudi Press
Agency, Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Yuli Vorontsov and guerrilla
leader Burhanuddin Rabbani agreed to meet again soon in Pakistan.
   The agency said Vorontsov reiterated Moscow's pledge to be out of
Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
