<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HomelessDeath     12-06 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless Death,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fast-Food Patron Ejected, Dies on Street</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A guard at a fast-food outlet said he was
ordered to drag an unconscious, homeless patron onto the street,
where the man later died, but the owner of the restaurant denied the
act was company policy.
   Joseph Eaton died early Saturday on the sidewalk outside the
24-hour fast-food eatery, where he lay for several hours as scores
of people walked by but never offered help. The 38-year-old man came
from a prominent Boston family, but his last years were troubled by
alcohol abuse and the loss of his lover to AIDS.
   ``If somebody was unconscious, and we put him out on the sidewalk
in front of the restaurant and watched him die, then we should be
taken out and shot ourselves,'' said Tom Thompson, one of the owners
of the Carl's Jr. franchises in San Francisco.
   ``That's not (our) policy, to carry people out of the restaurant
_ they have to walk out or we call the police,'' Thompson added.
   But guard George Waters, who was homeless himself before Thompson
offered him a job 3{ years ago, said in an interview Sunday that he
had followed the orders of the restaurant's shift manager, who was
identified only as Dan.
   The shift manager was reported not to be at work Monday and could
not otherwise be reached for comment.
   Waters said it was his responsibility to eject ``street people,
drunk people,'' and that he had done so before at Carl's.
   Waters said he found Eaton slumped over a burger at a restaurant
table, and assumed he had passed out from alcohol.
   Waters said he tried unsuccessfully to wake Eaton, shaking him
``just as hard as you can shake a ... car.''
   Waters said Eaton was breathing when he dragged him out to the
sidewalk just after midnight Friday, and he figured Eaton would
``sober up and get up and move on because it gets kind of chilly
when that wine wears off.''
   Waters said he noticed several times in the next few hours that
Eaton hadn't moved, but believed he was sleeping.
   ``If I'd known he was sick or something like that, I would have
called the paramedics. I would never have put him out.''
   A spokesman for the San Francisco coroner's office said autopsy
results on the cause of death were inconclusive. The preliminary
coroner's report showed apparent fresh needle marks on Eaton's arms,
and records indicate he was arrested in 1982 by San Francisco police
on a drug possession charge.
   It was 5 a.m. when the Rev. Thomas Flowers came upon Eaton,
someone he saw several times a week at his soup kitchen. He said he
couldn't see any breathing.
   ``I put my hand on his back and it was very cold. I felt for a
pulse and there wasn't one,'' he said.
   ``Unfortunately, this kind of thing happens all the time,'' said
Flowers. ``We have a lot of people who die in doorways and other
places.
   ``If (Eaton) had been a middle-class person at a restaurant
anywhere else in town and passed out, they'd have called for an
ambulance, or the cops if he was drunk and passed out. They wouldn't
just throw him out onto the sidewalk and let him lay there and die.''
   Police spokesman Jerry Senkir said the case was not under
investigation by police.
   Eaton's grandfather was Charles Freedom Eaton Jr., chairman
emeritus of Eaton-Vance Group Mutual Fund and founder of Investor's
Bank and Trust Co. of Boston. Joseph Eaton attended prep schools in
Connecticut. Years later he developed a problem with alcohol, said
his brother, Henry, a Boston reporter.
   Joseph Eaton also was gay, and his lover died of AIDS a year ago,
after which Eaton began to drink again after having not touched
alcohol for five years, his brother said.
   He apparently had been living on the streets since Nov. 12, after
his roommate asked him to leave because of his drinking.
</TEXT>
