<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StuartKarl     12-06 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stuart Karl,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Video Entrepreneur Given Probation, Fined, For Illegal Hart
Contributions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stuart Karl, who made a fortune
marketing Jane Fonda workout videotapes, was placed on three years'
probation and fined $60,000 for soliciting illegal campaign
contributions for Gary Hart and others.
   ``To be honest, I'm not sure why I did these things,'' Karl said
Monday in federal court. ``You're attracted to the allure of being
involved (in politics) and people begin to make you feel important.
I just regret doing this.''
   U.S. District Judge Alicemarie Stotler said she imposed a higher
fine than the $20,000 recommended by probation officials to send a
message to others who might follow Karl's example.
   However, she said she didn't make the sentence tougher because of
Karl's cooperation with the government and because this was his
first offense.
   ``This is a defendant who hopefully has had his one and only
brush with the law, although it was a sensational one,'' she said.
   Karl, 36, once considered a star in the home video production
industry, pleaded guilty Aug. 2 to two counts of campaign law
violations.
   The government alleged Karl asked former employees to contribute
up to $1,000 each to various candidates _ the legal limit _ then
reimbursed them in cash. The bulk of the donations went to Hart's
1984 presidential campaign, according to an indictment filed June
10. Hart, then a U.S. senator from Colorado, unsuccessfully
challenged former Vice President Walter F. Mondale for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
   Karl pleaded guilty to one count of making a political
contribution in the name of another person and one count of
conspiracy. Charges involving other candidates were dismissed Monday
as part of Karl's plea agreement.
   Both Karl and his attorney, John Vardaman, claimed the
entrepreneur was a tool of others. Without naming the others,
Vardaman said Karl had been lured into wrongdoing by promises of
access to a presidential candidate and proximity to power.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Bonner has said members of Hart's political
campaign who encouraged the contributions were under investigation.
   The Orange County Register has reported those under investigation
include David Rosen, Hart's 1984 finance director, and Laguna Beach
developer David Stein.
   Vardaman told the judge that Karl never sought any benefit for
himself from his manipulation of political contributions.
   But Assistant U.S. Attorney Nancy Wieben Stock said Karl's
business dealings benefited from his political connections.
   ``He had forged a very successful business with the Jane Fonda
videos that really stemmed from a political connection,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
