<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FortStVrain     12-06 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fort St Vrain,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utility To End Nuclear Operations At Fort St. Vrain Power Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS M. SEARLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public Service Co. of Colorado says it plans to end
nuclear operations by June 30, 1990, at its problem-ridden Fort St.
Vrain power plant, the nation's only helium-cooled nuclear reactor.
   A decision on whether to convert the plant to burn fossil fuel
will be made before the end of 1989, utility spokesman Mark Sieverts
said Monday.
   The utility earlier announced that if it could not find
third-party assistance to continue operating the plant as a nuclear
facility, it would cease nuclear operations in 1991 or 1992. The
plant is licensed by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission to operate
through 2008.
   Sieverts said decommissioning the plant could take up to 55 years.
   Fort St. Vrain employs a helium-cooled reactor found in France
but not elsewhere in the United States. The plant began providing
electricity in 1976.
   The 330-megawatt plant 35 miles northeast of Denver never was
allowed by the NRC to operate for any length of time at 100 percent
of capacity because of problems that caused numerous shutdowns.
   A spate of equipment problems in 1984 led to a 22-month shutdown.
In July 1986, NRC Commissioner James Asselstine told a congressional
subcommittee that Fort St. Vrain was one of the 10 worst-run nuclear
power plants in the nation.
   In 1986, the utility's executives ordered a $101 million
writedown of the facility, and in October 1987 a fire in its turbine
building caused millions of dollars worth of damage.
   The plant has been shut since July for scheduled repairs. It is
expected to resume electricity generation in January.
   The utility said earlier it had three options for Fort St.
Vrain's future: Shut it and remove everything of use; convert it to
a coal- or gas-fired plant; or find a third party to take over the
plant. Sieverts said the company is now left with the first two
options.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
