<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 0917EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BritainEggs     12-06 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain Eggs,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Eggs Maligned In Salmonella Poisoning Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health Secretary Kenneth Clarke has urged shoppers
to ``carry on buying eggs'' but defended a subordinate who said most
of Britain's egg production is affected by salmonella.
   As members of the opposition Labor Party yelled ``sack her,''
Clarke appeared before the House of Commons on Monday to defend
Edwina Currie, the junior health minister.
   ``She was right to stress the concern we feel about eggs,'' said
Clarke, citing 46 outbreaks of salmonella food poisoning, affecting
1,000 people in England and Wales, traced to eggs in October.
   ``We accept there is a health hazard which we are all tackling,''
Clarke said. ``The chief medical officer tells me he had egg
sandwiches for lunch and every healthy individual need not be too
worried.''
   Conservative lawmaker Sir Hal Miller said eggs were on sale in
Birmingham city market northwest of London labeled ``Dutch eggs _
salmonella free.''
   Eggs were taken off the menu Monday for 1,000 patients at
Nottingham's Queens Medical Center. They will not be served until
local health officials decides otherwise, said assistant manager
Rosalind Channon.
   Despite the furor, an egg-swallowing contest was held as
scheduled in Gloucester. Winner John Thornton, 25, swallowed 36
hard-boiled eggs in 15 minutes.
   In Kuala Lumpur, supermarkets removed British egg-based products
from their shelves because of reports of Mrs. Currie's comments in a
television interview Saturday, a store official said today.
   Lee Fook Kiong, manager of Weld Supermarket, said Malaysian
importers were to meet with the British High Commission to discuss
the problem and would restock only after approval from the Malaysian
Health Ministry.
   Britain's Ministry of Agriculture announced producers have agreed
to a voluntary code that includes buying chickens only from licensed
hatcheries, inspecting flocks regularly, discarding cracked eggs and
keeping eggs refrigerated. Most egg-related salmonella infections
come from dirty or cracked eggs.
   Furious egg producers have threatened to sue Mrs. Currie,
according to British Egg Information Service chairman John Coles.
   ``We have got an industry with a retail value of something like
one-and-a-half million pounds ($2.8 billion) and if we lose 25 to 30
percent of that market the losses will be astronomical,'' he said.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. reported only slight dips in egg
sales.
   Sir Donald Acheson, Clarke's chief medical adviser, told the BBC
pregnant women, infants, the elderly and the sick should only eat
eggs that have been cooked solid, killing the bacteria.
   For healthy adults, however, ``I think it is an acceptable risk _
it's a very small one _ for us to continue to enjoy our boiled egg
with a runny inside,'' Acheson said.
   Britons eat 30 million eggs a day produced by 39 million laying
hens on 5,000 commercial farms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
