<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Greece-Palestinian     12-06 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Palestinian,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greece Breaks Extradition Deal With Italy, Deports Suspected
Terrorist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece today reneged on an extradition deal
with Italy and deported a suspected Palestinian terrorist wanted for
alleged involvement in a 1982 grenade attack on a Rome synagogue.
   The attack killed a 2-year-old boy and injured 34 other people.
   Police sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Abdel
Osama Zomar left Greece early today but declined to say where he
went.
   Justice Minister Vassilis Rotis said in a statement that the
27-year-old Palestinian was deported to ``a country of his choice''
after serving two prison sentences.
   In 1984, the Supreme Court agreed to an Italian extradition
request for Zomar, but it was not carried out.
   ``The acts for which extradition is being requested are included
in the struggle for the reacquisition of the independence of his
country,'' Rotis said, apparently referring to the Palestinian
struggle for a independent state.
   The Palestinian is suspected of helping to organize the September
1982 attack on Rome's main synagogue.
   Zomar was sentenced to 20 months on weapons smuggling charges
after his November 1982 arrest at the Greek-Turkish border driving a
car filled with explosives.
   Italian authorities filed an extradition request in 1983 for
Zomar, who is said to be a member of a Palestinian splinter group
headed by terrorist Abu Nidal.
   In March 1985, a few days before Zomar was to be extradited,
Greek authorities said he was suspected of masterminding a grenade
attack against the offices of the Royal Jordanian Airlines in Athens.
   But the authorities did not explain how the Palestinian could
have organized the attack from his jail cell and the charges were
eventually dropped in December 1986.
   But two months earlier, Zomar had been charged with concealing a
weapon in his cell, and was convicted and sentenced in March 1987 to
another 20 months in jail.
   Zomar was one of three suspected Palestinian terrorists jailed in
Greece who are thought to be connected with the Abu Nidal group.
   The others are Mohammed Rashid, 39, a Palestinian wanted by the
United States for the 1982 bombing of a Pan Am jetliner and Omar
Mabrouki, serving a 10-year jail term for trying to shoot the
Jordanian charge d'affaires in 1984.
   The decision to extradite Rashid, arrested in May, has been
delayed.
   On Nov. 15, the Supreme Court indefinitely postponed its
extradition decision because it said it lacked key documents in the
case.
   U.S. officials have said they view Rashid's extradition as a test
of Greece's determination to combat international terrorism.
</TEXT>
