<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Unrest     12-06 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Unrest,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Reported Wounded During General Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAITHAM HAMAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least five Palestinian youths were reported
shot and wounded in clashes with Israeli troops today as a general
strike shut down much of the occupied territories, Arab reports and
hospital officials said.
   The victims included a 12-year-old and a 13-year-old, both shot
in the head, the reports said. Hospital officials also said 24
Palestinians had been beaten or hit with rubber bullets in the West
Bank city of Nablus.
   A military spokeswoman said the army was checking the reports of
bullet wounds. She said she was unaware of injuries with rubber
bullets, which are steel pellets encased in rubber fired to disperse
rioters.
   Businesses were reported closed and public transportation halted
in much of the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Many schools were closed,
and traffic was light as few Palestinianworkers went to their jobs
in Israel.
   A Jewish settler was injured when a stone was thrown at his car
as he drove past the Dheishe refugee camp near Bethlehem, Israel
radio reported. The man was taken to a hospital, it said.
   In the West Bank village of Shuweika near Nablus, a 13-year-old
Palestinian boy was shot in the head during a clash with troops,
Arab reports said. Officials at Jerusalem's Mukassed Hospital said
the youth was in critical condition.
   In Gaza, soldiers opened fire at dozens of youths who marched
through the Khan Yunis refugee camp carrying pictures of PLO
leaders, Arab reports said. A 12-year-old was hit in the head and a
16-year-old in the leg, officials at Nasser Hospital said.
   Two teen-agers also were wounded in a clash in the Deir Balah
refugee camp near Khan Yunis.
   Also in Nablus, dozens of Palestinians were reported treated for
injuries from beatings or the rubber bullets.
   Officials at the Ittihad and St. John's hospitals said many of
the injured were women and quoted some of them as saying soldiers
fired rubber bullets inside houses for no reason.
   In Gaza's Bureij refugee camp, a 15-year-old Palestinian was hit
with 12 rubber bullets during a clash with troops, officials at Ahli
Arab hospital said. The victim, Khaled Al-Amyah, told doctors a
soldier fired at him from close range.
   The army, meanwhile, confirmed a 15-year-old girl was killed by a
plastic bullet Monday after about 50 schoolgirls stoned an army
patrol. A spokeswoman said the commander fired the plastic bullets
to disperse the rioters.
   The victim was identified as Asma Abu Obadah, who died in Shifa
Hospital of a bullet wound in the head.
   She was the 319th Palestinian to be killed since the Palestinian
uprising began last Dec. 8. Eleven Israelis also died in the
violence.
   The Jerusalem Post today published details of the death that
sharply conflicted with the army's version. The paper quoted the
girl's 14-year-old sister, Sahar, as saying an Israeli soldier shot
and killed the girl at close range as she walked home from school.
   Sahar was quoted as saying that she heard screaming, looked back
and saw a bearded soldier with a red beret pointing a gun at her
sister. The girl tried to run but the soldier shot her in the head,
Sahar was quoted as saying.
   Today's strike was called by the PLO-backed United Leadership of
the Uprising to express sympathy with Palestinians held in the
Ketziot prison in the Negev Desert, who reportedly have been on a
hunger strike over conditions.
   About 2,500 Palestinians are believed held there, including 1,500
jailed under emergency regulations without charges or trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
