<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MedicalCenter     12-06 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medical Center,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Billionaire Gives $41 Million to Medical School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A billionaire businessman has pledged $41 million
for cancer and arthritis research at the University of Texas
Southwestern Medical Center.
   Harold C. Simmons' pledge Monday, which officials said represents
the largest single private commitment in the history of Texas higher
education or medical research, will be used in part to establish a
cancer research center.
   ``I've got arthritis and I don't want to get cancer,'' Simmons
said, chuckling as he explained why his money would be used for
research in those areas.
   ``We couldn't possibly, this Christmas season, have a nicer
gift,'' said Gov. Bill Clements, on hand for the pledge.
   Simmons, 57, made his fortune with an investment in a small
Dallas pharmacy and later created a 100-store chain that he sold in
1973 to Jack Eckerd Corp. He has more than 30 business interests
providing him with combined assets of more than $3 billion.
   Dr. Kern Wildenthal, school president, said $24 million of the
gift will be used to establish a comprehensive cancer research
center, including the endowment of four distinguished chairs; $5
million will go for a building to house the cancer center; and $12
million will be used to fund the Harold C. Simmons Arthritis
Research Center for 15 years.
   The pledge will be administered over a 20-year period by the
Harold Simmons Foundation and related organizations.
   Simmons has already given about $7 million to finance the
school's arthritis research center since 1983.
   ``The fact that I've had the experience with them on a smaller
scale and I felt such great regard for their abilities here, that
was a key factor in deciding to go forward.'' Simmons said.
   Simmons said school officials approached him about making the
gift two months ago.
   The medical school received two other large gifts earlier this
year. H. Ross Perot gave $20 million designated to train medical
scientists and augment programs in biomedical research, and the John
D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation donated 29 acres of land
for expansion of the school's 60-acre main campus.
   The 45-year-old institution consists of Southwestern Medical
School, Southwestern Graduate School of Biomedical Sciences and
Southwestern Allied Health Sciences School. About 2,400 students are
enrolled.
</TEXT>
