<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Sun-TimesContract     12-06 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sun-Times Contract,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newsroom Employees Accept Three-Year Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Editorial employees of the Chicago Sun-Times have
voted overwhelmingly to accept a three-year contract, ending a
six-month dispute with the management of the city's second largest
newspaper.
   The settlement, worked out last Friday moments after a strike was
set to begin, was approved in a 132-26 vote Monday, said Tom
Gibbons, chairman of the Sun-Times unit of the Chicago Newspaper
Guild.
   The pact includes a $500 payment on Jan. 1 and raises of 3
percent in each of the following two years. The pay scale for
reporters currently ranges from $625 to $895 a week, based on
experience.
   Gibbons said the next step would be to work on better relations
with management.
   ``This was a long and bitter fight and there's obviously hard
feelings on both sides as a result,'' he said.
   Sun-Times officials said they were pleased by the vote.
   ``Needless to say we're delighted that the guild members have
ratified the contract and we're glad that all of this hard
bargaining is over,'' said Michael Soll, a spokesman for the
newspaper.
   Newsroom employees have been working without a contract since
June 1.
   The Sun-Times has an estimated circulation of 605,000 daily and
614,000 on Sunday.
</TEXT>
