<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hamadi     12-06 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness: Misleading Statements Made After TWA Hostage Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American flight attendant who
was aboard a commandeered TWA jetliner testified today that crew
members later gave misleading accounts of the hijacking.
   ``There were so many different reports that I thought I myself
was at a different hijacking,'' Helen Sheehan, 45, told the court at
the air piracy and murder trial of Mohammed Ali Hamadi.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, has admitted he helped hijack
the Athens-to-Rome jetliner in June 1985. Thirty-nine Americans were
held hostage for 17 days, and U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem was
killed during the ordeal.
   Hamadi has denied killing Stethem, of Waldorf, Md.
   Mrs. Sheehan said she volunteered to testify at Hamadi's trial
because ``I was very concerned that misinformation ... should now be
coming out.''
   She did not give specific details of purported misinformation
during her initial testimony, but criticized a U.S. television movie
based on the hijacking, saying: ``Mr. Hamadi was clearly shown as
being the killer of Mr. Stethem. In my estimation, that was putting
someone on trial without giving them due process.''
   Mrs. Sheehan did not elaborate on the key events of the hijacking
or on Stethem's murder. She said she heard the shot that killed
Stethem, but did not witness the murder.
   Mrs. Sheehan said she disagreed strongly with some statements
made by her fellow crew members after their release. She also
criticized TWA management and FBI agents for the way they handled
events immediately after the hostages were released.
   ``We were returned to New York and we walked into a circus
atmosphere,'' she said.
   The accounts, as well as previous court testimony, accised Hamadi
of beating passengers and threatening to kill them.
   Mrs. Sheehan, however, said Hamadi sometimes acted with kindness
to the hostages.
   ``Mr. Hamadi personally gave a glass of water to a U.S. Navy
diver,'' Mrs. Sheehan said, referring to an earlier witness, Clinton
Suggs.
   ``Mr. Hamadi also served a meal to another American,'' who was
badly beaten by the hijackers, said Mrs. Sheehan, who added she
still works for TWA.
   Under court guidelines to protect witnesses, Sheehan was not
asked to give her current residence.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt Airport in January 1987 after
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
   The West German government last year turned down a U.S. request
for Hamadi's extradition.
   Hamadi's older brother, Abbas Ali Hamadi, is serving a 13-year
prison sentence in West Germany after being convicted of helping to
kidnap two West Germans in Beirut in an effort to win release of his
brother.
   The West German hostages have since been released.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
