<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-Carlucci     12-06 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Carlucci,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Visits Navy Combat Barge, Says U.S. Helped End Gulf War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci
visited a U.S. Navy combat barge in the northern gulf today,
carrying the message that American efforts helped end the Iraq-Iran
war.
   The Pentagon chief flew by helicopter to the barge Hercules,
anchored off Saudi Arabia.
   Carlucci later flew to Riyadh, the Saudi capital, for meetings
with senior defense officials before heading for Kuwait, the last
stop on his five-day gulf tour.
   He is almost certain to be the last top Reagan administration
official to visit the gulf. Carlucci is thanking leaders of Arab
states that supported U.S. efforts to protect shipping and maintain
open sea lanes despite the war.
   However, it was the refusal of Saudi Arabia and Kuwait to allow
U.S. bases on their territory that prompted the Pentagon to lease
the Hercules and another big construction barge as offshore combat
and supply bases.
   Highly secret until a few months ago, the fortified barges
supported U.S. helicopter and gunboat patrols. U.S. officer credit
them with halting Iranian attacks on commercial shipping in the
northern gulf for about eight months.
   The second barge, Wimbrown 7, was taken out of service a month
ago. But U.S. sources say Hercules probably will remain on station
until Washington is convinced the fighting will not erupt again.
   In Bahrain, Carlucci delivered a personal message from President
Reagan to the Emir, Sheik Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa, and talked to
top defense officials.
   Monday night he was guest of honor at a banquet hosted by
Bahrain's Crown Prince, Sheik Hamad bin Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa.
   Earlier today, Carlucci presented awards on the flight deck of
the Navy's gulf flagship USS La Salle and stopped briefly aboard the
missile cruiser USS Josephus Daniels, the missile destroyer Waddell
and the minesweeper Fearless, all in port for the occasion.
   He told La Salle's crew that the Aug. 20 cease-fire ending the
eight-year war between Iraq and Iran vindicated a U.S. intervention
policy originally condemned by critics.
   ``Results speak for themselves,'' said Carlucci. ``Through your
actions, in large measure, you have helped bring an end to one of
the bloodiest wars in history.
   ``We have succeeded in convincing Iran that terrorism on the high
seas does not pay political dividends. We have demonstrated that we
can stand by our friends, and we have demonstrated that we know who
our friends are.''
   He said the largest U.S. naval operation since Vietnam also had
``demonstrated to the world our ability to project power, to show
determination and to defend vital principles including the principle
of freedom of navigation.''
</TEXT>
