<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Swiss,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ambassador Urges Swiss Citizens To Leave Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swiss Ambassador Dino Sciolli today urged
the estimated 200 Swiss nationals in Lebanon to leave the country
following the Nov. 17 abduction of a Swiss Red Cross worker.
   Four Swiss staffers of the International Committee of the Red
Cross left for Geneva today aboard a Middle East Airlines plane,
said a police spokesman.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named under standing regulations,
refused to identify the staffers.
   No group has claimed responsibility for the abduction of Peter
Winkler, the 32-year-old Swiss Red Cross delegate seized by three
gunmen in the southern port of Sidon.
   Since the abduction, eight Swiss Red Cross employess have left
Lebanon, and about 23 remain in the country.
   ``I've advised the Swiss citizens to leave Lebanon,'' Sciolli
told reporters. The Swiss government has banned its citizens from
visiting Lebanon for non-essential reasons.
   Winkler said in a handwritten note released by his kidnappers
Friday that he was abducted in order to be exchanged for a Lebanese
member of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, held in Geneva.
   Lebanese police theorize Winkler was seized to swap him for
Shiite Moslem hijacker Hussein Hariri, who is scheduled to go on
trial in Geneva on Feb. 20 for a 1987 hijacking that ended when he
was overpowered after killing a passenger.
   Hezbollah is the umbrella group for pro-Iranian underground
factions believed to be holding most of the 14 foreign hostages,
including nine Americans, three Britons, an Irishman, an Italian and
a Belgian.
   The hostage held longest is American Terry Anderson, chief Middle
East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March
16, 1985.
