<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Security     12-06 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Security,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules Spy-Agency Employees Not Entitled to Hearings with
Fired</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal employees holding sensitive spy-agency
jobs are not entitled to administrative hearings when fired as
security risks, the Supreme Court ruled unanimously today.
   The justices reversed a lower court's ruling that would have
required such a hearing for a National Security Agency employee who
says he was fired because of his homosexual activities.
   The employee, identified in court documents by the fictitious
name ``John Doe'', works with secret codes at the spy agency.
   Doe told his superiors in 1982 that he had homosexual relations
with several foreigners during vacation travels abroad.
   After a psychiatric evaluation, the agency ordered him fired on
grounds his ``indiscriminate'' sexual activities posed a security
risk since he had access in the job he had held for 16 years to
highly classified information.
   The agency said his homosexuality was not the determining factor
in his firing.
   Doe sued the agency and the secretary of defense, who had upheld
the dismissal. The lawsuit claimed that the firing violated a civil
service law entitling each federal employee to an administrative
hearing before being fired.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here ruled for Doe last year.
   But Justice Byron R. White, writing for the high court today,
said the appeals court was wrong.
   White said Congress never intended to require the National
Security Agency to conduct such hearings for employees considered
security risks.
   White said the spy agency is authorized by law to appoint people
to sensitive intelligence jobs ``without regard to the civil service
laws.''
   ``Although (the authorizing law) does not refer to termination,
the court has held, as a matter of statutory interpretation, that
absent a specific provision to the contrary the power of removal
from office is incident to the power of appointment,'' White said.
   The Supreme Court ruled in a similar case earlier this year that
the Merit Systems Protection Board, which provides job protection to
federal workers, lacks the authority to reinstate an employee fired
for lacking security clearance.
   The court in that ruling upheld the firing of an employee at a
Navy facility.
   The case is Carlucci vs. Doe, 87-751.

</TEXT>
