<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Treason     12-06 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Treason,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Ban Protests Against Treason Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The police commissioner today
banned all protest meetings related to the treason and terrorism
trial of 11 black activists.
   Gen. Hendrik de Witt's order specifically prohibits a meeting
planned tonight at Johannesburg's University of the Witwatersrand.
Several anti-apartheid leaders were to speak, including the Rev.
Allan Boesak.
   Meeting organizers said they might instead hold a church service
for the convicted activists, who include three senior leaders of the
banned United Democratic Front, the country's largest anti-apartheid
group.
   The defendants were found guilty last month, four of treason and
seven of terrorism.
   Trial Judge Kees van Dijkhorst ruled the United Democratic Front
was a revolutionary organization that collaborated with the outlawed
African National Congress to incite anti-government violence in
1984. Boesak, Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu and other United
Democratic Front supporters were named as unindicted co-conspirators.
   The State Department criticized the treason verdicts delivered
last month, saying the defendants were convicted of activities
accepted in any legitimate democracy. South African Foreign Minister
Pik Botha angrily rejected it as unwarranted interference in a
domestic matter.
   Some of the best known opponents of apartheid have been called
since Monday to give evidence for the defendants at hearings to
determine their sentences. Half the orginal 22 defendants, first
brought to trial in 1985, were acquitted.
   Commissioner De Witt said protest meetings like that planned
tonight were used to ``mobilize the masses'' to oppose the
government. He cited van Dijkhorst's judgment that the core of
United Democratic Front leadership functioned as the internal wing
of the ANC.
   The three best known defendants in the trial, all convicted of
treason, are Popo Molefe, 36, who was the Unite Democratic Front's
national secretary; Terror Lekota, 40, its publicity secretary, and
Moses Chikane, 40, Transvaal province branch secretary.
   The maximum penalty is death, but van Dijkhorst is expected to
impose prison terms when the hearings end, possibly this week.
   Among those who testified Monday and today were South Africa's
foremost novelist, Nadine Gordimer, and Frederik van Zyl Slabbert,
former leader of the liberal Progressive Federal Party.
   They and other witnesses have said the government should lift its
ban on the ANC and acknowledge the broad support the group has among
the disenfranchised black majority.
   On Monday, visiting U.S. Sens. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., and David Boren,
D-Okla., attended the hearing. The senators met with President P.W.
Botha in Cape Town today, according to Botha's office. No details
were made public.
   The senators, who have issued no statements about their
fact-finding visit, are believed to be seeking a meeting with ANC
leader Nelson Mandela. Mandela, jailed since 1962, is recuperating
from tuberculosis in a Cape Town clinic and is expected to
transferred soon to some type of private residence where he will
remain under guard. He is serving a life term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
