<2ND_LINE>PM-Jewelry Heist,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunman Robs Neiman-Marcus Store of $560,000 in Jewels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An impatient gunman helped store
clerks scoop more than $560,000 in jewels into his shopping bag, but
hung around long enough for store cameras to record him, police said.
   The robber waited until customers had left the jewelry section of
the fashionable Neiman-Marcus department store before making his
move Sunday afternoon, police spokesman Bob Oakley said Monday.
   He asked a clerk to see one piece of jewelry, then showed her an
automatic pistol ``and told her he wanted it all,'' Oakley said.
   When another clerk appeared from a storeroom, the thief ordered
the clerks to fill a green shopping bag with fine jewelry, police
said.
   ``When they weren't doing it fast enough for him, he reached over
the counter, grabbed a rack and emptied it himself,'' Oakley said.
   The store's videotape security cameras recorded the robbery and
the man as he waited for his chance to be alone at the jewelry
counter, police said.
   Police were to review the tapes.
   After the robbery, the man fled the store and melted into the
holiday shopping crowd at the Newport Center mall.
   Store officials estimated the value of the take at $562,400,
Oakley said. No shots were fired.
   It was the second jewelry heist in as many weeks in the same area
of Orange County, but authorities said there was no apparent link
between the holdup on Sunday and the Nov. 22 robbery by four gunmen
of a Slavick's jewelry store in the South Coast Plaza in Costa Mesa,
adjacent to Newport Beach. An estimated $1 million was taken in that
robbery.
</TEXT>
