<HEAD>Man Sought In Three Slayings Kills Self</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Johnsen is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man wanted in the killings of his wife and
two convenience store clerks in Missouri and Illinois apparently
killed himself with his own gun while being pursued by police,
authorities say.
   Roger Moore, 37, a scrap metal worker from the Chicago suburb of
Berwyn, was found dead in his car late Monday after it struck a
light pole on Interstate 55 southwest of Joliet, said Will County
Sheriff John Johnsen. Joliet is about 40 miles southwest of Chicago.
   Police who were pursuing Moore's car heard a gunshot moments
before the crash and found a .357-caliber Magnum handgun lying in
the car's wreckage, Johnsen said.
   Johnsen said the cause of death appeared to be a single bullet
wound to the right temple, but an autopsy was planned.
   Moore was charged earlier Monday in a warrant with first-degree
murder in the shooting death of his wife, Sandra Moore, 36, said Lt.
Marilyn Dixon of the sheriff's department.
   Mrs. Moore was shot to death Sunday at her parents' home east of
Joliet during a domestic dispute, authorities said. The couple's
four children were in the house at the time, but none was harmed.
   Moore also was being sought for questioning in the killing of
Robert Bull Plume, 23, of Mahomet, Ill., who was shot during an
armed robbery.
   Plume's body was found early Monday behind the counter of the
convenience store where he worked in Mahomet, about 10 miles
northwest of Champaign in east-central Illinois, police said.
   Moore also was a suspect in the fatal shooting of Mary
Schweigert, 30, of rural Ste. Genevieve, Mo., about 60 miles south
of St. Louis, said Richard Lee, chief deputy of the Ste. Genevieve
County Sheriff's Department. Miss Schweigert was killed Monday in an
apparent robbery of a truck stop off Interstate 55, Lee said.
   A customer found her lying on the floor behind the counter of the
convenience store, authorities said. Money had been taken from the
cash register.
