<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest 2ndLd-Writethru   12-06 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0513,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Killed in Azerbaijan, Tension in Both Republics</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with three killed. Pick up 10th
pvs, `Official reports...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clashes between feuding ethnic groups in Azerbaijan
left three people dead and six wounded, including three soldiers
hurt while trying to halt riots, the Foreign Ministry and official
media said today.
   News accounts from the neighboring republic of Armenia reported
deaths there as well but gave no details.
   The renewed unrest came despite a Kremlin effort to restore
order. The effort included directives to party and government
leaders to stop the violence, establishment of a program of aid to
more than 180,000 refugees and threats to fire and prosecute
officials who allow workers to be fired for ethnic reasons.
   The deaths in Azerbaijan raised the toll in the last three weeks
of unrest to at least 31.
   ``Three people were killed, but not as a result of clashes with
law enforcement agencies,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim
Perfiliev told a news briefing.
   ``Six people were wounded, including three servicemen,''
Perfiliev added. He said the deaths took place in Azerbaijan, but
did not say when they occurred or provide other details.
   Earlier, official Baku radio said three soldiers and a medical
student were wounded Monday in clashes with gangs in the Azerbaijani
capital.
   ``Extremists and criminal elements provoked disorders on massive
scales and attempted to commit acts of looting and other illegal
actions'' in three districts of Baku, Baku radio reported in a
dispatch monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp. in London.
   It said soldiers fired warning shots Monday to break up the
gangs, and that ``three servicemen and a student of the Institute of
Medicine were wounded.''
   It did not say how they were hurt.
   Curfews were imposed in parts of Armenia, where ethnic tension
has increased between mixed Armenian and Azerbaijani populations.
   ``In regions of the republic the situation is extraordinarily
dangerous. There have been deaths in the Kalinin, Masis and Gugark
region,'' the newspaper Sotsialisticheskaya Industriya said today.
   An editor at the official Armenian news agency Armenpress, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, confirmed there had been new deaths
in the three regions, all located in northern Armenia. But he did
not know how many people died, or other details.
   Yerevan, the capital of Armenia, was reported to be quiet and a
10 p.m.-6 a.m. curfew that was imposed two weeks ago was reduced by
one hour on each end.
   But Sotsialisticheskaya Industriya said a curfew was imposed on
14 new regions of Armenia beginning at 11 p.m. Monday due to
increased tension in areas with a mixed population.
   Official reports have said more than 180,000 refugees have fled
both sides of the Armenian-Azerbaijani border in the past three
weeks because of the ethnic unrest.
   Armenian radio said Monday that 106,000 Armenians had fled
Azerbaijan, and Sotsialisticheskaya Industriya reported Monday that
the number of refugees from Armenia had reached 80,000.
   The Kremlin threatened Monday to fire and prosecute any Communist
Party officials or economic managers who dismiss workers in Armenia
and Azerbaijan for ethnic reasons.
   The toughly worded directive Monday from the central government's
Council of Ministers and the Communist Party Central Committee was
another step in the Kremlin's effort to impose order on the
republics.
   In February, ethnic rioting broke out in the Azerbaijani city of
Sumgait. At least 32 people, 26 Armenians and six Azerbaijanis, were
killed.
   Most Armenians are Christian, most Azerbaijanis are Moslem.
</TEXT>
