<HEAD>Peruvian Attache Assassinated In Bolivia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS three grafs with background on bombing of Shultz
motorcade, other details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed Peru's naval attache to
Bolivia on a downtown street today, and a previously unknown
extremist group claimed responsibility in a note left near his body,
witnesses said.
   A man and a woman grabbed Capt. Juan Vega Llona one block away
from the Peruvian Embassy, and one of them fired three shots at his
head, witnesses reported. Vega Llona died instantly.
   The man and the woman immediately left the site and have not been
found, the Ministry of the Interior said.
   Police mobilized units throughout La Paz in a effort to capture
the killers.
   A note left with the body signed by the Revolutionary Labor
Movement says ``This is our word against the imperialists that day
to day pretend to smother with blood the just struggles of the
people. In response to these veins full of blood today we make
justice, eliminating a bloody murderer of the people, naval attache
Juan Vega Llona.''
   The police and the U.S. Embassy in La Paz said they have no
knowledge of the Revolutionary Labor Movement.
   On Aug. 8, U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz escaped
injury when a bomb exploded as his motorcade drove into the Bolivian
capital.
   The leftist Simon Bolivar Command claimed responsibility for the
attack, which damaged three cars but caused no injuries. CIA
Director William H. Webster said drug traffickers were behind the
attack.
   Bolivian officials estimate the drug industry brings in $500
million annually, more than the $470 million brought in from all
legal exports.
