<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NursingHomeDeaths     12-06 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nursing Home Deaths,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Search For Motive in Nursing Home Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALKER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities investigating the suspicious
deaths of eight terminally ill nursing home patients focused today
on the means and motives of two former nurse's aides charged with
murder in two of the deaths.
   The arrests of Catherine May Wood and Gwendolyn Gail Graham
followed a two-month investigation into the deaths at the Alpine
Manor Nursing Home in this Grand Rapids suburb.
   Investigators believed at least some of the eight residents were
suffocated in their beds, said Walker Police Chief Walter Sprenger.
   Detectives investigated but were unable to confirm allegations
that the suspects began choosing their victims based on initials of
the victims' names, which they hoped to use to spell the word
``murder,'' Sprenger said.
   Walker police arrested Wood, 26, of Grand Rapids early Monday.
She was arraigned on two counts of open murder before 59th District
Judge Sherwin Venema, who ordered Wood held without bond in the Kent
County Jail pending a Dec. 16 preliminary examination.
   Wood could be sentenced to up to life in prison if convicted.
   Graham, 25, was arrested Sunday night in Tyler, Texas, about 100
miles southeast of Dallas. She was arraigned Monday in 7th District
Court in Tyler on one count of open murder before Judge Bill Coats,
who set bond at $1 million and returned Graham to the Smith County,
Texas, jail.
   Sprenger said he would seek Graham's extradition to Michigan on
the open murder count, which does not specify the degree.
   Wood was charged in the deaths of Marguerite Chambers, 60, and
Edith Cook, 98, and Graham was charged in the death of Cook. The two
patients were among about 40 Alpine Manor residents who died between
January and April 1987, when the eight suspicious deaths occurred,
said Ginny Seyferth, a nursing home spokeswoman.
   All eight deaths originally were attributed to natural causes,
and the bodies of three of the patients were cremated. But the
investigation _ which Sprenger said began after Wood's ex-husband
gave police information about the suspected killings _ led last week
to the exhumations of the bodies of Chambers and Cook.
   Autopsy results on both were inconclusive, but additional bodies
might be exhumed, Sprenger said.
   Sprenger said additional charges could be filed as the six other
suspicious deaths are examined. He said there did not appear to be
other suspects in the case.
   The police chief refused to label the deaths mercy killings but
would not speculate on a motive. ``A lot of this will come out
during the trial. I cannot share evidence that will be detrimental
to the case,'' he said.
   The chief refused to say whether either woman had confessed or
made any comment to authorities.
   Wood worked at Alpine Manor from July 1985 to October 1988, most
recently as a supervisor of nurses aides, Seyferth said. Graham
worked from June 1986 to June 1987 at the 208-patient facility, the
spokeswoman said.
   ``Both had very good reviews,'' Seyferth said. ``In patient
surveys, both were very well-liked by patients.''
   Graham returned to her native Texas and was hired in September
1987 at Mother Frances Hospital in Tyler, assistant hospital vice
president Beverly Mason said. Graham was fired Oct. 19 after
hospital officials learned of the investigation in Michigan, Mason
said.
</TEXT>
