<HEAD>Suspected Kurdish Guerrillas Kill Eight Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Kurdish guerrillas killed an army
lieutenant, two non-commissioned officers and five soldiers in a
daylong shoot-out in southeast Siirt province, Anatolia News Agency
reported today.
   It was not immediately clear if any guerrillas were slain in the
clash that started Monday morning at Judi mountain, the agency said.
   It quoted security officials as saying army units first found the
bodies of a lieutenant, two sergeants and one soldier. Four soldiers
found wounded died later, Anatolia said.
   Kurdish guerrillas belong to the outlawed Kurdish Labor Party, a
Marxist group fighting to set up a separate Kurdish state in
southeast Turkey. Their cause has claimed the lives of 1,500 troops
and rebels since 1984.
