<HEAD>Minister Accused of Murdering Girlfriend Pleads Guilty to
Manslaughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICKSBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister accused of killing his
girlfriend just hours before preaching a Sunday sermon pleaded
guilty to a reduced charge of manslaughter the day before his murder
trial was to begin.
   The Rev. Jonathan Hamlin entered the plea Monday in the July 3
shooting death of 24-year-old Lula Sims under an agreement with
prosecutors. A Jan. 6 sentencing date was set by Circuit Judge Rush
Clements, said Otha Jones, chief deputy in the Warren County
Sheriff's Department.
   Hamlin, a 24-year-old married man with three children, had been
living with Sims, according to investigators.
   Sheriff Paul Barrett has said Hamlin confessed to killing Sims, a
divorced mother of three, and led law enforcement officers to a
shallow grave in rural Jefferson County, about 40 miles southeast of
Vicksburg, where Sims' body was found about a week after she was
reported missing.
   Shocked members of the Zion Traveler Missionary Baptist Church,
one of three congregations led by Hamlin, had praised their pastor
as a ``first-class minister'' even after learning of the murder
charge.
   Hamlin's wife, Martha, did not answer questions in the case.
Under Mississippi law, one spouse cannot be forced to testify
against the other.
   Hamlin remains free until his sentencing on a $100,000 bond he
posted after his arrest, Jones said.
</TEXT>
