<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--CDC-AIDS     12-06 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--CDC-AIDS,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC AIDS Budget Up 25 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national Centers for Disease Control's
spending on AIDS is up 25 percent in the present fiscal year, while
the overall CDC budget is 27 percent higher than last year, the
agency said today.
   The budget approved by Congress for the 1989 fiscal year, which
began Oct. 1, includes $981.9 million for the CDC, said Gayle Lloyd,
a CDC spokeswoman. AIDS education and research programs account for
$382.3 million of the total, she said.
   In the 1988 fiscal year, the CDC budget was $771.8 million,
including $304.9 million for AIDS, Ms. Lloyd said.
   The Atlanta-based CDC compiles information and conducts research
on infectious diseases, including acquired immune deficiency
syndrome. AIDS has killed 44,590 people in the United States since
1981, according to the most recent CDC statistics.
   The CDC's AIDS programs are part of $1.3 billion included in the
federal government's budget to fight the disease this year.
</TEXT>
