<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-BlackLung 1stLd-Writethru a0557 12-06 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Black Lung, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0557,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Saves Mining Industry From Paying Some Benefits to Black Lung
Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 18-24, In other action, with other cases</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today saved the coal mining
industry from paying potentially billions of dollars in additional
benefits to miners with black lung disease.
   But at the same time, the justices ruled that more than 8,000
miners with pending black lung claims may be eligible to receive
hundreds of millions of dollars in benefits.
   By a 5-4 vote, the court said that miners with less than 10 years
of work in the mines are eligible to claim benefits if there is
other evidence they are disabled. That class of workers is estimated
by the government to be around 8,000 to 10,000 miners.
   But the court also overturned a lower court ruling that could
have opened the way for claims by possibly more than 100,000 miners
seeking as much as $13.6 billion in benefits.
   The larger group is barred from receiving benefits because miners
in that class failed to pursue adminisrative remedies or to appeal
to the courts within the prescribed time, the justices ruled.
   Justice Antonin Scalia, writing for the court, said Congress
never intended to exclude from benefit eligibility miners who worked
less than 10 years.
   ``We do not sit to determine what Congress ought to have done
given the evidence before it, but to apply what Congress enacted _
and ... the exclusion of short-term miners from the benefits...finds
no support in the statute,'' Scalia said.
   On the other hand, he continued, nothing in federal law requires
the government to reopen settled claims.
   ``There is not even a colorable basis for the contention that
Congress has imposed a duty to reconsider finally determined
claims,'' he said.
   He was joined by Justices William J. Brennan, Thurgood Marshall,
Harry A. Blackmun and Anthony M. Kennedy.
   The four dissenters agreed that settled cases should not be
reopened. But they also said that miners with less than 10 years of
work are not entitled to the benefits.
   Justice John Paul Stevens wrote the dissenting opinion, joined by
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Byron R. White and
Sandra Day O'Connor.
   The ruling is at least an important partial victory for the
Reagan administration, as well as the coal mining industry.
   The administration challenged a ruling by the 8th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals that Justice Department lawyers said could force
tremendous additional cost on the overburdened fund that pays black
lung benefits.
   The 8th Circuit court _ in the ruling overturned today _ said the
Department of Labor must take a fresh look at claims that were
denied in the late 1970s and early 1980s. The appeals court had
directed the department to use liberalized standards adopted by
Congress in 1977 to determine eligibility for benefits.
   Congress had previously created a special fund to pay off claims
by miners with black lung disease, also known as pneumoconiosis.
   Coal mine operators already owe the government some $3 billion
that has been loaned to the fund from the federal treasury.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Dismissed the appeal of an unwed California father seeking to
restore a parental relationship with his 7-year-old daughter.
   Eight days after hearing arguments in Edward McNamara's case, the
court dismissed the appeal ``for want of a properly presented
federal question.''
   There was no recorded dissent.
   The justices had been expected to use his case to decide whether
unwed fathers who actively seek custody of their children may be
stripped of all parental rights if adoption is deemed in the
children's best interest.
   _ Ruled unanimously that federal employees holding sensitive
spy-agency jobs are not entitled to administrative hearings when
fired as security risks.
   The justices reversed a lower court's ruling that would have
required such a hearing for a National Security Agency employee who
says he was fired because of his homosexual activities.
   The black lung cases are Pittston Coal Group vs. Sebben, 87-821;
Whitfield vs. Sebben, 87-827; and Office of Workers' Compensation
vs. Broyles, 87-1095.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881206-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VotingLawsuit     12-06 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Voting Lawsuit,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Sues New Mexico Over Information Given Indian Voters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government has sued the state
of New Mexico and Sandoval County for allegedly failing to give
Indian voters sufficient voting information in their native
languages.
   The Justice Department lawsuit filed Monday contends the state
and county violated the 1965 Voting Rights Act by failing to provide
interpreters and voter information in the Keres and Navajo tongues.
Keres is a Pueblo Indian language.
   The lawsuit said 8.2 percent of New Mexico's population and 27.3
percent of Sandoval County's population is Indian. The county
encompasses an area from the northern suburbs of Albuquerque toward
northwestern New Mexico.
   ``I hope this litigation shakes the state up,'' said state Rep.
James Roger Madalena of Sandoval, a Jemez Pueblo Indian.
   The Justice Department asked the U.S. District Court to require
state and local election officials to devise a bilingual election
program that will assure Indians equal access to voter registration
and absentee voting, and provide them information on how names are
removed from voting lists.
   The Justice Department also said the defendants failed to
implement procedures to give residents of isolated Navajo and Pueblo
areas the chance to register, to obtain and cast absentee ballots
and to avoid having their registration canceled.
   Other defendants are Secretary of State Rebecca Vigil-Giron,
Sandoval County Clerk Nettie Lucero-Griego and Sandoval County
Commission Chairman Tom Swisstack.
   The Justice Department said it sued after months of discussion
with state and county officials in an effort to get the defendants
to resolve the problems voluntarily.
   Ms. Lucero-Griego said Monday she was not aware the suit had been
filed. Randy Childress, chief assistant New Mexico attorney general,
said he had not seen the lawsuit and would have no comment until it
could be reviewed.
   Ms. Vigil-Giron said the state was warned of a lawsuit as early
as 1987. She said her office tried to get some changes made to state
law, and had hired Indians to address concerns of Navajo, Apache and
Pueblo voters.
   ``We've gone to great lengths to solve some of these problems,''
she said.
   But she said some concepts cannot be translated into all Indian
languages, such as defining a constitutional amendment.
   ``Basically, it's an interpretation problem that we have,'' she
said.
   Madalena said Keres is a spoken language only; it has no
alphabet. But he said Navajo is both spoken and written.
   Swisstack said the county had advertised for interpreters, but
nobody applied. Sandoval County attorney Tom Garde said the county
was targeted because it has the highest percentage of Indian
residents in the state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
