<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-Argentina     12-06 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Argentina,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Denies Connection to Argentine Rebellion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition party has charged
Panamanian leader Manuel Antonio Noriego supported the leader of a
failed rebellion in Argentina, who they say was a Noriega military
adviser.
   Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter on Monday called the accusations
``a fairy tale.''
   The Christian Democratic Party charged that Argentine Col.
Mohamed Ali Seineldin left Panama on a Panamanian military plane,
flew to Uruguay and took a boat to Buenos Aires to take over the
coup.
   However, Ritter said the Argentine left the Panama City airport
on a commercial flight last week.
   The insurrection that began Thursday was the third army mutiny in
20 months.
   Ritter also said the Argentine government will show ``the
falseness'' of versions connecting the Panamanian Defense Forces to
Seineldin's rebellion.
   ``It seems like a fairy tale, although a tragicomic one, that
every important event in Latin America, large or small, is tied to
Gen. Noriega,'' Ritter said.
   The Christian Democratic Party has called for Noriega to step
down. Noriega's rule is also opposed by the United States, where he
has been indicted on drug trafficking charges _ charges he denies.
   On Monday, Acting President Manuel Solis Palma sent a message of
solidarity to Argentine President Raul Alfonsin, the presidential
press office said.
   Seineldin was Argentina's military attache in Panama from 1985 to
1987 and also served as an instructor for the Defense Forces,
official Panamanian sources said.
   Sources at the Argentine Embassy in Panama said that Seineldin
left his post as military attache in 1986 and then was invited to be
a Defense Forces instructor.
   In a press release issued Monday the Christian Democratic Party
said, ``Col. Seineldin was a military adviser to Gen. Noriega for
the past two years, a fact that shows a direct tie between the
Panamanian military chief and the events in Argentina.''
   The party also claimed Seineldin was involved in repressive
actions against anti-government demonstrators in Panama.
   The press release alleged that ties between Noriega and
Seineldin's rebellion indicate ``an attitude of vengeance'' because
Alfonsin favored excluding Panama from the Group of Eight.
   The Panamanian government was excluded from the Group of Eight, a
group of eight Latin American democracies that consult on mutual
problems, on the grounds that it was not a democracy after Noriega
removed Eric DelValle as president in February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
