<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1136EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Switzerland-IranContra     12-06 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Switzerland-Iran Contra,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swiss Lift Banking Secrecy On Israeli Arms Dealer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Switzerland's highest court today
ordered the bank records of an Israeli arms dealer involved in the
Iran-Contra affair turned over to U.S. investigators.
   The Federal Tribunal, the nation's supreme court, lifted strict
banking secrecy rules in rejecting Yakov Nimrodi's appeal of a
decision by Swiss police to grant legal assistance in the
investigation.
   Nimrodi, an Israeli businessman, told the court his account at
the Geneva branch of Credit Suisse Bank was used to channel $1
million in Israeli funds to an account controlled by former White
House aide Oliver North. The Swiss account was code-named
``Trans-Eagle.''
   One of the judges, who cannot be identified under court practice,
said the money apparently came from arms shipments. He did not
elaborate.
   Nimrodi said he was acting on a secret mission for the Israeli
government. The court rejected his arguments that as middleman he
was an uninvolved third party and should be granted immunity.
   In August of last year, the Federal Tribunal ordered secrecy
lifted on accounts at Credit Suisse linked to other figures involved
in U.S. arms sales to Iran and diversion of the funds to Contra
rebels in Nicaragua.
   Those figures were Richard Secord, a retired U.S. Air Force
general; his associate, Iranian-born businessman Albert Hakim; and
Iranian arms dealer Manucher Ghorbanifar.
   Swiss authorities gave the records to U.S. investigators last
November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
