<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador-Attack     12-06 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Attack,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Army Bases; Claim Start Of New Offensive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas attacked two
major army bases in eastern El Salvador, according to rebel and
armed forces reports today.
   The rebels said the attacks on the bases near San Miguel marked
the beginning of a new offensive against the U.S.-backed government.
   The Marxist-led insurgents said on their clandestine Radio
Venceremos they inflicted 28 casualties on government troops Monday
night in an attack on the 3rd brigade headquarters in the provincial
capital of San Miguel. The report did not distinguish between killed
and wounded.
   Lt. Salvador Gonzalez Quezada, spokesman for the 3rd brigade,
said no government soldiers were killed or wounded in the attack. A
civilian woman was wounded during fighting outside the brigade
compound, he said.
   Gonzalez said four guerrilla mortar rounds fell inside the
brigade compound and four other rounds struck the grounds of the
elite Arce battalion, which is attached to the brigade.
   He said the rounds caused no damages and that rebels did not
penetrate the grounds.
   Guerrillas using incendiary bombs destroyed two stores in San
Miguel before retreating, said Gonzalez.
   Early today, rebels attacked the army's 4th detachment in Gotera,
15 miles north of San Miguel. The Armed Forces Press Committee said
one soldier was wounded in what it called guerrilla ``harassment''
of the base.
   The rebel radio broadcast said the attack on Gotera was part of
the eastern offensive. It did not provide a casualty report.
   The radio station YSU reported from Gotera that two civilians
were wounded there. It said they were in ``grave'' condition.
   Radio Venceremos said the attacks marked the beginning of a
regional offensive dubbed ``Fire of the Power and Organization of
the People on its March Toward Victory.''
   San Miguel, with 155,000 people, is El Salvador's third largest
city. It lies 85 miles east of San Salvador, the capital.
   A 9-year-old civil war between the guerrillas and the U.S.-backed
government has killed an estimated 65,000 people, most of them
civilians.
</TEXT>
