<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL Auction,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Real Estate Magnate Peter Thomas Won't Bid on PTL
^With PM-PTL</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCK HILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A real estate magnate who at first made a
bid for PTL's assets thinks the price being asked for what remains
of the evangelical empire is too high, according to his spokesman.
   Bob Ransford, a spokesman for Canadian Peter Thomas, said Monday
that Thomas does not plan to attend the Dec. 12 auction at U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in Columbia.
   Ransford told The Herald newspaper of Rock Hill that the
conditions set by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds made a bid by
Thomas unlikely.
   Thomas, who heads the Vancouver-based Samoth Capital Corp.,
expressed interest in buying PTL's assets in August. At a Nov. 17
bankruptcy hearing, Reynolds rejected Thomas' $70 million cash bid
because it was not high enough and it allowed him to walk away from
the deal for up to 30 days.
   Ransford said Thomas plans to see what happens at the Dec. 12
auction and a Dec. 13 hearing before making any more decisions
concerning the Heritage USA park owned by PTL in Fort Mill.
   Thomas' withdrawal from the auction makes Canadian Stephen
Mernick the leading bidder.
   Coffin would not comment on whether Mernick had altered his $115
million proposal, a proposal Reynolds ruled against because Mernick
would not make an unrefundable deposit or alter terms of a $65
million mortgage payment.
   Meanwhile, Heritage Ministries President Sam Johnson said his
group has raised $1.5 million toward buying Heritage USA and hopes
to have raised $5 million by Friday.
</TEXT>
