<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Rostenkowski     12-06 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rostenkowski,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ways and Means Chairman Suggests Hikes in Gas, Benefits Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee, today suggested raising the gasoline tax
and the amount of Social Security benefits subject to tax as ways to
reduce the federal budget deficit.
   However, the Illinois Democrat emphasized that it would be up to
President-elect George Bush _ not the Democratic-controlled Congress
_ to initiative any tax increase. Rostenkowski was having lunch with
Bush today.
   Rostenkowski, whose committee has jurisdiction over taxes and a
sizable share of federal spending programs, predicted Bush would
have little trouble backing away from his no-tax-increase pledge if
he wants to do so.
   Rostenkowski made his remarks at a breakfast meeting with several
reporters. Aides relayed his statements to other reporters.
   A spokesman said Rostenkowski suggested the federal gasoline tax,
now 9.1 cents a gallon, could be raised by 10 to 15 cents a gallon.
A 15-cent increase would bring in about $15 billion a year, almost
enough by itself to meet the tax-increase requirements of any
deficit-reduction package that Congress and the executive branch
might agree on.
   Raising the amount of Social Security benefits subject to income
tax would require many politicians of both parties to abandon
pledges not to tinker with the retirement system. Present law taxes
up to half of a retiree's benefits if a couple has total income over
$32,000 or a single person's income is over $25,000.
   Senior congressional Democrats have repeatedly rejected arguments
from President Reagan and Bush that the $150-billion-a-year deficit
can be reduced significantly without raising taxes. However,
Democrats have refused to initiate tax increases without the backing
of the administration.
   Rostenkowski contends a continued high deficit will destabilize
the economy to the extend that the nation's standard of living will
suffer.
   At the meeting with reporters, aides said, Rostenkowski also
announced that his committee will hold hearings on the wave of
corporate buyouts. The key issue for the committee will be whether a
full interest deduction should continue to be allowed for money
borrowed to finance buyouts and takeovers.
   Rostenkowski said he has an open mind on the question, aides said.
   The chairman also repeated his distaste for Bush's prposal to
reduce the maximum tax on capital gains. The lion's share of a
capital-gains tax cut would fall to the wealthy, and Rostenkowski
contends such a move would jeopardize the consensus that produced
the 1986 tax overhaul.
   Meanwhile, speaking at a breakfast sponsored by the Gannett Co.
Inc., the incoming chairman of the Senate Budget Committee predicted
that Bush would have to ask for a tax increase before the midway
point of his term.
   ``My view is there will be additional taxes ... within the next
two years,'' said Sen. James R. Sasser, D-Tenn. Bush would again ask
people to ``read my lips,'' he said, but this time he'll be saying,
``Let's get some additional revenue in the till.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
