<2ND_LINE>   NEW ORLEANS (AP) _ Louisiany</2ND_LINE>
<TEXT>
   within five hours of beginning a crackdown on companies with unpaid
fines for safety violations.
   ``We have troopers at all 10 of the truck scales in the state,
and they're checking every truck that rolls in,'' said Lt. Mike
Edmonson, director of the motor safety division. ``We have a list of
220 companies with unpaid penalties ranging from $100 to several
thousand dollars.''
   State police began issuing fines after a year of warnings,
Edmonson said.
   ``We spent the entire year of 1987 issuing warnings. We sent out
over 20,000 warning letters both in state and out of Louisiana.
Since Jan. 1, we've been issuing civil penalties,'' he said.
   Officers will stay at the scales around the clock for an extended
period, Edmonson said.
   ``They may wait us out for eight hours or 12 hours or even 24.
But they want those trucks rolling. It costs them money if they're
not. They won't be able to wait us out forever,'' he said.
   Violations include faulty brakes, bad tires or lights and drivers
who have been behind the wheel too many hours, Edmonson said.
   ``We're not asking them to do anything additional to operate
their trucks than is required under state law. Our main concern is
the growing number cidents in the
state. We're trying to stop trucks in bad shape before they drive
through Louisiana,'' Edmonson said.
   ``For the most part, truckers comply with regulations,'' Edmonson
said. ``It's not a large number of companies violating them, but we
don't want it to get any larger.''
