<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeamstersTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0501 12-06 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0501,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-FBI Agent Jailed For Refusing To Testify At Teamsters Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 7th, `Government attorneys ...,' to
explain role of FBI `handlers.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fired FBI agent has been jailed for refusing
to testify against two Teamsters officials charged with embezzlement
and racketeering.
   Robert S. Friedrick was taken to the downtown Justice Center jail
by federal marshals Monday after he refused to answer prosecutors'
questions about his role as the agency's chief contact for late
Teamsters union President Jackie Presser when Presser served as FBI
informant.
   U.S. District Court Judge George W. White, who had allowed
Friedrick to remain free on $1,000 bond Friday after refusing to
testify under immunity, revoked the bond and asked Friedrick if he
had experienced a change of heart.
   ``My position is the same as Friday,'' said Friedrick, whom the
FBI fired in August 1986.
   Friedrick, who could be jailed up to 18 months for criminal
contempt, conferred briefly with his attorney, William D. Beyer,
before giving him the contents of his pockets, making a phone call
and leaving for jail.
   Beyer has appealed the judge's contempt citation to the 6th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Cincinnati.
   Government attorneys indicated they wanted to call Friedrick to
the stand to prove that Presser's FBI ``handlers'' had never
authorized the union hiring of ``ghost employees'' who were paid for
doing no work.
   The handlers were assigned to keep in contact with Presser and
receive his informant's reports on union activities.
   Friedrick was fired after he was indicted for making false
statements when he told investigators in 1985 that the ghost
employees had been authorized by the FBI. In January 1986, Friedrick
admitted that he had lied about the authorization, but his attorney
has been able to suppress the admission.
   Stephen H. Jigger, a government prosecutor, said Friedrick's
testimony was crucial because Friedrick sometimes was the only one
of three FBI Presser ``handlers'' who attended meetings with Presser
and Anthony Hughes, a co-defendant and recording secretary of
Teamsters Local 507 in Cleveland.
   Hughes and Harold Friedman, a Teamsters international vice
president and president of Local 507, are charged with plotting a
$700,000 scheme to hire ``ghost employees.'' Presser, who remained
secretary-treasurer of his hometown Local 507 while Teamsters
president, was indicted on similar charges but died July 9 before
going on trial.
   Jigger asked the judge to consider delaying the trial to give
Friedrick time behind bars to reconsider his unwillingness to
testify.
   But White delayed such a ruling, and excused the jury until
Wednesday while attorneys argued whether the jury can see some
prosecution evidence.
   As an alternative to Friedrick's testimony on the stand, Jigger
tried but lost a bid to have three sworn statements by Friedrick
admitted as evidence. The judge said the material was untrustworthy
because of Friedrick's earlier conflicting statements.
</TEXT>
