<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AlaskaQuake     12-06 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alaska Quake,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moderate Quake West Of Homer; No One Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALMER, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake shook the Cook Inlet
area early today, but there were no reports of damage or injuries,
the Tsunami Warning Center said.
   Spokesman Alec Medbery said the 7:12 a.m. quake, with a
preliminary magnitude of 5.0 on the Richter scale, was centered
about 50 miles west of Homer and was felt as far north as Anchorage.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus, a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 time
stronger than one of 6.5.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight damage
in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6
severe damage. A 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of
widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable of
tremendous damage.
   The 1964 ``Good Friday'' earthquake in Alaska measured 8.5 on the
Richter scale and was centered in Prince William Sound. It generated
large waves that devastated several coastal communities and killed
114 people as far south as Oregon and Hawaii.
</TEXT>
