<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-NewsConference 1stLd-Writethru a0542 12-06 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-News Conference, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0542,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President To Hold Prime-time Question-and-Answer Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will hold a prime-time news
conference Thursday, the White House announced today, in what will
apparently be his last formal session with reporters.
   The news conference will be held at 8 p.m. EST in the East Room
of the White House, said spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   ``Be nice. It's his last one,'' first lady Nancy Reagan, told
reporters as she accepted the official White House Christmas tree.
   The session will come a day after Reagan's meeting in New York
with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and will likely be
Reagan's last such formal news conference before he leaves office
Jan. 20.
   It will be his fifth meeting with reporters this year and the
first in nearly six months.
   Reagan held news conferences in Washington on Feb. 24 and May 17,
and then held formal question-and-answer sessions with reporters
covering his Moscow summit with Gorbachev on June 1 and at the close
of the seven-nation economic summit in Toronto on June 21.
</TEXT>
