<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1222EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Mrs.Reagan     12-06 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mrs. Reagan,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mrs. Reagan Says She and Mrs. Gorbachev Are Not Fussing and Feuding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Nancy Reagan said today there really
isn't any ``fussing and feuding'' between her and Raisa Gorbachev.
   Mrs. Reagan answered reporters' questions as she received the
White House Christmas tree, an 18-foot balsam fir presented by tree
farmers Irv and Alyce Daggett of Montello, Wis., on behalf of the
National Christmas Tree Association.
   When asked if she was looking forward to seeing Mrs. Gorbachev,
with whom she will attend a lunch in New York on Wednesday while
President Reagan and Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev meet on
Governors Island, she said, ``Yes, I am.''
   ``I hope she has a good time in New York,'' Mrs. Reagan said.
``She has a wonderful time to go there.''
   Did she have any special message for Mrs. Gorbachev?
   ``Merry Christmas,'' she said.
   Asked if there was a feud between her and the Soviet leader's
wife, who have appeared to greet each other frostily at times, Mrs.
Reagan said, ``You all keep saying that there's ... fussing and
feuding, but there really isn't.''
   ``I think too much attention is being paid to it,'' she said.
   As to retirement plans, she said she and her husband are both
writing books and both plan to do some speaking, among other things.
When asked if they would be traveling abroad, she said, ``Probably.''
   Mrs. Reagan said she and the president will celebrate Christmas
at the White House on Dec. 22, the day before they leave for a
Christmas and New Year's vacation in California.
   She said they were giving each other furniture for the house they
will move into in Los Angeles after the president's term ends Jan.
20.
   The first lady said she had mixed feelings about leaving the
White House.
   ``It's sentimental, really,'' she said. ``There are some things I
will be glad to get rid of and some things I won't be glad to get
rid of.''
   She said she would especially miss some friends, the White House
telephone operators and Air Force One, the presidential airplane.
   A reporter asked if she would miss the press.
   ``In a way,'' Mrs. Reagan said. ``I think somewhere out there are
some good friends. Yes, I will.''
   The first lady wore a green cloth coat that she has worn at each
Christmas season that she has been in the White House.
   Noting the numerous events of a nostalgic nature that she and her
husband have been attending, Mrs. Reagan said, ``If there are many
more tributes, I think I will be washed away.''
   When a reporter noted that the president will hold a press
conference Thursday night, she said, ``Be nice. It's his last one.''
</TEXT>
