<HEAD>Top 11 grafs new with Brown announcement; picks up 6th graf pvs,
In
contrast.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veteran party activist Ronald H. Brown entered
the crowded race to become Democratic national chairman today,
saying he was his ``own man'' despite close ties with presidential
hopeful Jesse Jackson.
   Brown declared himself the front-runner in the competition to
succeed outgoing chairman Paul Kirk. His rivals, either announced or
unannounced, include Michigan Chairman Richard Wiener and former
Reps. Jim Jones of Oklahoma; Mike Barnes of Maryland and Jim Stanton
of Ohio.
   Brown said he would campaign as an ``independent, mainstream
progressive Democrat'' who was proud of his work on the past
presidential campaigns of Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, Walter F. Mondale,
Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis.
   Brown said he would ``certainly welcome the support of Jesse
Jackson's supporters,'' but took pains to declare his political
independence.
   ``I'm nobody's candidate. I'm my own man,'' the Washington lawyer
said at a news conference.
   Brown, who was Jackson's top aide at the Democratic National
Convention last summer, said he would be neutral in the race for the
1992 presidential nomination if he became chairman. ``No one will be
given an advantage,'' he said.
   Wiener also arranged to meet with reporters during the day to
discuss his candidacy.
   Among the others, Barnes declared his candidacy in a mailgram
sent to Democrats by his state's governor and senators on Monday.
   Jones, who advocates a three-year television advertising campaign
leading to the 1992 presidential election, said he would make a
formal announcement next week. Stanton has been exploring a race and
said late Monday he was ``looking forward to a candidacy.''
   The Democratic National Committee meets Feb. 9-10 in Washington
to select a new chairman, and Kirk's departure created the potential
for a free-for-all struggle to lead the party that has lost five of
the last six presidential elections.
   ``It makes it much more difficult to arrive at a choice without
some bloodshed,'' Democratic Sen. Lloyd M. Bentsen of Texas said
Monday after Kirk's announcement that he would step aside.
   In contrast to the Democratic maneuverings, Republicans are
expected to ratify without dissent President-elect George Bush's
selection of campaign manager Lee Atwater to be GOP national
chairman.
   Kirk exited at a news conference in Washington where he said the
Democratic Party is better off politically and financially than it
was four years ago. He said he decided when he took the job in 1985
that he would keep it for four years. ``My purpose was to give
something back and to leave something better than existed before I
was given the honor and the opportunity to serve,'' he said.
   Kirk said he will practice law when his term ends in February but
that he will not become a ``political dropout.''
   He said he expects a ``spirited contest'' among the candidates to
replace him, but brushed aside forecasts of a bloodletting. The
Democratic National Committee meets in Washington Feb. 9-10 to make
its selection.
   Bentsen, who was the party's vice presidential candidate this
fall, said Kirk's decision ``makes it much more difficult to arrive
at a choice without some bloodshed. ... Paul was my candidate,''
said the Texas senator, who joined a chorus of party officials
praising Kirk's work.
   Newly elected Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell said, ``I
and many other Democrats across the country will miss Paul's
leadership.''
   Kirk, a 50-year-old Massachusetts native, was urged publicly and
privately by party officials to accept a second four-year term, in
part to head off a battle shortly after the loss of the presidential
campaign.
</TEXT>
