<HEAD>Red Cross To Move Into Former Headquarters Of Secret Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Portuguese branch of the Red Cross
will set up a nursing school in the former headquarters of the
once-feared secret police, a Red Cross spokesman said Tuesday.
   The two buildings in Lisbhad been
occupied by the police force used by Portugal's rightist
dictatorship to supress opposition before a bloodless revolution
restored the country to democracy in 1974.
   The buildings are occupied by a commission investigating the
activities of the secret police, which had detained and tortured
thousands of political prisoners on orders of dictator Antonio
Salazar.
   No date has been set for the transfer of the Red Cross to the
buildings, which are owned by Dom Duarte of Braganza, the head of
Portugal's dethroned royal family.
</TEXT>
