<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Steinberg 1stLd-Writethru a0482 12-06 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0482,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steinberg Attorney Rebuffed In Attempt To Offer Insanity Defense</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with morning testimony, picking
up 4th graf pvs, ``We are ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ex-lover of a man accused of beating to death
their illegally adopted daughter testified today under
cross-examination that she used heroin, marijuana and cocaine and
believed in the powers of hypnosis.
   In an effort to discredit star witness Hedda Nussbaum's
testimony, the attorney for murder defendant Joel Steinberg
questioned Ms. Nussbaum about her drug use and her involvement with
cults and programming.
   Ms. Nussbaum, who lived with Steinberg for 17 years until the
death a year ago of 6-year-old Lisa Steinberg, has directly
implicated him in Lisa's death and painted him as a bullying drug
abuser.
   Under questioning by defense lawyer Ira London, Ms. Nussbaum said
that hypnotic suggestions and programming led her to believe that
she had had ``sex with everybody in the world.''
   Ms. Nussbaum testified that she once believed in the power of
hypnosis and of post-hypnotic buzz words, which when heard could
trigger certain actions.
   ``I was hypnotizing everyone ... and was using them sexually,''
M. Nussbaum said.
   At that point, London asked her if he detected the beginnings of
a smile on her face.
   ``Yes,'' she said. ``I just realized the absurdity of it.''
   Her testimony came one day after state Supreme Court Justice
Harold Rothwax denied a defense motion to change Steinberg's plea to
not guilty by reason of insanity. The Supreme Court is New York's
trial-level court.
   London argued that Ms. Nussbaum's testimony last week convinced
psychiatrists that Steinberg was not criminally responsible for
killing the girl.
   Last week, Ms. Nussbaum testified that Steinberg had admitted
knocking the girl down because she was staring at him.
   ``We are not abandoning our defense that Joel Steinberg is not
guilty of depraved indifference homicide,'' London said.
   He said he wanted his motion granted so the jury could consider a
verdict of innocent by reason of insanity.
   ``We are offering our motion as an alternative,'' London said.
   Assistant District Attorney Peter Casolaro strongly opposed the
plea change, calling it a ``strategic decision'' that should not be
granted.
   Rothwax denied the request, at least temporarily. He noted that
insanity defenses ordinarily must be filed before a trial begins and
within 30 days after a defendant enters a plea to an indictment.
   But the court has discretion to permit an insanity defense at any
time after an indictment. Rothwax said he would give the defense the
opportunity to resubmit it with ``proper papers.''
   Lisa's death in a household with affluent, well-educated adults
shocked many and led to a re-examination of the duty and ability of
neighbors, teachers and social workers to recognize and report
evidence of child abuse.
   In testimony Monday, Ms. Nussbaum said for the first time that
she had seen Steinberg physically abuse Lisa.
   Several weeks before the girl's death, she testified, ``Joel
grabbed Lisa by the arms and shoulders, shook her and threw her down
on the floor.''
   Casolaro asked her if she had ever hit Lisa or physically abused
her.
   ``No,'' Ms. Nussbaum replied.
   On cross-examination, London tried to suggest that Ms. Nussbaum's
opinion of Steinberg had been influenced by her lawyer, Barry
Scheck, and physicians, including psychiatrist Louis Opler.
   ``The only thing that I can recall is that he (Opler) indicated
Joel was a sociopath,'' she said.
   When London asked her if she knew what Opler meant by sociopath,
she chuckled for the first time in her three days on the witness
stand. She said she did not understand at the time that it meant a
violently anti-social personality.
   Under further questioning, she said that when she first talked to
Scheck about testifying against Steinberg, she had, ``for the most
part,'' a positive view of Steinberg.
   She testified that Scheck eventually told her he was trying to
come to some sort of written agreement about testifying against
Steinberg.
   Scheck said afterward that prosecutors had decided before the
agreement that Ms. Nussbaum had nothing to do with Lisa's death and
that the agreement was not in exchange for testimony against
Steinberg.
   London also asked Ms. Nussbaum about her $3.6 million civil suit
against Steinberg.
   ``Were you made aware that a successful criminal prosecution ...
against Joel Steinberg would enhance the value of your lawsuit?''
London asked.
   ``I thought one case would have no influence on the other,'' she
said, adding that Scheck had told her that.
</TEXT>
