<1ST_LINE>u a PM-GaryBusey 1stLd-Writethru a0518 12-06 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gary Busey, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0518,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actor Busey `Out of the Woods,' Condition Upgraded Day After Cycle
Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with condition report today,
picking up 4th graf pvs, `Busey, who ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Gary Busey was responding to simple
commands and showed no signs of brain damage following surgery for
head injuries he suffered when he was thrown from his motorcycle and
smacked headfirst, without a helmet, into a curb.
   Busey, 44, a longtime opponent of laws requiring motorcyclists to
wear helmets, underwent neurosurgery to remove blood clots from his
brain after Sunday's crash in Culver City. His condition, listed as
critical following the operation, was upgraded to serious but
stable, Ron Wise, spokesman for Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, said
today.
   ``He continues to show progress. He will react appropriately to a
question or a statement,'' Wise said, adding that those signs
indicate a lack of brain damage. ``He's not 100 percent; he's still
groggy,'' the spokesman said.
   Busey, who was nominated for an Academy Award for his starring
role in the 1978 movie ``The Buddy Holly Story,'' was visited by his
wife, Judy, and 17-year-old son, Jake.
   The actor was talking, moving his arms and legs and had no
trouble recognizing his wife and family, though ``of course, he's
groggy,'' Wise said.
   The spokesman, who predicted Busey would be in the hospital a
couple of weeks, said the switchboard was inundated with telephone
calls from hundreds of fans and friends. Among the celebrity callers
was Kris Kristofferson.
   The actor was one of a group of celebrity motorcycle enthusiasts
who have campaigned against manadatory helmet laws.
   Backers of state legislation that would require helmets for all
motorcyclists said Monday the crash, though tragic, could counter
some damage done by Busey an some other actors to the cause of
mandatory safety measures.
   ``It saddens me for anybody to be injured or killed, (but) this
is a very sad opportunity to again say, `Why not helmets?''' said
Dr. Elizabeth McLoughlin of the Trauma Foundation at San Francisco
General Hospital.
   A helmet law passed by the state Assembly but vetoed by the
governor last session was re-introduced by Assemblyman Richard Floyd
on Monday, the first day of the new legislative term.
   Police said the one-vehicle accident in suburban Culver City
appeared to be Busey's fault. He picked up the bike from a repair
shop Sunday morning, accelerated up a street and lost control making
a turn about half a block away.
   Big-street bikes are all the rage with male celebrities these
days.
   Busey's manager, Herb Nanas, said Busey rolled out his 1300-cc
Harley Heritage Softail for regular Sunday rides in the California
countryside with a loose-knit group that includes actors Lorenzo
Lamas and Ray Sharkey and assorted professional men.
   ``We're not hot-rodders; none of us are,'' Nanas said. He
explained the attraction of trundling a big bike along a rural
highway, helmetless, at legal speed: ``It's out of the mainstream of
the energy of the city. It's the wind in your hair. It's freedom.''
   Other actors sighted astride the big-bore ``hog'' motorcycles,
which sell for up to $25,000, include Sylvester Stallone, Arnold
Schwarzenegger, and Fred Dryer, the former pro football player who
appears on the ``Hunter'' TV series.
   Busey's film credits include ``Lethal Weapon,'' ``A Star Is
Born,'' ``Carny,'' ``Big Wednesday'' and ``The Bear.'' He recently
completed a movie ``Hider in the House,'' with Mimi Rogers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
