<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Gorbachev     12-06 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet News Coverage of Gorbachev Visit Focuses on U.N. Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet media Tuesday gave prominence to Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's scheduled address to the U.N. General Assembly, rather
than his planned meetings with President Reagan and President-elect
George Bush.
   The official Tass news agency's stories on the 57-year-old
president's departure for New York said only that he would speak to
the world body on Wednesday, and did not mention his sessions the
same day with the U.S. leaders.
   Other Tass stories reported Bush's remarks Monday that he was
eager to move relations with the Soviet Union forward, and comments
by Americans about Gorbachev's trip.
   While Tass issued a separate story praising the decision of U.S.
television networks to cover Gorbachev's arrival in New York live,
state-run Soviet TV didn't show his departure from Moscow until
three hours later.
   In a traditional sendoff, members of the ruling Politburo stood
and waved on the tarmac of Moscow's Vnukovo 2 airport as Gorbachev
and his wife, Raisa, walked to their plane at midday Tuesday. The
sky was overcast and wet snow made the ground slushy, and all the
officials wore fur hats.
   The Soviet media did not report Gorbachev's itinerary, and gave
only a general idea of what he would discuss in New York. Tass said
he would speak with Reagan and Bush about ``arms limitation and
reduction, human rights, a settlement of regional conflicts, and the
development bilateral relations.''
   As for the U.N. speech and meetings with Reagan and Bush, the
clearest hint for Soviets of what their leader might propose was a
reference in the Red Army's newspaper, Krasnaya Zvyezda, on Tuesday
to the possibility the Soviet Union will reduce the size of its
armed forces. The article mentioned Gorbachev's speech and his
meetings with Reagan and Bush, but it did not make clear whether
Gorbachev would announce an armed forces reduction, or provide
details of the step.
   Radio Moscow gave only this tantalizing preview in an
international broadcast: ``It's presumed that during his stay in New
York, Mikhail Gorbachev will advance new initiatives.''
   The evening newspaper Izvestia said in a front-page story Tuesday
that the big question in New York was what proposals or offers
Gorbachev would make.
   ``The answer is given in various forms, but with one thought:
wait just a little longer: on Dec. 7, all will become known,'' the
newspaper said.
   In a dispatch by a diplomatic correspondent distributed after
Gorbchev's departure, Tass said the Soviet leader intends to discuss
the entire range of U.S.-Soviet issues with Reagan and Bush.
   ``The Soviet leadership intends to talk about important
substantive matters concerning real political cooperation between
the two countries on the broadest range of problems, including the
state of affairs and prospects for further headway in the fields of
arms limitation and reduction, human rights, a settlement of
regional conflicts, and the development of bilateral relations,''
the dispatch said.
   Gorbachev's decision to address the United Nations was a sign of
Soviet regard for the world body as an ``indispensable mechanism in
the quest for a peaceful solution to international issues, for
resolution of crisis situations, and for settlement of other global
problems,'' Tass said.
   In several reports Monday, the media emphasized the new style of
Soviet diplomacy and the need for speedy progress on arms control
issues when Bush takes office in January.
   Bush has said he will meet with Gorbachev in his capacity as vice
president, not as president-elect, so as not to overshadow Reagan
before he leaves office next month. But virtually all Soviet reports
about the session referred to Bush only as president-elect, and they
stressed the importance of the meeting in continuing improvements in
relations in the Bush administration.
   Gorbachev was accompanied by Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze, Politburo member Alexander N. Yakovlev and Deputy
Premier Vladimir Kamentsev.
</TEXT>
