<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1349EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Rumsfeld'sRules     12-06 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rumsfeld's Rules,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>An Old Washington Hand's Advice to the Newcomers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Don't play president _ you're not,'' old
Washington hand Donald H. Rumsfeld advises those who will serve at
the side of George Bush. ``The Constitution provides for only one
president.''
   `Assume that most everything you say or do will be on the front
page of The Washington Post the next morning,'' he tells those who
will move into the White House in January.
   ``Learn quickly how to say, `I don't know,''' he adds. ``If you
foul up, tell the president and others fast, and correct it.''
   And this calming piece viewpoint: ``From the inside, the White
House more than occasionally looks as untidy as the inside of a
stomach. Don't let the perspective you have, which is unique, or the
buffeting you receive panic you. It probably looks better and is
likely going smoother than it may seem from where you sit.''
   While holding a half-dozen jobs over two decades in three
Republican administrations, Rumsfeld jotted down his observations on
how to work for and around presidents without getting
presidential-sized egos.
   When he joined former Presidents Carter and Ford, scholars and
other former government officials in writing ``American Agenda,'' a
compendium of policy advice for President-elect Bush, Rumsfeld
pulled out his bits of Washington wisdom. They make the final
chapter of the blue-covered briefing book.
   Many of ``Rumsfeld's rules'' deal with keeping the ego in check
and reflect lessons learned through service directing Richard
Nixon's Office of Economic Opportunity and the wage-price control
program and as Nixon's ambassador to the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization; as Ford's chief of staff and secretary of defense; and
as President Reagan's Middle East envoy.
   Samples:
   _``Don't speak ill of your predecessors (or successor) _ you did
not walk in their shoes.''
   _``Don't begin to believe you are indispensable or infallible,
and don't let the president, or others, think you are _ you're not.''
   _``Don't speak ill of other members of the administration.''
   _``Never say `the White House wants' _ buildings don't `want.'''
   _``One price of proximity to the president is the duty to bring
bad news. You fail him, and yourself, if you are unwilling to do
so.''
   _``Don't forget that the 50 or so invitations you receive a week
are sent not because those people are just dying to see you, but
because of the position you hold. If you don't believe me, ask one
of your predecessors how fast they stop.''
   _``Don't take the job, or stay in it, unless you have an
understanding with the president that you are free to tell him what
you think, on any subject, `with the bark off' _ and the freedom in
practice to do it.''
   _``Work continuously to reduce the number of people who have
White House phones, White House stationery, White House Mess
privileges, and the like. Only those who see the president
frequently, say three or four times a week, should be in a position
to represent themselves as being `White House staff.'''
   _``Simply because a problem is shown to exist, it doesn't
necessarily follow that there is a solution.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
