<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Doctors-Antitrust     12-06 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Doctors-Antitrust,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Juries Probing Possible Collusion by Doctors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal grand juries are delving into
allegations that some doctors are organizing to block new health
delivery systems, agreeing on minimum prices and allocating patients
among themselves, a Justice Department official said Tuesday.
   ``We are prepared to indict and fully to prosecute the
professionals involved if the evidence warrants it,'' Assistant
Attorney General Charles Rule told a meeting of an American Medical
Association group in Dallas.
   Rule, chief of the Justice Department's antitrust division, said
there are ``a few in the profession who it appears may have chosen
to hold themselves above the law.''
   He added that ``naked agreements'' to fix prices, allocate
territories or to boycott competing health-care providers are
violations that can be prosecuted with penalties of up to three
years in prison and $250,000 fines for each violation. Copies of his
speech were released at the Justice Department in Washington.
   Rule declined to give any specifics about the grand jury probes,
but a Justice Department spokesman, Mark Sheehan, said three grand
juries are empaneled, investigating possible price-fixing by some
allergists in Boston, some dentists in Tucson, Ariz., and some
obstetricians in Savannah, Ga.
   It is rare for the government to prosecute organizations of
medical professionals for criminal violations of the antitrust laws.
   The AMA was successfully prosecuted in the 1940s for attempting
to eliminate an employee-sponsored organization that sought to
compete with fee-for-service doctors, Rule noted.
   Rule declined to provide any details about the grand jury probes,
but in his speech text he said ``we have heard about doctors
organizing to block new delivery systems ... by agreeing to withhold
their services or to boycott doctors who do agree to provide their
services.''
   He said this kind of behavior ``is not unlike that prosecuted
nearly 50 years ago in the AMA case.''
   Rule also said there have been allegations that groups of
independent doctors meet secretly to agree to a minimum price or to
other terms that they will insist upon when they discuss
participating in a group.
   Other allegations, he said, concern doctors agreeing to allocate
patients among themselves on the basis of the patient's residence or
some other criteria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
