<HEAD>Jail Inmate Disturbance Quelled After Two Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-hour disturbance involving 150 to 200
inmates of the Essex County jail erupted just after a television
news show was broadcast depicting overcrowding at the jail.
   Sheriff Charles Reardon told reporters ``there was a lot of
destruction'' inside the jail. He said inmates had set small fires,
pulled pipes off walls and knocked off railings. He said there was a
lot of water damage.
   Reardon said overcrowding probably was a factor in the
disturbance. One inmate and one guard suffered minor injuries,
authorities said.
   A man who identified himself as inmate Michael Robitaille
telephoned the Union-News newspaper in Springfield from the jail and
said the violence began shortly after 8 p.m., after a segment on
WCVB-TV's ``Chronicle'' series focused on conditions at the jail.
   ``Chronicle'' producer Mark Mills said the program focused on
overcrowding at the Salem jail as well as other elements of the
troubled criminal justice system, including overcrowded courts in
Boston.
   ``I don't think there was anything that was provocative,'' said
Mills. ``(It was) a look at conditions that they live with every
day.''
