<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LeadersSummit-Homeless     12-06 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Leaders Summit-Homeless,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Visitor Explores American Poverty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One thing had been bothering Soviet
interpreter Inna Novikova since the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Emerging Leaders
Summit began last week.
   She had seen people sleeping on steam grates and living in
cardboard boxes and wanted to know how a country with a reputation
for wealth could allow its poor to live that way.
   ``I think people (Soviet delegates) will have a view of America
that it is just perfect and only rich people live here,'' Ms.
Novikova said as she stopped at the Dignity Shelter. ``The hosting
party is only showing us things in the best possible light.
   ``I want to see the other side of America, not just the best part
of America. I want to see how ordinary people live. Not everything
is perfect in this country.''
   Ms. Novikova and the 169 other Soviet delegates have been staying
in a leading hotel and received VIP treatment at the Army-Navy
football game Saturday and from the Cigna Corp. on Sunday, when the
group visited the Philadelphia insurance company's posh suburban
conference center.
   When Monday's session broke early, Ms. Novikova persuaded U.S.
delegate Arthur Schwartz, who operates the Philadelphia Youth
Leadership Institute, to take her to homeless shelters.
   At Women of Hope, a shelter for chronic mentally ill women and
operated by Sisters of Mercy, Ms. Novikova asked a woman what being
homeless meant.
   ``I just left home because I got tired of the aggravation,'' said
Deneen Ferbee, 30, who works as a mental health aide but who has
been homeless for seven months. ``I stayed in hotels and friends'
houses'' until money ran out.
   As for the other women residents, Ms. Ferbee said, ``The streets
become their homes.''
   For Ms. Novikova, it was difficult to grasp why someone would
choose to live on the street.
   ``I cannot digest this,'' said Ms. Novikova, 30, who lives with
her parents because Moscow apartments are at a premium.
   When someone is living on the street, Ms. Ferbee said, ``You
don't know who to go to, where to go. If you go to a shelter, you
might not feel comfortable there. All shelters are not clean. ...
The food is bad. They don't want to live there. There may be rats
and roaches running around. They say, `Why live here when we can
live on the streets?'
   ``Do you understand?''
   ``Maybe a little better,'' replied Ms. Novikova, who peeked into
bedroms, closets and bathrooms of the neatly kept shelter.
   ``There's not as much wealth (in the Soviet Union), but we don't
have the tremendous poverty either,'' she said.
   Staff member Kathy Murray said some homeless people, including
substance abusers and the mentally ill, will not leave the streets.
Ms. Novikova saw what Ms. Murray was talking about at a subway exit,
where about 40 people were living in rows of cardboard boxes.
   ``I'm starving, hungry, down here with nothing to eat,'' said
Michael Jordan, 30, who said he has been homeless for four years.
   ``How did it happen?'' Ms. Novikova asked.
   ``I'm very upset and hungry and haven't eaten in three, four
days,'' Jordan said. ``You have any money?''
   Thomas Wiggins, 30 and homeless, interjected that ``you'd be
surprised how many Viet vets live down here. The government is
obviously not doing their job.''
   Ms. Novikova asked him why he didn't go to a shelter.
   ``Living in a shelter is like living in a penitentiary,'' Wiggins
replied.
   Jordan remarked to Ms. Novikova, ``If you go back to Russia, I'll
go with you. It's got to be better than here.''
   Replied Wiggins, ``No, man, this is the best country in the
world.''
</TEXT>
