<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1418EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EagleDies     12-06 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eagle Dies,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tainted Water At Refuge Suspected In Bald Eagle's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bald eagle that died two days after it was
discovered ill in the Stillwater National Wildlife Area probably was
poisoned by the increasingly toxic waters at the wetlands,
biologists said.
   The bird's carcass was shipped Tuesday to the National Wildlife
Health Laboratory in Wisconsin so scientists could confirm the cause
of death.
   If the 1{-year-old eagle did die Monday from toxic poisoning, it
would be the first confirmed case at Stillwater of a bald eagle
dying from such a cause, said biologist Steve Thompson.
   About 18,000 birds and 10 million fish have died at the
164,000-acre wildlife refuge 90 miles east of Reno during the past
three years as drought evaporated the waters, allowing toxins to
build up and disease to spread.
   Thompson said scientists suspect the 9-pound bald eagle died of
toxins because of the bird's behavior, including wheezing, and its
low weight.
   ``These could be signs of trace-element toxicity or avian
disease,'' Thompson said. ``Right now, we strongly suspect either
lead or mercury poisoning.''
   Preliminary data from a study of the Newlands Project, a farming
area that drains into Stillwater, shows high levels of selenium,
boron, arsenic and mercury entering the wildlife refuge through
irrigation ditches.
   During the past two years, the wetlands, which serve as a
stopover for migrating ducks, geese and shorebirds on the Pacific
Flyway, have shrunk from 14,000 acres to less than 4,000 acres.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881206-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1425EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     12-06 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Seeks Talks With Likud, Shamir Faces More Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres responded Tuesday
to a plea from the president and again urged his Labor Party to
renew coalition talks with the rival Likud bloc.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, meanwhile, ran into more
difficulties in his efforts to build a coalition led by his
right-wing Likud. Leaders of two religious parties claimed Shamir
had promised both the same Cabinet post, and the two rabbis held a
shouting match on state-run Israel radio.
   Peres' new stand emerged after a breakfast meeting with Israeli
President Chaim Herzog, a veteran Laborite who pleaded Monday for a
Likud-Labor national unity government as he granted Shamir a 21-day
extension to form a government.
   Herzog told Peres such a government was the wish of the majority
of Israelis.
   ``I was very impressed by what the president had to say,'' Peres
said. ``I told him I will propose to convene the (party's) Central
Committee this week. I will recommend to the committee to meet the
request of the president.''
   Labor's 110-member executive bureau, the party's governing body,
last week voted in defiance of Peres and Labor's No. 2, Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin, and vetoed coalition talks with Likud.
   The 1,300-member central committee is empowered to overrule the
bureau's decision, and Labor Secretary-General Uzi Baram said the
committee would meet Thursday.
   ``Even though I feel we should not join a Likud government under
any circumstances ... if there's a demand to convene the commitee we
will do so immediately,'' said Baram, who led younger Labor members
in the vote against Peres and Rabin last week.
   The issue of negotiations with Likud has deeply divided the party
and renewed a long-standing rivalry between Peres and Rabin.
   Shamir, who has said he prefers a broad-based, Likud-led Cabinet,
also is working on composing a narrow government with far-right
parties and the four ultra-Orthodox parties that hold a decisive 18
seats in the 120-member parliament.
   In the Nov. 1 elections, Likud won 40 seats to Labor's 39, with
the remaining seats divided between 13 small factions.
   Shamir's efforts to weld together the religious parties ran into
trouble Tuesday as Rabbi Menachem Porush of Agudat Israel and Rabbi
Avraham Ravitz of the Torah Flag said Likud promised both control
over the Education Ministry's ultra-Orthodox department.
   A debate between the rabbis on Israel radio quickly deteriorated
into a shouting match, with each interrupting the other.
   Despite the difficulties, Shamir was quoted as saying that Likud
would not seek new talks with Labor until Labor reversed its ban on
contacts with Likud.
   ``There will be no chances for a broad-based government as long
as the Labor Party doesn't change its decision of last week,''
Shamir told the Maariv newspaper.
   Peres, in turn, criticized Shamir for making too many concessions
to potential coalition partners, especially the Orthodox parties
that are pushing for far-reaching religious legislation.
   A broad-based government, Peres said, must ``prevent legislation
that will divide the Jewish people.''
   He was referring to the so-called ``Who is a Jew'' law demanded
by the religious parties. Such legislation would give Orthodox
rabbis sole authority over conversions to Judaism.
   The proposal has sparked anger among U.S. Jews, most of whom
belong to the more liberal Reform and Conservative branches of
Judaism and feel such that such legislation would delegitimize their
beliefs.
   Dozens of American Jewish leaders have come to Israel in recent
days to campaign against the proposed law.
   In a meeting Tuesday with representatives of the U.S. Council of
Jewish Federations, Peres said the Labor would not vote for the
``Who Is a Jew'' law even if it joins a government.
   ``The Labor Party would not change its position. It will vote
against the law as one man,'' he said in remarks broadcast on Israel
army radio.
</TEXT>
