<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     12-06 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brite & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MYSTIC, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The success of a movie about three
girlfriends who work in a small-town pizza parlor has turned the
real Mystic Pizza into one of this tourist town's top attractions.
   Mystic Pizza owners Steve and Fofi Zelepos say they have lines
outside their parlor and are even entertaining a franchising
proposal put forward by a group of New York businessmen in the wake
of the opening of the popular movie, ``Mystic Pizza.''
   ``But it means more work,'' Fofi Zelepos said. ``I used to go
home after 2 in the afternoon. Now sometimes I'm here until 11 at
night.''
   Zelepos, 51, said people are coming from New York and New Jersey
to the restaurant his family has run for 14 years in the Connecticut
shoreline town.
   ``Some of them call and say they want to make reservations. What
reservations? This is a pizza place. We don't take reservations. I
say to them to come and take their chances on getting in.''
   The Zelepos family does plan to expand, opening a branch _ Mystic
Pizza the Second _ in nearby North Stonington. It will be operated
by the couple's 23-year-old son, John.
   The motion picture that has altered the lives of the Zelepos
family was the brainchild of Amy Jones, a director and screenwriter
who dropped into the pizza parlor during a vacation in Mystic.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RADCLIFF, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Looking for that unusual stocking stuffer?
How about a time-bomb alarm clock for just $14.95? Or a knife
concealed in a lipstick container.
   Yes, it's Christmas time at the U.S. Cavalry store in Radcliff,
where a Nativity scene in the window shares time with examples of
one of the world's largest varieties of military products available
in one place.
   Company President Randy Acton said the selection has attracted
customers as varied as singer Michael Jackson, who ordered the knife
concealed in a lipstick container, and Panamanian Gen. Manuel
Noriega, who has called on the company for his personal uniforms and
underwear.
   Acton said the company had sales topping $10 million last year.
   Camouflage is, indeed, the design of choice at U.S. Cavalry. It's
on computer covers, duct tape toilet paper, pen-and-pencil sets and
of course, canteens, cots, goggles, gloves, hats, holsters, jackets,
tarpaulins and sleeping bags.
   The company also offers a full line of camouflage clothing for
toddlers.
   The business started in 1973 when Acton, a Vietnam veteran with a
marketing degree from Oklahoma State University, began selling
permanent-press fatigue uniforms out of a Volkswagen van.
   U.S. Cavalry, now with a staff of about 150 people, has a
recently renovated 50,000-square-foot headquarters, warehouse and
shipping facility.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Their initial reaction is ``yech,'' but by
the time the annual Rat Olympics roll around psychology students at
Nebraska Wesleyan University view their rodents with new respect and
affection.
   The Rat Olympics to be held Saturday were established in 1975 to
help psychology students get more out of their laboratory work in
the department's learning and motivation class, according to Kenneth
Keith, associate professor of psychology.
   Students train the white rats in six events _ the five-yard dash,
four-foot tightrope walk, five-yard hurdles, five-foot rope climb,
weightlifting and long jump.
   Diana Stratbucker, 20, a psychology major, was a little leery of
training a rat when the topic first emerged in class, but now she
thinks her rodent named ``Gumby'' can break the Olympic record of
four feet in the long jump.
   ``That's about the only event we have any hope in. Mine was
jumping four feet today so hopefully we'll beat the record,'' she
said.
   Keith said the typical reaction from some students on the first
day is, ``Yech.''
   ``A lot of them feel at first they couldn't possibly handle a
rat. But then, when they get to work with them, they find out they
are mostly like kittens or puppies and they get kind of attached.
Most of them end up keeping their rats as pets.''
</TEXT>
