<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Asia     12-06 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Asia,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze's Visit to Japan to Focus On Trade, Disputed Islands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze's visit
to Japan will bolster the nearly $5 billion bilateral trade and help
resolve the dispute over islands claimed by both nations, the Soviet
ambassador said Tuesday.
   Shevardnadze, the first high-level Soviet official to visit Japan
in nearly a decade, is due in Tokyo Dec. 19-21 for meetings with
Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno and Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita.
   Ambassador Nikolai N. Soloviev said improved ties between the two
countries were important to stability in the Pacific region and that
the diplomatic visit would be ``very important ... because
Japan-Soviet relations are at an important stage.''
   He said bilateral trade has grown to $4.98 billion in 1988, up
from $4.9 billion last year, and the potential for bilateral
economic cooperation was great.
   The talks were expected to touch on Japanese investment in
western Siberia. In November, the Soviet Union signed a preliminary
agreement with Mitsubishi Corp. and other Japanese companies to
build a $8.3 billion chemical complex there.
   Soloviev said the two countries have concluded six joint
ventures, and 40 others were under negotiation.
   A major obstacle to improved Soviet-Japanese ties is a
territorial dispute over the tiny Kuril islands off the northern
Japanese coast, which are claimed by Japan but have been occupied by
the Soviet Union since 1945. Soviet troops invaded the islands at
the end of World War II and later fortified them with 10,000 troops.
   Soloviev told a private group in Tokyo that both nations must
respect each other's claims to the islands.
   ``In history, (Soviet-Japanese) relations have been very
complicated ... but we must now direct our line of vision to the
future,'' he said.
   Japanese diplomats have said they expect no substantial
improvement in bilateral ties until Moscow agrees to negotiate the
return of the islands.
   After Tokyo, Shevardnadze will visit the Philippines and North
Korea, the Kyodo News Service said.
</TEXT>
