<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Panama     12-06 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Tells Deposed President He Supports Return to Democracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan told Panama's deposed
president, Eric Arturo Delvalle, by telephone Tuesday that the
United States still supports a return to democracy in the Central
American republic, the chief White House spokesman said.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan talked for about 10
minutes with Delvalle, who was in Miami visiting Panamanian exiles
there.
   He said Reagan told Delvalle that the U.S. policy in favor of
freedom in Panama ``remains steady.''
   ``We will continue to work with you and the Panamanian people in
favor of a realistic and durable solution,'' Fitzwater quoted Reagan
as saying.
   He said the president told Delvalle that ``we were very pleased
to see the unity that you and your colleagues put together last
month'' _ a reference to a meeting of Panamanian opposition leaders,
who restated their desire for the ouster of military leader Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Fitzwater said the United States still believes that Noriega
``shouessential to the restoration
of democracy'' in Panama.
   Asked why Reagan chose to call Delvalle at this particular time,
the spokesman said it was because the ousted Panamanian president
was easily accessible in Miami. Delvalle had gone into hiding after
he was deposed last Feb. 26 and replaced by Manuel Solis Palma.
   The United States has sought to undermine Noriega's hold on power
with an array of economic sanctions and with diplomatic pressure.
But there has been no indication that Noriega, who is charged with
drug trafficking in federal indictments in Florida, has lost his
grip on power.
</TEXT>
