<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PilotCrackdown     12-06 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pilot Crackdown,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>2 Florida Pilots Convicted in New Air Safety Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Florida pilots were among the first to
be convicted in a federal crackdown on pilots who have failed to
report drunken driving and drug convictions on their license
applications.
   Thirty-nine pilots have been indicted in Florida, Colorado and
Utah, and a probe of 7,850 others is under way, according to the
Federal Aviation Administration.
   ``We're bringing these cases because the U.S. government finds it
essential for air safety,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Gary
Librick, who prosecuted Gary Lee Anderson in Orlando.
   Anderson, 34, was convicted Monday of four counts of making false
statements on medical forms to obtain his pilot's licenses. He faces
up to 20 years in prison and $755,000 in fines.
   Anderson failed to report a 1983 conviction for drunken driving
and possession of marijuana and a 1987 conviction for reckless
driving, then lied to FBI agents who questioned him about the forms
in September, said the prosecutor.
   Also on Monday, William Dixon Gard, 41, a private pilot from
Punta Gorda, was convicted in Fort Myers federal court on two counts
of filing false statements, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Doug
Fraser. Gard faces 10 years in prison and $500,000 in fines.
   A third case is scheduled in Orlando this week.
   Defense attorneys criticized the felony charges.
   ``The heavy hammer of a felony prosecution is entirely
unwarranted,'' said Anderson's lawyer, former federal prosecutor Tom
Turner. ``Prosecution based on this form is a crime itself,'' Turner
told the federal jury in Orlando.
   The defense lawyer argued that the cases should be handled
administratively by the FAA.
   Anderson, a flying instructor and freight pilot, was fired from
his job with Flight Express in Orlando. He was released on bail, and
sentencing was set for March 20. He did not testify and would not
comment.
   ``I think it's a politically motivated witch hunt,'' said
Assistant Public Defender Ray Dvorak about the federal crackdown.
``It seems to me that they got their message across.''
   A computer audit has determined that 711,000 people have licenses
and permits from the Federal Aviation Administration, said FAA
spokesman Ben Lorigo in Washington. He said 10,300 pilots had their
driver's licenses suspended or revoked for drug and alcohol
offenses, and 7,850 failed to report it.
   ``It's essential that the FAA receive complete and truthful
information by those who fly recreationally or privately as
pilots,'' said prosecutor Librick.
</TEXT>
