<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AutoInsurance     12-06 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Insurance,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auto Insurers, Consumer Activists Square Off Over California
Proposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurance industry officials told Congress on
Tuesday that California's recently approved initiative slashing auto
insurance rates was ``no mandate'' and would do nothing to control
soaring premiums.
   But consumer activist Ralph Nader and the author of California's
Proposition 103 testified to the same House panel that the measure
is an important first step toward reining in high insurance costs.
   Nader found a sympathetic audience in Rep. James Florio, D-N.J.,
chairman of the House commerce, consumer protection and
competitiveness subcommittee, which has held four hearings on auto
insurance in recent months.
   ``People are justifiably angry over the rates they pay,'' said
Florio, saying insurance rates have increased 10 percent to 15
percent over the last year, well ahead of overall inflation. ``And
with equal justification they are losing confidence in a system that
allows this to go on.''
   But William B. Snyder, chairman of the GEICO Corp., one of the
nation's largest insurers, said that Proposition 103 was the wrong
way to proceed.
   The measure, approved by California voters on Nov. 8 in a
campaign in which the insurance industry reportedly spent $75
million to defeat it, has so far been blocked in the courts.
   It would immediately reduce auto, home and business premiums by
20 percent. It would also establish a long-term system requiring
companies to increase their discounts for drivers with good safety
records and forcing firms to open their books and justify any future
rate increases.
   ``Fraud and chicanery are rampant,'' Snyder told the lawmakers in
his prepared statement, complaining that ``a large number of crooked
lawyers, medical doctors and chiropractors are available to any one
who wants to subvert'' the insurance system.
   ``The real answer to the problem is not the meaningless and
senseless insurance bashing about which we have heard so much, but
true claim cost control,'' he said.
   John B. Crosby, director of Citizens for No-Fault, an insurance
industry group that waged an unsuccessful battle against Proposition
103, noted that the initiative had been approved by a margin of
about 4.6 million to 4.4 million. Fifty of California's 58 counties
voted against the measure
   ``There is no mandate in the vote for Prop 103,'' said Crosby,
who blamed auto theft, fraud, health care costs and increasing
numbers of lawsuits for growing insurance costs.
   Nader, however, blamed the industry's ``waste, inefficiency and
inattention to loss prevention'' for the increasing premiums.
   ``Insurance customers will be standing up for their rights
against unreasonable insurance rates, arbitrary practices and
lobbying pressure by insurance companies and their corporate allies
to take away victims' rights,'' he said.
   Harvey Rosenfield, chair of Voter Revolt and author of
Proposition 103, accused the insurers of ``raw arrogance, bluster
and bullying tactics'' for trying to block the initiative and
threatening to leave the state if it is implemented.
   ``People want both immediate relief from years of high insurance
rates and long-term, fundamental reform of the insurance system,''
he said.
</TEXT>
