<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Gorbachev     12-06 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Gorbachev,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Unite to Clean Bust of Marx</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Superpower Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karl Marx has been cleaned up and will be his old
self again if President Mikhail S. Gorbachev calls to pay his
respects next week.
   Art students on Tuesday finished chipping away with surgeon's
scalpels to remove the last traces of paint that some anti-Marxist
four years ago oured over the massive bronze bust atop the grave in
north London.
   The students also regilded the famous exhortation, ``Workers of
all lands unite,'' from the 1848 ``Communist Manifesto'' inscribed
on the plinth of Cornish granite.
   ``We are highly privileged to work on Marx,'' said Karin Hignett,
23, climbing down from a makeshift trestle scaffold in Highgate
Cemetery, a vast graveyard that opened in 1839.
   ``But it was a bit monotonous,'' she confided clasping her arms
around herself in the damp and the cold.
   ``Plenty of people envy us. A friend of mine would give his life
to work on Marx's tomb,'' said Simone Boux, 21.
   ``It was black bitumastic paint and very difficult to remove. We
worked two days a week for four weeks to get it off,'' said Nick
Durnham, the students' tutor in stone conservation at the City and
Guilds of London Art School.
   ``There must have been a whole can of the paint poured over Marx
by someone who climbed up there,'' he said. ``The paint dribbled
down and hardened. We tried solvents and then found scraping with
scalpels and washing with cold water was best.''
   Marx was buried in 1883 and Laurence Bradshaw's sculpture of his
head was put up in 1956.
   Since then, anti-Marxist slogans have been painted on the plinth.
The bust was attacked with hammers, daubed with the British national
colors of red, white and blue, and someone even tried to blow it up.
   ``There's been an attempt to cut off the nose and it has four
great cuts made by an ax or chisel, but you can't see them unless
you get up there,'' he said.
   Jean Pateman, who runs a volunteer group caring for the cemetery,
said the cleanup had nothing to do with the scheduled visit of
Gorbachev.
   ``It's a coincidence, but if Mr. Gorbachev comes, Marx is
ready,'' she said.
   ``I think Mr. Gorbachev may very well come _ he didn't when he
was here in 1984,'' Durnham said.
   ``We were working on other memorials when the cemetery manager
asked us to take care of Marx. Then the London communists who look
after the Marx grave asked us to do the regilding and make sure it
was finished by the end of this week,'' he said.
   Marx was born in 1818 in Trier, now in West Germany, and spent
most of his life in exile for his political ideas and leadership of
working men's organizations. He settled in London in 1849, making a
patchy living from journalism and relying on handouts from his
friend and collaborator, Friedrich Engels.
   About 20 people turned up at Marx's funeral to hear Engels say:
``The greatest living thinker has ceased to think.''
   Marx lies between Claudia Jones from Trinidad who died in 1964
and a couple named Griffiths: John, died 1952, and Grace, died 1976.
   ``Anyone can be buried here, the humble and the eminent,'' said
Mrs. Pateman.
   ``We've just buried Anna, the last daughter of (composer) Gustav
Mahler, and (actor) Sir Ralph Richardson is over there.''
</TEXT>
