<1ST_LINE>u a AM-IslandPrepares Bjt   12-06 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Island Prepares, Bjt,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governors Island Prepares for Crowds, Confusion of Gorbachev
Luncheon</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After the crowds, noise and confusion of the
Liberty Weekend extravaganza two years ago, residents of Governors
Island consoled themselves with one thought: Nothing like it would
happen again.
   They were wrong. In the words of Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Paul
Milligan, ``The two major individuals in the world are coming here
to have lunch.''
   On Tuesday, the small island in New York Harbor, which is
administered by the Coast Guard and used for a base, was abustle
with preparations for the arrival Wednesday of Mikhail Gorbachev,
Ronald Reagan and George Bush.
   Even though it sits in the nation's busiest harbor and is just a
brief ferry ride from Manhattan, Governors Island is a quiet town,
barred to the public except for one day in the spring and one in the
fall when visitors are allowed to tour. The speed limit on the
island's roads _ 15 mph _ pretty much typifies the pace of life
enjoyed by its 4,000 residents, all of them connected to the Coast
Guard base.
   The 173-acre island was the epicenter of the four-day Statue of
Liberty relighting celebration in 1986. Some island residents who
survived that experienced an unwanted sense of deja vu this week.
   ``It took people a month to recover from the Statue of Liberty,''
recalled Henry Apicos, principal of the island's elementary school.
``The island was turned into a carnival. People felt imposed upon.''
   This time, restrictions necessitated by the visit ``are going to
create difficulties for some families,'' he said.
   On Sunday night, a four-page notice was handed out to residents
to inform them that for much of Wednesday there would be no driving
on the island and no ferry service. Hours at the Coast Guard mess
hall were changed, school was called off, and the Greg Smith
Singers' performance at St. Cornelius Chapel was canceled.
   Residents of ``high security areas'' have been told to leave
their homes or stay inside all afternoon. They can look out the
windows, but may not open them, ``peek from behind drawn shades'' or
stand on their porches.
   Although areas were set aside for islanders to view the leaders,
they had to arrive early, stay late, and bring identification.
``Mostly they'll see a lot of police and security people,'' Apicos
predicted.
   On Tuesday, ``No Parking Wednesday'' signs popped up around the
island, and parked cars were towed from along the motorcade route.
Outside the base's gymnasium, which was being converted into a giant
press room for 800 reporters, a flatbed truck deposited portable
toilets to replace bathrooms that had been converted into
photographers' darkrooms.
   Six Coast Guard men raked leaves in front of an apartment
building, grousing. ``This is what I went to school for?'' asked one.
   At Liberty Village, a new housing complex built on the spot where
Reagan threw the switch to relight the Statue of Liberty, a woman
and her two children tried to reach their car through a maze of
yellow mesh fence thrown up for security.
   ``This is because Reagan and Gorbachev are coming,'' she
explained. ``We're not usually caged up like this.''
   Coast Guard personnel have been working around the clock to set
up press facilities, install communications lines and construct
bleachers, Milligan said.
   ``Liberty Weekend was bigger than this, but it had a longer
planning period _ we learned about this a week ago,'' he said. ``But
the Coast Guard is good at crisis management, whether it's a
search-and-rescue mission or an oil spill or this.
   ``There's been a little grumbling, but people realize it's only
an inconvenience,'' Milligan said. ``This starts the relationship
between the U.S. and the Soviet Union for the next four years.
   ``We'll all remember this, from the smallest child to the
admiral.''
</TEXT>
