<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     12-06 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says It Intends to End Rationing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday it hopes to end
gasoline rationing April 1 and will end meat rationing as part of an
experiment in one province at the start of 1989.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban made the announcements at a news
conference, in which he stressed the government is committed to
reforming the economy.
   ``The intention and the goal of the government is to lift all
those forms of rationing,'' Urban said.
   Poles receive monthly gasoline ration cards based on the size of
their automobiles that entitle them to buying a limited amount of
fuel at the official price of about 91 cents per gallon.
   Ration coupons entitle motorists to 6.2 gallons of fuel a month
for small cars and 9.4 gallons a month for big cars at the official
price.
   Since June, Poles also have been permitted to buy gas at a
``commercial price'' of about $2.50 per gallon.
   Poles' average monthly wage is about $112.
   The spokesman said that while no final decision has been made,
the government would like to lift gas rationing April 1.
   Urban said the decision was more difficult in the area of meat
rationing, because it was not certain whether the government could
assure adequate supplies of meat to the market if rationing was
lifted. He also said the concept of rationing remained popular among
a majority of Poles because it allows them to buy meat relatively
cheaply.
   Most Polish families are entitled to 5{ pounds of meat per person
per month at controlled official prices. Meat can also be purchased
at private farmers' markets for about four times as much.
   Ham costs about $1.80 a pound at official prices or as much as
$7.27 a pound in private markets.
   As an experiment, Urban said, one of Poland's 49 provinces would
cease to use meat ration cards as of Jan. 1. This would allow
authorities to gauge the effect of lifting the ration-card system,
he said. Urban did not specify the province where the experiment was
to take place.
   After six months, he said, ``only if it is possible will we
propose to society to lift the coupons ... in such a way that it
could gain social approval.''
   Urban also said the government was formulating price increase
plans for 1989 that envisioned the overall inflation rate at about
50 percent. Inflation for 1988 has been estimated at more than 70
percent.
</TEXT>
