<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gorbachev-Security     12-06 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-Security,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Gears Up For Soviet Leader's Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Superpower Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deployment of thousands of police officers and
traffic agents began Tuesday to ensure the safety and smooth passage
of Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev during his three-day visit in the
midst of the holiday crush.
   ``It really is a maximum security operation,'' said Gillian
Martin Sorensen, the city's liaison to the United Nations.
   Tremendous snarls, already dubbed ``Gorbylock,'' were expected
when traffic, swollen with Christmas shoppers, is stopped on some of
New York's busiest streets so that Gorbachev's 45-car motorcade can
wheel through the city.
   Sorensen said the Police Department, which assigned 6,600
officers to the Gorbachev detail, was working closely with the
Secret Service, the State Department and the United Nation's
250-member police force to coordinate protection for Gorbachev.
   On Tuesday afternoon, for Gorbachev's arrival at Kennedy
International Airport on Long Island and travel to the Soviet
Mission in Manhattan, officials ordered closings of the Van Wyck
Expressway and the Grand Central Parkway in Queens, the Triborough
Bridge and FDR Drive in Manhattan to ``make sure they're completely
clear'' for the Soviet motorcade.
   ``It's gridlock for peace so I guess we can bear with it,'' said
Nelson Castillo of the city Department of Transportation.
   ``Given the stature of the Soviet leader, we've got appropriate
security, which happens to be extraordinary in this case,'' said
Port Authority Police Lt. Frank Talbert.
   At least five protest groups will demonstrate outside the United
Nations during Gorbachev's appearance before the General Assembly.
And there is a history of anti-Soviet sentiment in the city,
including the 1984 firebombing of a car at the Soviet residence in
the Bronx, the 1986 tear-gassing of a Moiseyev Dance Company
performance and a 1987 bomb scare when the Bolshoi Ballet opened at
Lincoln Center.
   Since Gorbachev had no scheduled public appearances after his
arrival Tuesday, law enforcement authorities focused more concern on
Wednesday, which one police official called ``the day of infamy''
with extensive traffic disruption.
   Wednesday's itinerary, released by the Police Department, had
Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, visiting the observation deck atop
one of the 110-story World Trade Center towers in lower Manhattan
after the Soviet leader's luncheon meeting with President Reagan and
Vice President Bush.
   Their 45-car motorcade then is to pass the New York Stock
Exchange and go through Wall Street and toward Times Square in mid
Manhattan _ all in the heart of rush hour.
   Among Gorbachev's expected sightseeing stops Thursday were the
Javits Convention Center on the West Side of Manhattan, the
Metropolitan Museum of Art uptown on the East Side, and Central Park.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
