<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Church     12-06 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Church,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Warns of Threat to Vatican Relations Over Archbishop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state governor on Tuesday joined a
dispute between some Roman Catholics and the Vatican over the naming
of Cologne's new archbishop.
   North-Rhine Westfalia Gov. Johannes Rau said there would be
``far-reaching consequences for state-Vatican relations'' if the
Vatican does not work with the state to resolve the dispute. He did
not elaborate.
   The position has been vacant since Cardinal Joseph Hoeffner died
in October 1987.
   Cologne's archbishop is potentially the most influential church
post in the nation. He traditionally has headed the West German
Bishops' Conference.
   The archdiocese is made up of the states of North-Rhine Westfalia
and the Rhineland-Palatinate.
   Rau, a Lutheran, said any attempt by the Vatican to resolve the
problem by making the appointment itself would violate a 1929
agreement giving the states veto power over the appointment.
   ``We insist that (Cologne) church leaders come to us with their
choice,'' Rau said.
   According to terms of the agreement, a panel of high-ranking
Catholics in Cologne is charged with selecting one of three
candidates suggested by the Vatican.
   After the selection, the two states have the right to challenge
the choice if they have serious objections about his political views.
   Church officials in Cologne have been unable to make a decision.
They have refused comment on the selection process, but it is widely
believed the panel is unhappy with the Vatican's choices.
   Pope John Paul II on Tuesday had a private audience with Bishop
Karl Lehmann, president of the West German Bishops Conference. No
details were released.
   One of the pope's prime candidates for the Cologne archbishopric,
Berlin's Cardinal Joachim Meisner, was reported to have given up his
candidacy for the position.
   The Bonn-based Die Welt newspaper on Dec. 1 said Meisner took
himself out of the running after an audience with the pope. The
newspaper said Meisner's candidacy was opposed in Cologne and by the
two state governments.
   On Dec. 1, Rhineland-Palatinate Gov. Bernhard Vogel also told the
Vatican not to violate the agreement.
</TEXT>
