<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaRouche     12-06 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Finance Officer Says Loan Trouble Began In 1985</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former finance officer for Lyndon H.
LaRouche Jr. testified Tuesday that he resigned in mid-1986 after
realizing that millions of dollars in loans to the political
eccentric's organization weren't going to be repaid, but he said he
was unaware of any policy to refuse to honor the debts.
   Wayne Hintz told jurors in LaRouche's mail and tax fraud
conspiracy trial in U.S. District Court that he got no response to a
series of memos to his superiors _ including LaRouche _ warning of
an alarming growth in loan debts.
   Hintz also was disturbed, he said, when regional fund-raisers in
late 1985 began seeking forgiveness of loans.
   ``It was not an easy thing to do,'' he said. ``It had not been
attempted until recently as a systematic approach to reducing
indebtedness.''
   Hintz said he finally quit in June 1986 when his time devoted to
managing the loan debt was reduced and he was forced to take on new
fund-raising efforts, Hintz said.
   ``It became clear to you that the loans weren't going to be
repaid?'' asked defense attorney Michael Reilly.
   ``Yes,'' Hintz replied.
   ``You felt that in good conscience you couldn't continue to be
part of that process?''
   ``Yes.''
   But later, under questioning by other defense attorneys, Hintz
said he did not know of any official policy to deliberately refuse
to pay off the loans as promised, except for short periods of time
when cash revenues were running low.
   ``There was no policy I was aware of not to repay the loans,''
Hintz said.
   Hintz testified as government prosecutors neared the completion
of their case against LaRouche, a perennial minor-party presidential
candidate, in the third week of the trial.
   LaRouche and six associates are charged with mail fraud and
conspiracy for allegedly raising more than $30 million in loans from
supporters with no intention of repaying them.
   In addition, LaRouche is charged with conspiring to defraud the
Internal Revenue Service by having all his personal expenses paid
from funds of various corporations he controls. The government says
LaRouche has filed no federal income tax returns since 1978.
   If convicted of all 13 counts against him, LaRouche faces a
maximum penalty of 65 years in prison and fines totaling $3.25
million. He has denied any wrongdoing.
   Hintz said that at one point in late 1985 loans accounted for
more than half the LaRouche organization's weekly income of $600,000
and the percentage was growing at a rate that alarmed him.
   He said his superiors offered to allocate $80,000 a week to make
payments on some loans primarily involving hardship cases or those
that were targets of litigation. He said his bosses also agreed to
impose a ceiling on new loans.
   But he said these measures weren't nearly enough to ``help us get
out of the woods.'' By the time he resigned, Hintz said, ``I did not
know how it would be possible'' to reduce the indebtedness.
   ``I had run out of ideas, an image of how this might be done,''
he said.
</TEXT>
