<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Bush 7thLd-Writethru a0647 12-06 1068</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0647,1100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds additional Bush comments; edits to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush today named Texas
oilman Robert Mosbacher as secretary of commerce and tapped Carla
Hills, the first woman picked for a high-level post in the incoming
administration, to be special trade representative.
   Bush also named Michael Boskin, a Stanford University professor
of economics and a campaign adviser, to head his Council of Economic
Advisers.
   Turning to foreign policy, Bush also said CIA Director William
Webster would remain in his post, the latest in a string of holdover
appointments from the Reagan administration.
   The president-elect completed an assortment of appointments by
naming Thomas Pickering, the former ambassador to Israel, Nigeria,
El Salvador and Jordan, as his ambassador to the United Nations.
   Bush is not expected to make additional nominations until after
his meeting in New York on Wednesday with President Reagan and
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev.
   Careful to avoid impinging on President Reagan's final weeks in
power, Bush said he would attend the superpower s years than he
would like to admit _ more than three decades. The Texas oilman was
a key fund-raiser in Bush's winning presidential campaign.
   Fielding questions after making his announcements, Bush said
neither Pickering nor Webster would hold Cabinet rank.
   He said both men would be invited to Cabinet meetings as needed,
but said there was no point in having the United Nations ambassador
sitting in for Cabinet discussions of agriculture policy _ something
Bush recalled doing while serving at the U.N. in the 1970s.
   He said Webster would stay in his post for an ``open-ended''
period. There has been frequent speculation that he would stay in
his job for only a few months.
   In tapping Boskin, Bush named a man who helped design the
``flexible freeze'' that serves as the cornerstone of his
deficit-cutting proposals. Boskin also was involved in Bush's
campaign proposal to cut the capital gains tax.
   Mosbacher and Ms. Hills will oversee the nation's trade policy.
The office of U.S. Trade Representative negotiates trade agreements
and the secretary of commerce enforces them and seeks to expand
markets for U.S. goods.
   Mosbacher will take over Commerce from former steel executive C.
William Verity, who has held the job for only a year. Reagan
appointed Verity after the death of Commerce Secretary Malcolm
Baldrige in a horseback riding accident.
   The sources said Mosbacher had been promised the job several
weeks ago, but that the FBI background check on him had taken longer
than expected because of his vast financial holdings.
   Ms. Hills will succeed U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter
to a job that has become more sensitive as the national trade
deficit has risen to record levels. It was $170 billion last year
and is running at an annual rate of $137 billion this year.
   Bush transition sources said that the vice president would not
name a secretary of defense before he and Reagan meet on Wednesday
in New York with Gorbachev. The sources said Tower remains the
favorite for the post.
   New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu, who will be Bush's chief of
staff, said today in Concord, N.H., that the Defense Department's
top echelon may be named in a batch of as many as five appointments.
   The naming of a new secretary of defense and his subordinates
``is being measured in two handfuls,'' he said.
   Earlier today, Bush told Cabinet veteran Elizabeth Dole that he
would like her to participate in the new administration but no job
commitments were made, an aide said.
   Mrs. Dole, a former transportation secretary, and Bush spent
about 45 minutes together over breakfast, according Steve Hart,
Bush's spokesman.
   The vice president ate lunch with Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill.,
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee. Earlier today,
Rostenkowski suggested raising the 9.1-cents-a-gallon federal
gasoline tax as a way of boosting government revenue and easing the
deficit.
   Asked about taxes, Rostenkowski said: ``I don't know. It will be
a decision the president-elect is going to have to make. But I'm in
the tax business.''
   ``I used to be in that business when I served under him (on Ways
and Means),' interjected Bush, a former congressman from Texas. Bush
called their talks confidential, but said both he and Rostenkowski
``want to move this country forward.''
   Meantime, a spokeswoman for Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., said he had
not met with Bush transition people about the possibility of
becoming the secretary of Housing and Urban Development.
   ``He is planning to go into the private sector,'' Mary Burnette
said.
   Kemp, whose own presidential ambitions fell by the wayside early
in the 1988 primary season, has long been rumored as a strong
candidate for the HUD job.
</TEXT>
