<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1918EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Postal     12-06 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Postal,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Post Office Reports Loss for 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service lost $597 million in
the 1988 fiscal year but expects to finish the new year about the
same amount to the good, officials said Tuesday.
   Final figures for fiscal 1988, which ended in October, were
reported at the monthly meeting of the agency's board of governors
and released at headquarters here.
   The loss of $597 million included payments of $510 million to the
federal treasury. The Postal Service has not received a government
subsidy since 1982.
   The postal rate increase that took effect April 4 is expected to
move the agency into the black in the current fiscal year, with
projections calling for it to finish between $550 million and $600
million to the good.
   Overall, the Postal Service has been in the black five times in
the last 10 years.
   When it was made an independent federal agency in the early
1970s, the post office was directed to break even over the long term
and its subsidy was phased out over time.
   Breaking even has required periodic rate increases, currently
scheduled about every three years. The next rate hike is expected to
be filed in 1990, to take effect in 1991.
</TEXT>
