<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OceanSpray     12-06 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ocean Spray,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cranberry Cooperative Wants To Change Plea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ocean Spray Cranberries Inc. will plead guilty to
federal charges that it intentionally dumped hazardous waste into
sewers near its fruit-processing plant in an eastern Massachusetts
town, authorities said Tuesday.
   Ocean Spray, which pleaded innocent to the charges in February,
has asked for a change of plea hearing Dec. 20 before U.S. District
Judge David Nelson.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard E. Welch 3rd said Tuesday the
only possible plea change is to guilty, and ``there will be pleas of
guilty to negligent and willful charges.''
   The cranberry cooperative declined comment on the settlement.
   Ocean Spray could be fined $2.1 million if convicted of the six
felony and 72 misdemeanor charges that allege it discharged
cranberry peelings and acids into municipal sewers and the Nemasket
River from 1983 to 1987 despite being fined by Middleboro, a town 35
miles south of Boston.
   The case was the first in which the government charged a company
with a felony under the Clean Water Act.
   Despite the plea change, the possibility remains that some of the
charges could be dropped, including the felonies, federal
prosecutors said.
   Ocean Spray spokesman John M. Lawlor said the company would have
no further comment on the case until it is settled.
   ``We are working on a solution that is in the best interests of
our company, our grower-owners and the Middleboro community,'' Ocean
Spray President and Chief Executive Officer John S. Llewellyn Jr.
said in a statement Monday.
   ``The negotiations are still in progress so it's premature to
disclose any specifics now,'' he said.
   Middleboro Town Manager John Healey said town officials have been
working with Ocean Spray since the indictment was issued Jan. 28.
   Ocean Spray, a $781 million cooperative, employs 400 people full
time and up to 575 people part time in the town of 20,000.
   On the day it was indicted, Ocean Spray said it never endangered
the public's health or the environment.
   U.S. Environmental Protection Agency officials had described the
indictment as a test case of the Clean Water Act.
   ``It took them about six months to come to the conclusion that
they had done something in fact that was a violation of the Clean
Water Act and they had to do something to correct that,'' Healey
said.
   The indictment charged that Ocean Spray, almost daily since 1976,
dumped up to 200,000 gallons of poorly treated, excessively acidic
waste water into the Nemasket River and Middleboro's sewer system.
   Ocean Spray said Monday it has spent $3.2 million since 1986 to
improve and clean up its operations in Middleboro.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
