<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hamadi     12-06 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness: Hijacker Showed Kindness to Some Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Confessed TWA hijacker Mohammed
Ali Hamadi showed kindness to several hostages during the ordeal, a
flight attendant from the jetliner testified Tuesday.
   Flight attendant Helen Sheehan also said some crew members gave
misleading accounts of the hijacking to the news media after their
release.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, was charged with murder and air
piracy in the June 1985 hijacking. Thirty-nine Americans were held
hostage for 17 days, and U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem was killed
during the ordeal.
   Hamadi has admitted he and an accomplice hijacked the
Athens-to-Rome flight, but has denied killing Stethem, of Waldorf,
Md.
   Mrs. Sheehan said the crew of the hijacked airliner met in
September 1985 to discuss the hijacking and agreed that Hamadi's
accomplice was the leader of the operation and that he, not Hamadi,
might have shot Stethem.
   Hamadi's accomplice, identified in court documents as Hassan
Ezzeddine, is a fugitive. Witnesses at the trial have testified that
he used the name ``Said'' during the hijacking.
   ``The consensus of opinion at the time was that it was Said who
was in charge about the aircraft and while we discussed that nobody
saw who murdered Mr. Stethem, we did feel that Said might have been
the one who could have done it,'' Mrs. Sheehan said, referring to
the meeting of the crew at TWA headquarters in New York.
   Pilot John Testrake testified earlier that he believed Hamadi
pulled the trigger, and co-pilot Philip Maresca testified he saw
Hamadi with a gun seconds after Stethem was shot.
   Mrs. Sheehan, 45, said Hamadi was carrying a gun before Stethem's
murder, but that after she heard a shot, she saw Said with a pistol.
   She also said Hamadi sometimes acted with kindness to the
hostages.
   ``Mr. Hamadi personally gave a glass of water to Clinton Suggs,''
a U.S. Navy diver, said Mrs. Sheehan, who has U.S. and British
citizenship and still works for the airline.
   ``Mr. Hamadi also personally served a meal to Kurt Carlson,''
said Mrs. Sheehan. Carlson was one of the Americans severely beaten
by the hijackers. Mrs. Sheehan said she was aware of the beatings
but did not witness them.
   ``When I saw Mr. Stethem for the first time it was apparent to me
that he had internal injuries because he had trouble breathing and
had difficulty walking,'' she said.
   Mrs. Sheehan said she disagreed strongly with statements made by
other crew members after their release.
   ``There were so many different reports that I thought I myself
was at a different hijacking,'' she told the court, without giving
any specifics.
   She criticized a U.S. television movie based on the hijacking,
saying: ``Mr. Hamadi was clearly shown as being the killer of Mr.
Stethem. In my estimation, that was putting someone on trial without
giving them due process.''
   Mrs. Sheehan also criticized TWA management and FBI agents for
the way they handled events immediately after the hostages were
released.
   ``We were returned to New York and we walked into a circus
atmosphere,'' she said.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt Airport in 1987 after customs
officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
</TEXT>
