<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Cameroon-Panic     12-06 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cameroon-Panic,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Orders Investigation into Deaths of Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YAOUNDE, Cameroon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president has ordered an
investigation into the deaths of 60 students who jumped from windows
or were trampled after hearing rumors their school would collapse,
Radio Cameroon reported Tuesday.
   About 70 students remained hospitalized after the incident
Monday, including several in critical condition, according to
medical sources who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Hospital officials said an estimated 60 children between the ages
of 12 and 15 died at the Institut Jean Monthe, a private school in
the capital.
   The school, which was still under construction, was being built
by the students.
   At the time of the accident, there were an estimated 10,000
students in the five-story building that had only one stairway and a
single exit, the French news agency Agence France-Presse reported.
   Radio Cameroon reported that a fight between a teacher and some
students was misunderstood as warning that the building was about to
crumble.
   As the panic spread, students rushed down the staircase toward
the exit. Some were trampled to death or pushed from the staircase,
others jumped from the windows on the upper floors.
</TEXT>
