<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Scotus-Father     12-06 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Father,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justices Toss Out Unwed-Father Rights Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unwed California father lost the last chance
to legally restore parental ties with his 7-year-old daughter
Tuesday, eight days after his case was argued before the Supreme
Court.
   The nation's highest court dashed Edward McNamara's hopes in a
one-sentence decision: ``The appeal is dismissed for want of a
properly presented federal question.''
   There was no recorded dissent.
   In his appeal, McNamara contended that his parental rights had
been terminaife.
   In arguments before the justices Nov. 28, McNamara's lawyer
contended that California law unfairly discriminated against
McNamara by making it more difficult for him to assert his rights as
a parent.
   San Diego County had defended the state's policy of giving an
unwed mother the primary right to decide whether to surrender a
child for adoption.
   The county also had argued that McNamara waited too long to
assert his rights.
   McNamara's lawyer, James E. Sutherland, said he felt
``disappointment and frustration for my client, who's been told by
all the California courts that he should have won this in the first
place, but because the county got possession of his daughter and
placed her with adoptive parents, it was not in a position to be
corrected.''
   ``It seems to be an issue which has grasped the imagination of a
lot of the public,'' Sutherland said. ``It would have been nice to
get a resolution on the merits of the case.''
   As for McNamara's hopes of visitation, the lawyer said: ``There's
nothing more legally we can do. The trial court recommended that he
be part of Katie's extended family, but there hasn't been any
accommodation. He still hasn't seen her.''
   On the grounds for dismissal, Sutherland said he was surprised
because a state appeals court had refused to consider the federal
constitutional issues, ruling that the California Supreme Court had
addressed those issues and upheld the state law.
</TEXT>
