<2ND_LINE>AM-Africa-Famine,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Says Five African Countries Face Famine</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Sudan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five nations in sub-Saharan Africa face
famine next year, although increased rain and abundant harvests in
1988 have improved the food outlook in most other countries, a U.N.
agency said Tuesday.
   Sudan, Angola, Ethiopia, Malawi and Mozambique face critical food
shortages due to civil strife or large numbers of refugees,
according to the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization.
   The Rome-based agency said the grain harvest in Ethiopia appears
to be good, but that civil war continues to impede distribution of
food to areas affected by last year's severe drought.
   Grain harvests also appear good in northern Sudan, the agency
said, but ``further deaths from starvation appear inevitable'' in
the southern part of the country, where civil strife has interfered
with relief efforts.
   Western agencies estimate 260,000 people have died this year in
southern Sudan because of drought and the refusal of the government
or the rebels to permit distribution of emergency food supplies.
   The International Red Cross and U.N.-sponsored agencies began an
airlift of food to towns in the southern Sudan on Monday. It was the
first time in the 5-year-old war that both sides assured the
agencies that planes carrying aid would not be fired upon.
