<2ND_LINE>AM-Nielsens,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Stretches Streak to 24 in a Row as `Cosby' Resumes Top Spot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a lot of season premieres last week, a
repeat of ``The Cosby Show'' was back at the top of the A.C. Nielsen
Co. rankings after dropping to No. 10 on Thanksgiving.
   NBC won the week as usual, but ABC grabbed second place with help
from a No. 2-rated Barbara Walters special.
   The top-rated prime-time shows of the week were: ``The Cosby
Show,'' NBC; ``The 50th Barbara Walters Special,'' ABC; ``A
Different World,'' NBC; ``Cheers,'' NBC; ``Golden Girls,'' NBC;
``Roseanne,'' ABC; ``60 Minutes,'' CBS; ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC;
``Murder, She Wrote,'' CBS and ``Growing Pains,'' ABC.
   NBC stretched its streak to 24 weeks in a row, winning the week
ending Dec. 4 with an average, prime-time rating of 16.0. ABC was
second with a 13.4. CBS had a 12.2.
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' continued to be the highest-rated new show of
the season. Next-highest were NBC's ``Empty Nest'' and ``Dear
John,'' ranked 12th and 13th respectively.
   NBC also made the top 20 with the two-hour preview movie of ``In
the Heat of the Night'' at 17th.
   ABC resumed its high-rated Wednesday lineup with the season
premieres of ``The Wonder Years,'' at 24th, ``Hooperman'' at 33rd
and ``China Beach'' at 37th.
   NBC's ``Unsolved Mysteries'' and ``Night Court'' fared reasonably
well on Wednesday, but ``Baby Boom'' dropped to 48th in the
rankings, and ``Tattinger's'' was 60th.
   CBS was an also-ran on Wednesday. Its back-to-back Mary Tyler
Moore and Dick Van Dyke comedies were near the bottom of the
rankings. CBS bounced back a little with a theatrical film, Tom
Selleck in ``Runaway,'' at 41st.
   CBS' new ``TV101'' had an inauspicious ratings debut Tuesday at
63rd, just below ABC's new George Segal vehicle on Saturday,
``Murphy's Law.'' CBS did better with Monday night's ``Almost
Grown,'' which ranked 44th.
   The sore spot for NBC is Friday night where CBS' ``Beauty and the
Beast,'' ``Dallas'' and ``Falcon Crest'' still prevail.
   ``NBC Nightly News'' won Thanksgiving week, its first win in over
a year, but dropped back to third in a close race among the news
broadcasts. ``CBS Evening News'' was first with a rating of 11.5 and
a 21 share. ``ABC World News Tonight'' had an 11.3 and 20 share. NBC
had a 10.7 and 20.
   Each rating point represents 904,000 households with television.
The share is a percentage of sets in use.
   The lowest-rated network shows of the week were: ``West 57th''
tied with ``TV 101,'' ``Dirty Dancing,'' ``Knightwatch,'' ``The Van
Dyke Show,'' ``Police Story,'' ``Burning Questions: Defense,''
``Trackdown,'' ``Annie McGuire,'' ``Simon & Simon'' and ``Raising
Miranda.''
