<DOCNO> AP881206-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 2046EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-InmateWorkers     12-06 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Inmate Workers,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmates Building Their Own Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former sheriff, a few businessmen, a
microbiologist and some drug dealers are working side-by-side to
turn five surplus buildings at a naval base into their own prison.
   They are among 70 inmates building a new minimum-security federal
penitentiary at Saufley Field west of this Florida Panhandle city.
   The work is expected to be completed by mid-January but an open
house is scheduled for local officials Friday.
   A bank owner with an architectural degree drew up the renovation
blueprints. Other inmates do everything from plumbing to painting.
   ``I'm a union plumber,'' said Billy Joe Campbell, 38, of North
Miami Beach, serving time for a marijuana conviction. ``I'm doing
everything according to code. I take pride in my work.''
   Campbell is supervising everything from new bathrooms to
sprinkler system repairs.
   His assistant is Steve Reece, 46, a former microbiology teacher
from Greensboro, N.C., who was convicted on a methamphetamine charge.
   Saufley Field is a naval training systems center that provides
logistical and engineering support services for Navy and Marine
training. No aircraft are based there, but its runways are used for
landing and take-off practice by training aircraft from Whiting
Field near Milton.
   The prison renovation began in June when 15 inmates were brought
to Saufley from the federal prison at Eglin Air Force Base, about 40
miles away, and the work force was increased to its present level
last month, said prison Superintendent Mark Henry.
   He was unable to say how much money the government is saving by
having the prisoners renovate existing facilities.
   The renovation work is expected to cost $500,000 with the inmates
being paid 11 cents an hour for their work, he said.
   Eventually, Saufley will house 320 inmates, mainly from the
Panhandle and South Alabama areas, Henry said.
   Most will be prisoners committed for drug-related crimes and many
others will be sent here on tax- or bank-fraud convictions, Henry
said.
   He said the government's 51 prisons are operating at 157 percent
of capacity and the situation may get worse. Tough new sentencing
guidelines and abolition of parole are expected to nearly double the
present 44,000-inmate population by 1993, he said.
   Saufley is one of nine new prisons planned for opening within the
next year and 25 scheduled for the next five years.
   As a minimum-security facility, the new prison will not require
new fences or additional security measures at the base, Henry said.
   Like most minimum-security prisons it appears attractive with
inmates wearing street clothes after their work day is completed and
amenities such as chess boards and a soft ice cream machine.
   ``While this may look nice, it's still prison,'' Henry insisted.
``The people who are here get up when we tell them to, eat when we
tell them to, take the jobs we want them to.''
</TEXT>
