<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 2056EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r r AM-Kenya-Editor     12-06 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Editor,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Editor Critical of Government Arrested, Then Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested the editor of a business
magazine Tuesday but later released him after he apologized for an
article implying Kenya had changed proposed land legislation under
pressure from Britain.
   Attorney General Matthew G. Muli described the article as ``a
complete distortion of the whole truth of the matter and, therefore,
a complete falsehood.''
   It involved a proposed amendment to bar foreigners from buying
agricultural and commercial land in Kenya. This capitalist-leaning
East African nation's annual population growth of about 3.8 percent
_ the world's highest _ has aggravated a land shortage.
   Peter Kareithi, the Financial Review editor-in-chief who was
detained for three hours, said: ``The police referred to a sentence
in the article and said it created the impression Parliament acted
under pressure from Britain.
   ``I agreed such an impression might have been created and
apologized to the government and the vice president,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
   In its Dec. 5 issue, the magazine said the amendment was dropped
because of hostile reaction in the former colonizing power Britain,
where Kenyan Vice President Josephat Karanja was visiting to assure
investors they still were welcome.
   The Review said Karanja was ``told in no uncertain terms that the
just-passed amendment was hostile to would-be investors and was
likely to send those who had their money in the Kenyan economy
packing home.
   ``He (Karanja) must have hastily telephoned Nairobi to say the
bill did not augur well for continued British investments and should
be scrapped,'' the magazine said without attribution.
   Kareithi, 36, said Criminal Investigations Department director
Noah arap Too told him the government was offended by the magazine
saying Karanja might have telephoned Nairobi.
   Muli said the amendment only had been published and not passed
when the anti-foreigner clause was deleted.
   Parliament passed the amendment Oct. 14 without imposing
restrictions on foreigners buying land.
   Kareithi's arrest also followed government criticism of a Nov. 28
editorial alleging government officials were involved in flooding
the Kenyan market with imported gunny sacks while local bag makers
have had to lay off 3,000 workers. The bags are used primarily for
grain and produce.
   Two days after the editorial appeared, a government statement
said the ``insinuations implied in the editorial are malicious, in
bad taste and are calculated to ridicule the government.''
   Earlier this year, the government banned the magazine Beyond,
published by Kenya's National Christian Council of Churches, after
it described Feb. 22 primary parliamentary elections as a ``mockery
of democracy.''
</TEXT>
