<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush-Boskin     12-06 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Boskin,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Adviser Confident of Deficit Cut Without New Taxes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stanford University economist Michael Boskin,
chosen to be President-elect George Bush's chief economic adviser,
said Tuesday that the new administration will be successful in
cutting the budget deficit while upholding Bush's campaign pledge to
avoid new taxes.
   One of the key architects of Bush's ``flexible freeze,'' Boskin
defended the proposal saying that it would produce a balanced budget
through holding the growth of overall spending to the rate of
inflation.
   Boskin, a conservative economist who served as a top Bush
campaign adviser, was named by the president-elect to be chairman of
his Council of Economic Advisers.
   Critics of the flexible freeze have charged it is unworkable and
would force draconian reductions in some areas of domestic spending
to make up for faster growth in such programs as Social Security,
which Bush has vowed to leave untouched.
   In a speech Tuesday before his appointment was announced, Boskin
defended the flexible freeze and predicted that it could balance the
budget somewhere around 1993, depending on how fast the economy
grows in the next few years.
   ``I think you will see the Bush administration take strong action
on the budget deficit quickly after the inauguration and I think it
will be on the spending side of the budget, consistent with the
flexible freeze,'' Boskin told a policy conference sponsored by the
American Enterprise Institute.
   Bush on Tuesday also named Texas oilman Robert Mosbacher as
secretary of commerce and tapped Carla Hills to be trade
representative. Bush earlier announced his choice of Richard Darman
as his budget director and asked Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady
to stay on in the new administration.
   In making the economic appointments, Bush pledged that his
administration would take the lead in proposing a solution to
Congress to reduce the budget deficit, which climbed to $155.1
billion in the fiscal year that ended Sept. 30.
   ``I do feel the urgency of getting something moving on the
deficit front and I will do my level best early on to take the
offense,'' Bush said. He said he would not simply leave the problem
up to Congress to solve.
   ``I am not going to do that. I am going to lead,'' Bush said. But
he refused to be specific on how detailed a budget proposal he
planned to submit once he takes office, saying his advisers were
still working on those details.
   Boskin, in his speech, responded to critics who charge that the
flexible freeze will not produce a balanced budget because of new
spending demands on government and rapid growth in such politically
sensitive programs as Social Security and Medicare.
   ``It's certainly valid technical economics if your goal is to get
to a balanced budget in the 1993 period, give or take a year,''
Boskin said.
   ``I can assure you that people who are very careful with numbers,
myself included, have gone over this and it is eminently do-able,''
he said. ``So the accusations that this doesn't add up are kind of
silly and not based on economic reality.''
   Boskin said Bush would quickly appoint budget negotiators to work
with Congress on a spending compromise.
   ``I know (Bush) takes the deficit very seriously and I expect him
to deal forcefully with it early on,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
