<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DemocraticChairman     12-06 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democratic Chairman,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ronald Brown Declares Candidacy to Head Democratic Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald H. Brown, Jesse Jackson's chief
operative at last summer's Democratic convention, entered the race
for chairman of the party Tuesday with a declaration that he was
seeking the office as ``my own man.''
   Brown, who also worked on the presidential campaigns of Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy, Walter Mondale and Michael Dukakis, said at a
press conference he was an ``independent, mainstream progressive
Democrat'' independent of Jackson or any other party leader.
   Brown said he considered himself the front-runner in what was
shaping up as at least a five-way race to succeed Paul Kirk, the
Democratic National Committee chairman who announced Monday he would
leave his post after four years.
   And while welcoming the support of Jackson's supporters on the
DNC, Brown emphasized his long party service and independence.
   ``I'm nobody's candidate. I'm my own man,'' he said. If elected,
``no one will be given the advantage'' as the party looks toward
1992, he said.
   Also running or expected to run for the party post were Michigan
Democratic chairman Richard Wiener and former Reps. Michael Barnes
of Maryland, Jim Jones of Oklahoma and Jim Stanton of Ohio.
   Wiener, who announced his candidacy for the national post Monday,
told reporters Tuesday he planned to spend upwards of $100,000 on
the race and would release in about two weeks a list of DNC
supporters representing all regions of the country.
   ``I believe I enter as a strong contender, as a favorite,'' he
said, downplaying other candidates' counts of supporters and
refusing to release his own. Adding together the numbers of
supporters claimed by each candidate would yield double the 404
members on the DNC, he said.
   The DNC meets Feb. 9-10 in Washington to select a new chairman.
   ``All of the other candidates are good Democrats,'' said Wiener,
who described himself as having a political philosphy modeled after
that of John F. Kennedy.
   Instead of philosophy, the ability to run the party machinery
would be foremost, the outgoing president of the Association of
State Democratic Chairs said.
   ``I believe the most important job ... is to have this party
ready in 1992 to win the presidency of the United States,'' he said.
The party needed to build a ``fighting machine'' to counter the
Republican apparatus which will be headed by Lee Atwater, who was
George Bush's campaign manager.
   What is needed is to build upon Kirk's fund-raising and
organizational efforts, he said, but not changing the party's basic
message.
   ``I do not believe it was a philosphical problem in this
election,'' he said. Michael Dukakis ``allowed himself to be
defined'' in a way that distorted Democratic values, which he said
included a strong defense and no tolerance of crime.
   Barnes declared his candidacy in a mailgram sent out Monday to
Democratic leaders. Jones planned to make a formal announcement next
week, while Stanton said Monday he was ``looking forward to a
candidacy.''
</TEXT>
