<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Arafat 1stLd-Writethru a0624 12-06 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arafat, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0624,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Chief Meets American Jews in Stockholm</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs, comment after meeting; PICKS up 6th pvs:
Rita Hauser</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat met with a group
of American Jews on Tuesday to promote his new image of moderation
and build support for the declaration of an independent Palestinian
state issued last month.
   The meeting, arranged by the Swedish government, took place a
week before Arafat is to address the U.N. General Assembly in
Geneva. The assembly decided to move its session from New York to
the European U.N. headquarters when the United States refused Arafat
a visa.
   A Swedish government statement after the meeting said ``major
issues were addressed and important progress was made.'' When
reporters asked Arafat about the results of the meeting, he replied:
``It is better to wait and see.''
   Mounted police sealed off the snow-covered park around the Haga
Palace, where Arafat and aides conferred with the five-member Jewish
delegation from the United States.
   Foreign Minister Sten Andersson was in the 18th century building
for the first hour of the meeting, then left and returned two hours
later for the end.
   Ingvar Carlsson, the prime minister, cut short a trip to Paris to
return home and act as host at a dinner for the two delegations.
   He greeted Arafat with an embrace after the meeting and received
the Jewish group at his office 40 minutes later. None of the
delegation members commented to reporters.
   Rita Hauser led the Jewish group. She is chairman of the U.S.
branch of the International Center for Peace in the Middle East, a
coalition of leftist organizations in Israel and other countries.
   Abba Eban, former Israeli foreign minister, is international
chairman of the center. Its Israeli branch includes prominent
members of the center-left Labor Party of Foreign Minister Shimon
Peres, to which Eban belongs.
   The center believes Israel should give up at least some of the
Arab territory captured in the 1967 Middle East war and many of its
members urge the Israeli government to deal directly with the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Israel and several Jewish organizations protested the meeting.
The Israeli Foreign Ministry lodged an official protest with the
Swedish ambassador.
   An Israeli source said privately a message was sent to one
participant, Menachem Rosensaft of the Labor Zionist Alliance, by
his group's parent organization ordering him to resign all official
positions.
   Sweden's Foreign Ministry described the delegation members as
``prominent personalities'' representing a significant portion of
U.S. Jewish opinion, but an Israeli diplomat in Stockholm dismissed
them as ``unimportant.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Benjamin Cohen, president of the American Zionist Federation,
issued a statement in New York saying, ``The Americans who are at
the meeting are participating for their own benefit, without the
support of any recognized organization in the Jewish community.''
   Israeli refuses to deal with the PLO and has made it a criminal
offense for any Israeli citizen to do so. It has urged Israel's U.S.
supporters to abstain from contacts with an organization it
describes as a band of terrorists.
   Other members of the Jewish delegation were Drora Kass, the
center's executive director; Stanley Sheinbaum, an economist and
publisher from Los Angeles, and Avraham Udovitch, chairman of the
department for Near East Studies at Princeton University.
   Arafat's delegation included Mahmoud Darwish and Yasser
Abed-Rabbo, both members of the PLO executive committee; his
spokesman Bassam Abu Sharif, and Akram Haniah, a former journalist
expelled by Israel last year.
   Ministry officials said Andersson spent months arranging the
meeting. The newspaper Aftonbladet called it a personal triumph for
the foreign minister.
   Sweden said it was a way to ``contribute to the peace process in
the Middle East.''
   Andersson has urged Israel to respond to what he called ``the
historic decisions'' announced Nov. 15 in Algiers, when the PLO
accepted U.N. resolutions that recognize Israel.
   Carlsson told reporters before leaving Paris, in an apparent
reference to the PLO and Israel: ``If a dialogue can be started
between the two parties, it would be a major breakthrough.''
</TEXT>
