<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-Taxes     12-06 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Taxes,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Position on Taxes Intact After Meeting With Rostenkowski</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Final three grafs, At a, are for release at 8 p.m. EST, time
set by source</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush and Rep. Dan
Rostenkowski, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee,
disagreed over the need to raise taxes Tuesday, but cemented what
they said was a long-time friendship.
   ``We talked about taxes but he did not change his position at
all,'' Rostenkowski said after the Illinois Democrat ate lunch with
Bush at the vice president's office.
   Bush was ``very firm in the fact that he did not want to discuss
the increasing of revenue,'' said the head of the tax-writing panel.
   ``Everybody knows my position on taxes,'' said Bush, who vowed
during the campaign to hold firm against tax hikes.
   When Rostenkowski broached his idea of raising the federal
gasoline tax by 10 or 15 cents per gallon, Bush replied, ``That's
interesting ... That is as far as he went with respect to discussing
taxes,'' the congressman said.
   A 15-cent increase in the gas tax would bring in about $15
billion annually, a mere dent in the $150-billion-a-year-deficit.
   Rostenkowski, echoing the line of some congressional Democrats,
said he does not think the deficit can be brought down without
increasing revenues and cutting domestic and defense spending.
   In Rostenkowski's view, lingering high deficits will destabilize
the economy to the point where the nation's standard of living will
decline.
   But he said the decision to initiate tax increases is in the
hands of the president-elect. The Democrats will not take such a
step.
   Earlier, Rostenkowski predicted Bush would have little trouble
backing away from his no-tax-increase pledge if he wants to do so.
   While the men were at odds over taxes, Bush said they enjoy each
other. ``What we did today ... is renew a friendship,'' the
president-elect said. Bush served on Ways and Means with
Rostenkowski when he was a congressman from Texas in the late 1960s.
   Said Rostenkowski: ``George Bush is the same George Bush he was
when he was a member of Congress ... He has a great perception of
what the legislative process is.'' He has called Bush a friend.
   Bush will also have an easier time dealing with Congress because
he understands the system, Rostenkowski said.
   Rostenkowski announced Tuesday that his committee will holding
hearings beginning Jan. 31 on whether the tax code should be changed
as a result of the recent wave of corporate takeovers, especially
those requiring huge debts.
   ``It is... apropriate to ask if these transactions allow certain
corporations to escape the payment of fair taxes, thereby harming
the average American taxpayer,'' said Rostenkowski, who made no
specific proposal for a new tax or other change in the law.
   Meanwhile, speaking at a breakfast sponsored by the Gannett Co.
Inc., the incoming chairman of the Senate Budget Committee predicted
that Bush would have to ask for a tax increase before the midway
point of his term.
   ``My view is there will be additional taxes ... within the next
two years,'' said Sen. James R. Sasser, D-Tenn. Bush would again ask
people to ``read my lips,'' he said, but this time he'll be saying,
``Let's get some additional revenue in the till.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Final three grafs are embargoed for 8 p.m. EST release</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   At a speech in New York Tuesday night, Rostenkowski argued
against imposing a national sales tax or making major changes in the
income tax.
   A sales tax would require a new administrative structure,
Rostenkowski said. And although there may be some remaining
deductions and exclusions that could be reduced, ``the income taxes
ought not be a candidate for serious surgery.''
   He argued against any soak-the-rich tax increase, saying any plan
must be balanced. And he rejected a favorite Bush campaign proposal
to cut the tax on capital gains as a plan that would hand more money
to the rich _ not raise federal revenues.
</TEXT>
