<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NorthSupporters     12-06 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North Supporters,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservative Groups Plan to Flood Reagan With Requests for North
Pardon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative group said Tuesday it is
organizing a drive to flood the White House switchboard with calls
urging President Reagan to pardon Oliver North before he leaves
office in January.
   The president has indicated he will not issue a pardon for North,
who is under indictment for his role in the Iran-Contra affair. But
he also has said he will not give up classified government documents
that North says he needs for his defense, a position that could keep
North from coming to trial.
   ``We are disappointed but undaunted,'' Robert Grant, president of
the American Freedom Coalition, said of Reagan's refusal so far to
pardon North. ``We will not halt our national project until Col.
North is either exonerated by the courts or justly pardoned by the
president.''
   North was a lieutenant colonel in the Marine Corps, on the
National Security Council staff under Adm. John Poindexter, when the
alleged offenses occurred involving the diversion to the Nicaraguan
Contra rebels of proceeds from U.S. arms sales to Iran.
   Grant and three other well-known conservatives held a news
conference against a backdrop of dozens of mail bags which they said
held petitions for a North pardon that would be delivered to the
White House.
   ``We believe that North and his family have already been severely
and justly punished through public humiliation and extensive legal
defense fees,'' Grant said. ``This is no way, in my opinion, to
treat a patriotic war hero who had the guts to stand up to Congress
and its wishy washy on-and-off support of the freedom fighters.''
   Peter T. Flaherty, chairman of Citizens for Reagan, said the
president is going out of office ``a winner'' but that if North is
not pardoned, ``the Reagan foreign policy will be on trial for
several months after he's left office.'' He said failure to pardon
North ``will confirm congressional control of foreign policy.''
   Richard Viguerie, chairman of United Conservatives of America,
said only three groups want a trial for North: the press, which
likes a hot story; Democrats, who want to keep the Bush
administration on the defensive; foreign enemies ``who will benefit
by having our country divided and our intelligence systems paralyzed
at the start of a new administration.''
   Richard Ichord, a former congressman from Missouri and vice
chairman of Grant's group, said North was caught up in a policy
dispute between Congress and Reagan.
   The country, he said, ``has little to gain and much to lose from
a criminal trial that could require the disclosure of national
secrets and even the testimony of a former president and a sitting
president in order to protect the rights of the accused.''
</TEXT>
