<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NursingHomeDeaths     12-06 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nursing Home Deaths,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patients Allegedly Killed For `Emotional Release'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALKER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former nursing home supervisor charged
with killing two patients told police her alleged accomplice killed
six elderly patients, all but one for the ``emotional release'' it
provided her, according to court documents.
   Catherine Wood, 26, and former nurse's aide Gwendolyn Graham, 25,
are suspects in eight deaths last year at Alpine Manor Nursing Home
in this Grand Rapids suburb, authorities said.
   Wood was charged Monday with two counts of murder and held
without bond pending a Dec. 16 preliminary hearing. Graham was
arrested Sunday near her home in Tyler, Texas, and arraigned on one
count of murder. She is being held on $1 million bond while fighting
extradition to Michigan.
   During questioning by police Oct. 7, Wood said Graham had
suffocated the elderly patients in their beds and collected a
``souvenir'' from each, according to search warrants released Monday.
   She said Graham told her ``that each of the killings provided an
emotional release for her,'' with the exception of the death of
97-year-old Edith Cook, who was killed to end her suffering from
gangrene, the court document said.
   Wood also told police that she and Graham lived together from
September 1986 to July 1987 and ``were involved as lovers in a
homosexual relationship,'' the documents said. The alleged killings
occurred between January and May 1987.
   Wood told police she witnessed the Jan. 18, 1987, killing of
60-year-old Marguerite Chambers, an Alzheimer's disease patient. She
``observed Gwendolyn Gail Graham suffocating (the patient) by
pressing a washcloth beneath the chin of Chambers and another
washcloth over Chambers' mouth and nose,'' the warrant said. Wood
told police she did not intervene.
   Wood also told police Graham would tell her of the killings
either just before or after they occurred.
   At the time of their deaths, the eight female patients were
believed to have died from natural causes and no autopsies were
performed.
   Wood, who worked at the home from July 1985 to this October and
most recently was supervisor of nurses' aides, is charged with
killing Cook and Chambers. Graham, who worked at the home from June
1986 to July 1987, is charged with killing Cook. Both bodies were
exhumed last week, but autopsies have proven inconclusive.
   Both aides had received good marks from patients and neither was
fired, nursing home officials said.
   Walker Police Chief Walt Sprenger said Tuesday six more deaths
were being investigated and that more charges against the two women
were likely. He said he did not know if any other bodies would be
exhumed.
   Sprenger would not discuss possible motives in the case, but has
ruled out mercy killings and financial profit. He said the women's
lesbian relationship was ``part of a complex web that brings the
whole thing together.''
   Wood's ex-husband, who first approached police about the deaths
in October 1988 and sparked the investigation, told police his
former wife admitted helping while Graham suffocated the patients,
hoping to spell the word ``murder'' with the victims' initials, the
warrants said.
   Sprenger said he has not been able to substantiate that
allegation. The initials of the alleged victims, identified in
warrants and by relatives contacted by nursing home officials, do
not spell out ``murder.''
   Employees at the nursing home said Wood had a quick temper.
   ``She (Wood) would throw diapers at me and cuss at me,'' Patricia
Patterson, a nurse's aide at Alpine, told The Grand Rapids Press.
``Cathy was always such an angry person.''
</TEXT>
