<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Crowe-Defense     12-06 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crowe-Defense,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Chief Counsels Against Defense Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush should not accept
the conventional wisdom that ``political realities'' dictate
Pentagon budget cuts, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff said
Tuesday.
   Members of Congress who offer that wisdom to the incoming
administration seldom have much to say, ``to me or to our citizens,
about overseas threats or `military realities' which do not conform
to their version of political reality,'' added Adm. William J. Crowe
Jr., the joint chiefs chairman.
   ``This inability to consider strategic questions in a reasonable
and consistent manner is both inefficient and dangerous,'' he said,
adding the danger is intensified because the nation's fiscal
problems are occuring at a time of relative peace around the world.
   ``In war, we remember the Alamo, the Maine, Pearl Harbor. In good
times, we forget.''
   Crowe spoke Tuesday night before the World Affairs Council of
Washington, offering a broad review of military and diplomatic
affairs at home and abroad. A text of his speech was released in
advance by the Pentagon.
   The four-star admiral said he wanted to work with Bush to improve
Pentagon management, to convince Congress that stable financing
instead of peak-and-valley cycles could save huge amounts of money,
and to continue improving the nation's ability to fight guerrilla
wars.
   ``Like everything else, Pentagon management is not as bad as the
critics say, nor as good as some defenders argue,'' Crowe said.
``But nevertheless, we are going to need strong leadership to
implement a wide range of reforms.''
   The nation's top military officer said he understood the Pentagon
was unlikely to get all the money it wanted. But he said he would
counsel Bush not to reduce military manpower or the funds needed to
preserve readiness.
   ``Adjustments _ some of them significant _ are clearly ahead as
we conform our forces and our collective security approach to
emerging international realities and evolving challenges, including
economic considerations,'' he declared.
   ``But it would be a grievous _ and probably, ultimately disabling
_ error to undertake those adjustments with an eye only to the
concerns of accountants.''
   Crowe said the diplomatic and military situation in Asia and the
Pacific rim was probably the most stable; the situation in the
Middle East, Central and South America and Near East the least, and
Europe in between.
   The problem in Europe is that Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev
talks about reforming his nation's economy and downplaying defense,
but Russian military forces are ``still most formidable, structured
and postured for the offensive and backed up by a continued
commitment to modernization,'' Crowe said.
   In the Pacific, the United States will face the ``challenging
issue'' of retaining access to forward bases. But he said that more
important are Mideast tensions, Latin American drug trafficking, the
threat of terrorism, and the need to preserve access to overseas oil.
   ``We'll need flexibility and open-mindedness on all sides, as
well as the wisdom, tenacity and political courage to take a long
view of the national interest,'' Crowe said. ``It's going to be a
tough road in a frequently short-sighted town.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
