<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Death, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0746,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Memorial Held for Homeless Man Dragged into Streets from Restaurant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS typo Band to Bank in 13th graf bgng ``Eaton grew up''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 mourners attended a streetside
memorial service Tuesday for a homeless man who died on a sidewalk
after being ejected from a fast-food restaurant where he had
collapsed over a bacon cheeseburger.
   Joseph Emerson Eaton, 38, a member of a prominent New England
family, was found dead just outside the doorway of Carl's Jr.
restaurant on Market Street at 5 a.m. Saturday.
   Coroner's authorities said Eaton suffered from alcoholism, drug
abuse and AIDS-related complex and his arms showed fresh needle
marks. They were waiting for toxicology test results before
determining the exact cause of death.
   Five hours before Eaton died, he had been dragged out and dropped
on the sidewalk by a security guard who said he thought he was
``drunk as a skunk'' when he collapsed unconscious.
   The memorial service was organized by the Rev. Thomas Flowers, an
Eastern Orthodox monk who runs a soup kitchen at the nearby United
Nations Plaza. It was Flowers who found Eaton's stiff, lifeless body
while making rounds in the seedy area known as the Tenderloin
District, just two blocks from City Hall.
   The neighborhood is known for panhandlers, homeless sleeping in
doorways and on benches, and a tent city outside the U.S. Health
Department office demanding more federal funding to fight AIDS.
   Flowers and the Rev. Stephen Graham officiated at the service
attended by approximately 100 mourners, many of them street people
who held candles or carnations in memory of Eaton and 160 ``John
Does'' who have died on San Francisco streets this year.
   As the smell of burning incense enveloped the crowd, Flowers
urged the listeners not to ignore people lying in doorways or on the
street. ``Let the ambulance come quickly when that 911 number is
called _ even if it's down here in the Tenderloin,'' he said.
   ``The most evil thing today is indifference,'' said The Rev.
Cecil Williams of Glide Memorial Methodist Church, which operates a
free food program in the neighborhood.
   Scattered throughout the gathering were gaunt people with
bedrolls or shopping carts laden with belongings. One man had a cart
with a sign, ``Donations to help support two girls'' and a group
called Food Not Bombs distributed free fruit.
   Flowers said he had seen Eaton several times at his soup kitchen,
often in the company of another homeless man known as ``Fast Eddie.''
   Mayor Art Agnos' spokeswoman Eileen Maloney said the mayor had no
comment about Eaton's death because it was a private incident and
could lead to lawsuits. But she said Agnos ``was upset personally.''
   Eaton grew up in the affluent Boston suburb of Duxbury, Mass. His
late grandfather, Charles Freedom Eaton Jr., was a prominent
financier, a founder of Investors Bank & Trust Co. His father,
Joseph Emerson Eaton Sr., is a retired business executive.
   Eaton enjoyed the privileges of his family's wealth, attending
prestigious New England prep schools. But his brother, Nick, a New
Hampshire contractor, said he ``was an alcoholic from the time he
was 13, from the time he took his first drink. And later, he got
heavily into using drugs. But time after time after time, it was
alcohol that brought him his troubles.''
   Relatives said Eaton tried several treatment programs with their
moral and financial support.
   Nick Eaton said his brother called Friday to ask the family to
finance another treatment program. They agreed.
   He never attended college, and worked as a chef and florist. He
moved to San Francisco in 1981 and told his family he was gay.
   ``We accepted his choice of lifestyle,'' said another brother,
Henry Eaton, a reporter at a Boston TV station. ``It was only his
self-destructive drinking that ever concerned us.''
   Eaton and Phillip Coleman, also a gay, recovering
alcoholic-addict, moved in together in 1983. According to Eaton's
Alcoholics Anonymous sponsor, Skip B., they were very happy and
Eaton was sober until Coleman died of AIDS in November 1987.
   By then, Eaton knew he had AIDS-related complex, a condition that
includes some of the symptoms of AIDS but not life-threatening
cancers or infections that take advantage of the body's weakened
immune system.
   ``Phil's death really devastated Joey,'' said Skip B., who took
in Eaton until he passed out with a lit cigarette and started a fire
in Skip's home. On Nov. 12, Eaton was told to move out and he became
one of the city's estimated 6,000 homeless.
</TEXT>
