<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Walesa     12-06 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Walesa,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passport for Walesa Aide Likely, Spokesman Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday it is changing
its attitude toward Solidarity founder Lech Walesa and indicated one
of his main advisers could accompany him to France.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said the reply ``may be
positive'' to the passport application of historian Bronislaw
Geremek.
   President Francois Mitterrand of France has invited Walesa,
winner of the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, to attend observances Saturday
of the 40th anniversary of the Declaration of the Universal Rights
of Man.
   Walesa was told last Saturday he could make the trip but he
wanted Geremek, whose specialty is French medieval history and who
speaks fluent French, to accompany him.
   Geremek said Sunday that he had been refused a passport on all
five recent occasions when he applied.
   Adam Michnik, another Walesa adviser, said from Gdansk on Tuesday
that Walesa planned to leave Friday and return Sunday.
   It would the first time authorities have granted Walesa a
passport since the free trade union was suppressed and outlawed
after the imposition of martial law in December 1981.
   Permission for the trip coincided with signs of a more positive
feeling toward Walesa by authorities.
   ``There has been a change of attitude toward Walesa,'' Urban
confirmed at his news conference.
   Citing Walesa's statements during a Nov. 30 nationally televised
debate with official unions chief Alfred Miodowicz, and his public
statements since, Urban said it was ``a different Lech Walesa than
the one who in past years many times spoke in a confrontational
spirit.''
   ``Is this new Walesa, growing to be a partner, going to be
stable? Is he going to keep this tone which dominated his television
statements? I think yes,'' Urban said.
   In another development, Solidarity spokesmen said Walesa was
allowed to address about 4,000 students Monday night in an unusual
meeting in a Gdansk University lecture hall and answer questions
about his debate with Miodowicz.
   The meeting was organized by the banned but active Independent
Students Association, roughly the campus equivalent of Solidarity,
and was attended by some university officials, said Michnik.
   Walesa was quoted by Solidarity spokesman Robert Kozak as telling
the students: ``Many interesting things are happening now. May Poles
really reach agreement and find a place for themselves.''
</TEXT>
