<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Gorbachev-CommandCenter     12-06 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-Command Center,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official `Problem Solvers' Staff Command Center</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Superpower Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal and local trouble-shooters watched
Mikhail Gorbachev's arrival Tuesday on a video screen in a darkened,
vaultlike room at Police Headquarters, which has been turned into a
command center for his visit.
   ``It's an assembly of people who are problem-solvers,'' said
Deputy Inspector James Vitti. ``The premise is that we have one
location where people who can speak for their agencies are available
to cope with any potential problem that may develop.''
   More than 20 agencies, including the FBI, the Secret Service, the
Coast Guard, the Federal Aviation Administration, the Fire
Department, the city's traffic department and its ambulance corps
were represented.
   Two long tables with banks of telephones and a 26-foot-by-10-foot
video screen dominated the room. One side panel of the screen
contained a slide of Time Magazine's ``Man of the Year'' cover that
depicted the Soviet leader.
   In the middle panel, television coverage of Gorbachev's arrival
alternated between local stations and Cable News Network.
   ``We would define success as having nothing to do for the next
three days,'' Vitti said.
   But the command center, which is in constant contact with agents
and officers in the field, was called upon at least three times
before Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, were safely delivered to the
Soviet Mission in Manhattan from Kennedy International Airport.
   The first call came before their arrival when motorists on the
Long Island Expressway became impatient with detours and drove up on
the grass to avoid roadblocks.
   This problem went to police officials who dispatched extra
patrols to turn back the motorists.
   Another traffic problem arose on the Van Wyck Expressway in
Queens when a propane truck broke down in a lane that was to be
closed for Gorbachev's motorcade.
   The representative for the city Transportation Department at the
command center ordered the immediate dispatch of a tow truck, which
removed the disabled vehicle 10 minutes before Gorbachev left the
airport.
   As the motorcade traveled down the Grand Central Parkway in
Queens, another call came in to the command center _ a private
helicopter hired by a news organization was hovering too close to
the procession of 45 cars.
   The FAA representative notified the closest air control tower and
the helicopter was told to pull back.
   When the motorcade pulled into the Soviet Mission, police Lt.
Vincent Kennedy said: ``As an old friend of mine used to say, it
went like ice cream. No problems.''
</TEXT>
