<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     12-06 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition to Contest Roh's Choice of Premier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main opposition party said Tuesday
it would contest President Roh Tae-woo's choice for premier.
   The Party for Peace and Democracy led by Kim Dae-jung said it
would oppose National Assembly confirmation of Kang Young-hoon
because Roh did not consult the legislature about the appointment.
   Kim's party does not have enough votes to block approval and
would need the support of other opposition parties.
   Roh named Kang and 19 new ministers Monday in a shake-up prompted
by a political crisis over demands that former President Chun
Doo-hwan, Roh's predecesor, be made to account for human rights
abuses and corruption during his tenure.
   Roh said the appointments were among several measures to cut his
ties with Chun's authoritarian regime, but critics called the
changes insufficient. A similar reorganizaion is expected in the
governing Democratic Justice Party.
   National Assembly hearings into the suppression of a 1980
uprising in the southern city of Kwangju, in which hundreds of
people were killed, resumed Tuesday with legislators questioning
witnesses on who was responsible. Chun and Roh were senior generals
at the time.
   Officials said privately Tuesday the government plans to limit
the functions of the Defense Security Command to keep the powerful
military agency out of civilian affairs. They said the Agency for
National Security Planning, the government's main intelligence
organization, would be streamlined and barred from political
surveillance.
   Past rulers of South Korea have used the Defense Security Command
as a political tool. Chun was head of the command when he seized
power in 1980.
   Kang, the designated prime minister, paid a courtesy call Tuesday
on Kim, but the opposition leader said the party already had decided
to challenge the confirmation.
   Kim's party claimed Roh violated the Constitution by naming a
Cabinet along with a premier. Party officials said Roh should have
selected only a premier, who in turn would choose a Cabinet.
   The Constitution says a Cabinet should be formed after the
National Assembly confirms the premier, but naming both at the same
time has been common in recent years.
   Chun went into rural exile in a remote Buddhist monastery last
month after apologizing to the nation for abuses while in power. He
left office in February.
   Roh opposes efforts to punish Chun and asked the nation to
forgive the former president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
