<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-06 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain And Snow In The Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cold, wet weather dominated the Northwest on Tuesday, but the
upper Midwest had record warmth.
   A cold front moved across the Northwest, producing rain, freezing
rain and snow.
   Rain extended over the northern Pacific Coast through the
morning, changing to freezing rain across eastern Washington, the
Idaho Panhandle and western Montana, with rain changing to snow at
higher elevations.
   Snow showers extended over central New England, and rain was
scattered from north-central Texas into south-central Oklahoma.
   Record high temperatures for the date included 40 at Duluth,
Minn., and 46 at Marquette, Mich. Madison, Wis., tied its record of
53, which has been on the books since 1879.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 19
degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 80 at Fort Myers, Fla. Tuesday
morning's official low was 7 degrees below zero at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Wednesday, snow showers were forecast from the northern and
central Rockies into western South Dakota, and over Upper Michigan.
Scattered rain was forecast from central Texas across north-central
Texas.
   Highs in the teens were predicted from northern Minnesota into
eastern North Dakota; in the 20s and 30s in northern Maine, the
upper Great Lakes, the remainder of the upper half of the
Mississippi Valley, the upper two-thirds of the Plains and the
Rockies; in the 40s and 50s from central Maine across New Jersey,
the Appalachians, the lower Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley, the
Tennessee Valley, from southeastern Missouri across northern
Arkansas, Oklahoma, northern Texas, and the northern half of the
Pacific Coast; in the 70s from the South Carolina coast across
Florida, across the Texas Gulf Coast, and southern California; and
generally in the 60s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
