<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Birth 2ndLd-Writethru a0674 12-06 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Birth, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0674,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Without Ovaries Gives Birth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to reflect baby's sex.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRENOBLE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman without ovaries gave birth to a
baby produced from her egg and her husband's sperm, a medical
advance that offers hope to women who might otherwise be infertile,
doctors said Tuesday.
   The 6-pound, 5-ounce baby girl, Laure, was born Monday in this
Alpine city to a 37-year-old woman who asked to be identified only
as Aline to protect her family's privacy.
   ``I'm so happy, I was without hope,'' she told The Associated
Press in a telephone interview from her bed at the Hopital Sud.
   French doctors said the birth was the first time a woman without
ovaries delivered a baby conceived from her own egg.
   Other women without ovaries have carried babies to term, but in
the past the infant was produced from the egg of a donor. Aline's
egg was fertilized in a laboratory dish by her husband's sperm, the
resulting embryo was frozen and implanted 10 months later in her
uterus.
   The birth represents a major medical advance because it means
biological ``motherhood is still possible for young women who have
no ovaries or for leukemia patients, for example, whose ovaries have
been irrevocably damaged by radiation or chemotherapy,'' Dr. Nicole
Quenard said.
   The doctor, who attended delivered Laure by Caesarean section,
called the birth ``very moving for everyone.''
   She said the surgical delivery was necessary for reasons not
related to the conception.
   Aline first consulted the fertility specialists at Hospital Sud
in the spring of 1985. She was in pain and had been unable to
conceive.
   Aline had lost an ovary years before to infection and doctors at
Hopital Sud discovered she suffered from advanced endometriosis, a
condition in which uterine tissue grows outside the womb.
   In Aline's case, the endrometriosis had surrounded her remaining
ovary. When she did not respond to medication, doctors decided to
remove the ovary.
   Before the ovary was removed, doctors extracted four eggs and
fertilized them with Aline's husband's sperm. Four embryos resulted,
and two were implanted in Aline's uterus. No pregnancy resulted.
   On Dec. 14, 1987, doctors removed Aline's remaining ovary and
Fallopian tubes, leaving her uterus. Three months later, the
remaining embryos were implanted in Aline's uterus, and Laure's
birth was the result.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
