<HEAD>Warden Held Hostage In Prison Riot, 13 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUAYAMA, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inmates held a prison warden hostage
Tuesday night after fighting broke out among 300 convicts at the
maximum security unity of a prison, police said.
   Five prisoners were reported wounded by gunfire and eight were
injured in the rioting at the Guyama Regional Prison, 51 miles south
of San Juan.
   Prison officials were negotiating with inmates, who took the
warden hostage during the rebellion. It was not immediately known
what the inmates wanted in exchange for releasing the warden,
identified as Roberto Sanchez.
   About 100 riot police surrounded the prison while negotiations
took place.
   Police Capt. Paulino Rodriguez Fonseca said the fighting started
when two prison gangs clashed in the prison's maximum security ward.
   The injured, suffering from gunshot wounds, burns and broken
bones, were being treated at area hospitals.
   ``This was a horrible rebellion,'' said Rodriguez.
   He said fighting flared at around 3:50 p.m. when one gang tried
to break into the new maximum security section of the prison where
another gang was being held.
   He said many inmates went on a rampage and set fire to part of
the prison. A wing of the prison appeared gutted.
