<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Slayings-Fugitive     12-06 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Slayings-Fugitive,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charges Filed In Universal Studios Slayings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Murder charges calling for the death penalty
were filed Tuesday against an escaped psychiatric patient accused of
shooting two guards at Universal Studios after demanding to see
actor Michael Landon.
   According to witnesses, Nathan Nicholas Trupp, 42, apparently had
delusions that Landon, star of the ``Highway to Heaven'' television
series, was a Nazi.
   Trupp was charged with first-degree murder in the slaying of
Jeren Beeks and Armando Torres, and one count of attempted murder
stemming from the shootout he had with sheriff's deputies after the
slayings. Trupp was wounded by deputies.
   ``The motive is not robbery,'' said Deputy District Attorney
Sterling Norris, who filed the charges. ``It is that he believed
that he was killing Nazis.''
   Norris said Trupp believed not only that Landon was a Nazi, but
also three people authorities say were slain by Trupp in an
Albuquerque, N.M. bagel shop on Nov. 29.
   The charges allege a multiple murder special circumstance, which
permits a possible death penalty if Trupp is convicted.
   Tests indicated the .38-caliber handgun used in the Universal
Studios shootings was the same weapon used in the bagel shop
killings, authorities said.
   Trupp, who had lived off and on in Albuquerque since August 1987,
walked away from a supervised boarding house for the mentally ill in
Trenton, N.J., April 5, 1987, after being involuntarily committed
for state psychiatric care.
   Trupp allegedly shot the Universal guards Thursday after
demanding to see or talk by telephone to Landon. The guards declined
to let Trupp use the telephone in their shack to call Landon.
   Trupp was scheduled for arraignment Tuesday afternoon, but
prosecutors said beforehand that Trupp was not well enough. The
hearing later was continued to Dec. 13.
</TEXT>
