<DOCNO> AP881206-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 2217EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TankerFire     12-06 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tanker Fire,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gas Tanker Collides With Locomotive, Killing 1 and Torching 2 Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARTERET, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gasoline tank truck collided with a
Conrail locomotive at a road crossing and burst into flames Tuesday,
killing the truck driver, destroying two houses and leaving 15
people homeless, authorities said.
   An 80-foot plume of flame from the tanker burned for an hour
before being brought under control by about 100 firefighters, said
Carteret Fire Superintendent Richard Greenberg.
   ``The gas was flowing all over the place, catching fire,'' said
police Sgt. Ron Bennett.
   Driver Enrique Cosme, 53, of Elizabeth, was killed instantly when
the tanker ran into one of two joined locomotives crossing an
industrial section of tracks about 6 a.m., Bennett said.
   The crossing has no warning system, officials said. When trains
need to cross the junction, a crew member gets out and signals to
oncoming traffic.
   Conrail spokeswoman Pat Linskey in Philadelphia said a train
worker saw no traffic and radioed the locomotives to proceed.
   He then saw the truck and ``waved a flare and the truck continued
to advance and the accident happened,'' she said. None of the three
Conrail crewmen was injured.
   The 9,000-gallon capacity truck, which had just been filled at a
Shell Oil Co. depot, spilled about 4,000 gallons on the road and
into sewers, culverts and the grounds of two factories.
   The fire spread to several buildings in the lightly populated
industrial area, destroying two homes _ a four-family dwelling and a
single-family unit. Two buildings from the nearby FMC chemical
manufacturing company and a third home also were damaged.
   A half-mile wide stream of black smoke from the blaze reached
across the Arthur Kill waterway toward New York. The state
Department of Environmental Protection told residents of
northeastern New Jersey and New York City to take precautions
against heavy breathing as the smoke moved into the area. It
dissipated by noon.
   A small but undetermined amount of fuel spilled into the
waterway, which separates New Jersey from Staten Island, but
officials said there appeared to be no major contamination.
   Three people were admitted to hospitals for observation and
released, Greenberg said.
   The tanker truck was owned by Island Transportation of
Woodbridge. An employee who answered the telephone at the company
said officials had no comment. He refused to identify himself.
   The area remained closed to traffic until late in the afternoon,
while about 40 workers from the Middlesex County Hazardous Materials
Emergency Response Unit and Clean Venture of Perth Amboy, an
environmental cleanup company, recovered the spilled fuel with
suction equipment.
</TEXT>
