<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Gorbachev-Protests     12-06 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-Protests,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrations Held Near Soviet Mission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of protesters gathered Tuesday night near
the Soviet mission where Mikhail Gorbachev is staying to vent their
displeasure at the Soviet leader's policies on Armenians and Jews.
   With speeches, songs and chants, the demonstrators made their
positions known, but got no apparent response from anyone at the
mission a half-block away in a fashionable section of Manhattan's
East Side.
   ``Gorbachev stop the massacres,'' chanted several hundred
American-Armenians, referring to reports of atrocities against
Armenians in Azerbaijan.
   Across from the placard-waving Armenians stood a handful of
placard-waving Jews calling for improved human rights for Jews in
the Soviet Union.
   ``We hope the light of Hanukkah penetrates the darkness of Soviet
Russia,'' said Glenn Richter, an organizer of the demonstration by
the Student Struggle for Soviet Jewry.
   Rabbi Avraham Weiss, addressing the gathering of about 20 people,
said ``We're here for the hundreds of thousands denied permission to
leave the Soviet Union. We're here for all of those who died waiting
for exit visas.''
   Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., who came to the Armenian rally at
the request of the organizers, said, ``We want to let the Soviets
know that we are concerned about human rights.''
   Long-simmering racial antagonisms in the southern Soviet
republics of Armenia and Azerbaijan have surfaced under Gorbachev's
twin policies of perestroika and glasnost, or restructuring and
openness, forcing the Kremlin to impose a virtual state of martial
law there.
   Lautenberg said Western reporters and the Red Cross should be
allowed in the region ``and tell us the truth about what's
happening.''
   ``In Azerbaijan and the area called the Karabakh, Armenians are
assaulted, their homes have been invaded, families have been in some
cases raped,'' Lautenberg said. ``We want to know the true facts.''
   The Soviet leader, accompanied by his closest foreign policy
advisers, arrived in New York City on Tuesday for a two-day visit
that includes an address to the United Nations on Wednesday. Later,
he is to meet with President Reagan and President-elect George Bush.
</TEXT>
