<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PuertoRico-PrisonRiot     12-06 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico-Prison Riot,1st Ld-Writethru,a0804,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warden Held Hostage In Prison Riot, 13 Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with condition for warden's release, more
prisoners involved, background on prison, fighting at two juvenile
centers; no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LUIS R. VARELA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUAYAMA, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of inmates rioted when a
gang war broke out at a southern Puerto Rico penitentiary on
Tuesday, and prisoners took the warden hostage, police said. At
least 13 inmates were reported injured.
   Five inmates were wounded by gunfire and eight others were
injured during the riot involving 400 inmates of a maximum-security
unit of the Guyama Regional Prison, about 51 miles south of San
Juan, police said.
   Part of the prison was set on fire and a wing appeared gutted by
the blaze.
   The violence was triggered by a clash between two gangs, said
police Capt. Paulino Rodriguez Fonseca.
   Prison officials were negotiating with inmates who took the
warden hostage during the rebellion. Prison officials said inmates
of one gang were demanding that members of the other gang be
transferred to another prison.
   Prison officials identified the warden as Roberto Sanchez.
   The injured, suffering from gunshot wounds, burns and broken
bones, were being treated at local hospitals.
   ``This was a horrible rebellion,'' said Rodriguez Fonseca.
   About 100 riot police surrounded the prison while negotiations
took place.
   Department of Corrections administrator Mercedes Otero said the
prison has a capacity of 1,000 but that only 774 prisoners were
jailed at the time of the riot.
   Rodriguez Fonseca said the rebellion flared at around 3:50 p.m.
(4:50 p.m. EST) when one gang tried to break into the new
maximum-security section of the prison where another gang was being
held.
   He said many inmates went on a rampage during the fighting and
set fire to part of the prison. A wing of the prison appeared gutted.
   Meanwhile, police reported two girls and an employee at the
Villalba Juvenile Home were injured after fighting broke out at the
girl's home, located in the central city of Villalba. Police also
reported a rebellion at another juvenile center in the southern city
of Ponce but there were no injuries.
</TEXT>
