<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MOVEHouse     12-06 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MOVE House,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Trying To Sell Rebuilt MOVE House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city wants to sell the home rebuilt on
the site of the bombed-out MOVE headquarters, but neighbors in the
area that burned in the 1985 battle between police and the radical
group want officials to come to terms with the former owner first.
   Louise James, sister of late MOVE founder John Africa, owned the
house, which was condemned by the city so the neighborhood could be
rebuilt. The city gave the rebuilt homes to all the residents except
Ms. James.
   Her suit against the city to recover the house, which is under
24-hour police guard, is pending in Common Pleas Court.
   While neighbors don't want Ms. James to get the house back, they
don't want it sold until the city can come to an agreement with her,
said one resident, Gerald Renfrow.
   ``She's not going to walk away with no money and no house, and
that's going to keep us in the middle of their fight,'' he said.
   Sixty-one houses were destroyed after police dropped a bomb on
the roof of the fortified MOVE row house in an effort to evict the
members. John Africa; Ms. James' son, Frank James Africa; and nine
others in the house died in the siege.
   The city Redevelopment Authority, which owns the house, plans to
meet Wednesday to arrange transfer to a city-controlled agency that
can arrange a sale without public bidding, officials said in Tuesday
editions of the Philadelphia Daily News.
   Carl Tobey Oxholm III, deputy city solicitor, said Monday the
city had no intention to sell Ms. Africa the house.
   Ms. James' attorney, Fincourt B. Shelton, said that if there's an
attempt to sell the house, ``we'll ask the court for a petition to
stay any attempt to sell the property. The property is the subject
of litigation.''
</TEXT>
