<HEAD>Bakker to Plead Innocent, Will Preach Sunday Despite Charges,
Attorney Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf, `The maximum,' with Bakker
picking up summons at courthouse. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `I
spent...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PINEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defrocked evangelist Jim Bakker is
``wholly comfortable with the honorable character of the way
Heritage USA was operated under his leadership'' and will plead
innocent to fraud charges, his attorney said Tuesday.
   A federal grand jury on Monday indicted Bakker, founder of the
PTL ministries, and former aide Richard Dortch on charges of
diverting more than $4 million in PTL money to their own use. Each
was charged with eight counts of mail fraud, 15 counts of wire
fraud, and one count of conspiracy to commit wire and mail fraud.
   A second 11-count indictment charged David Taggart, Bakker's
former personal aide, and Taggart's brother, James, with evading
nearly $500,000 in income taxes and diverting about $1.1 million of
PTL funds for personal expenses.
   Bakker's wife, Tammy, was not indicted.
   Although Bakker himself remained silent Tuesday on the charges,
his attorney, Jim Toms, said the former TV evangelist planned to
preach Sunday at his new church in a converted roller rink.
   Toms said his client would plead innocent to all of the charges
in the 24-count indictment. The indictment said Bakker, 48, and
Dortch, 57, engaged in a conspiracy designed to ``create and
continue lavish and extravagant lifestyles'' by defrauding
supporters who bought lifetime partnerships at PTL's Heritage USA
complex.
   The maximum penalty for each count is five years in prison and a
$250,000 fine, which means Bakker faces a possible sentence of 120
years in prison and $6 million in fines. Bakker and the other
defendants are scheduled to appear in court Dec. 15.
   Bakker and the Taggart brothers visited the federal courthouse in
Charlotte late Tuesday afternoon to pick up summonses ordering them
to appear in court.
   Chief Deputy U.S. Marshal Ray Abrams said the three were
photographed and fingerprinted and gave biographical information to
court officials to be used when bond is set next week. After about
two hours in the courthouse, Bakker left, eluding reporters by going
out a side door.
   ``I spent a good deal of time going over the text of the material
with him last night,'' Toms said in an interview from his
Hendersonville, N.C. office. ``It's going to take time now for him
just to study what's there and decide how we go about dealing with
it.''
   Toms said Bakker's emotional state was good, considering the
circumstances.
   ``I'd say he was relieved to see the specifics so he has a
problem he can start working on,'' he said. ``His faith in his
Christian vocation is unshaken and he is determained to do what he
needs to do to work his way through this.''
   Bakker ``has indicated he is wholly comfortable with the
honorable character of the way Heritage USA was operated under his
leadership and desires to see its ministry restored and continue,''
the attorney said.
   Bakker, who began the ministry in 1972, left it in disgrace in
March 1987 after admitting to a sexual encounter with church
secretary Jessica Hahn eight years earlier.
   After failing to regain control of PTL in bankruptcy proceedings
several months ago, the Bakker moved his newly formed Jim & Tammy
Ministries to a leased brick colonial building on the Yager Estate,
south of Charlotte. The Bakkers live in a 14-room log cabin on the
grounds.
   Friends and supporters dropped by the Bakkers' home throughout
the day as security guards kept reporters and photographers at a
distance.
   Supporters have erected a wooden manger with Christmas lights
outside the offices. A wooden angel was placed in a fountain by the
front door.
   ``The people are cheerful; they're hoping for the best,'' said
Darold Dotson, a former Bakker employee, after delivering a dozen
long-stem roses to the offices.
</TEXT>
