<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Israel-Bombs,1st Ld-Writethru,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six-Year U.S. Ban On Sale Of Cluster Weapons Lifted</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs after last graf pvs with reax from Arab group</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has lifted a six-year ban on
U.S. export of cluster bombs to Israel on the understanding that the
weapons will not be used against civilian targets, the State
Department said Tuesday.
   Reagan banned the sale of such munitions to Israel after that
country used them against civilian target areas in Lebanon in
violation of Israeli assurances to the United States, it was
announced at the time.
   ``Following a recently concluded understanding on the use of
cluster munitions, the president has determined that the ban on
their sale is no longer warranted,'' State Department press officer
Anita Stockman said Tuesday.
   ``Now that the issue of usage has been resolved pursuant to the
terms of the recent understanding'' barring use against civilians,
``we see no reason to prohibit Israel's access to these weapons
which can contribute to Israel's security,'' Ms. Stockman added.
   She noted that the United States sells to many other countries a
variety of cluster bombs and shells, which produce multiple
explosions and fragments on impact.
   Reagan's decision was denounced by Ambassador Clovis Maksoud, the
League of Arab Nations' representative in the United States, who
called it ``shocking,'' ``very provocative'' and ``sickening.''
   Maksoud said many maimed Lebanese and Palestinians ``bear witness
to Israel's reckless use of these weapons during the invasion of
Lebanon and Israel's repeated raids on Lebanese soil.''
   Maksoud added that the decision, coming after U.S. refusal of an
entry visa for Palestine Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat
to speak at the U.N. General Assembly, prompts people to ``wonder if
this latest provocation is a deliberate attempt to strain Arab
patience to the breaking point. Or is this sickening decision a
further departing vindictive shot against the Arab world and another
gift to Israeli rejectionists from the present administration?''
Maksoud asked.
   He added that regardless of such U.S. acts, the ``Palestinians'
commitment to reconciliation will stay the course'' charted last
month in the Palestine National Council declaration at Algiers.
   A New York-based Arab group, the American-Arab Relations
Committee of the National Council on Islamic Affairs, also denounced
the move.
   Committee President M.T. Mehdi said the decision will strengthen
Arab conviction that the United States is a ``permanent ally of
Israel and a permanent enemy of the Arab people.''
   He said that the ``Arabs cannot trust that Israel will not use
these bombs again.''
</TEXT>
