<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   12-06 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0532</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several industrialized nations agreed to lower
import barriers to tropical products like coffee, cocoa and bananas,
but wide gaps remain over the most contentious issues in a new round
of talks on free trade.
   Negotiators expressed pessimism Monday over the outlook for
accords on such controversial issues as farm subsidies, trade in
services and international protection of patents and copyrights.
   Cabinet ministers are meeting to give a political push to
negotiations at the midpoint of a four-year round of free-trade
talks that are the most ambitious since World War II.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s resolve to fight
looming criminal charges appears to be weakening and a possible
climax to its 2-year-old legal trauma seems close, sources familiar
with the case say.
   The prospect of crippling fines and a hostile judge, the taint of
a rackeetering indictment, enormous legal fees and a potential
avalanche of civil lawsuits all are pressuring Drexel to plead
guilty to lesser crimes, the sources said Monday.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder declined comment on the firm's
strategy, but management sent a letter to employees last week
suggesting a settlement was possible and even preferable.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court will again study the
constitutionality of multimillion-dollar punitive damage awards, a
growing phenomenon in U.S. courtrooms that has sparked legislative
debate nationwide.
   The justices agreed Monday to decide whether such awards that far
exceed actual damages violate a constitutional ban on excessive
fines. At stake are large sums of money awarded in a wide variety of
lawsuits.
   The court, which failed in the past to resolve the question, will
tackle the issue in an appeal by a Texas-based waste collection
business ordered to pay $6 million to a Vermont competitor.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturers improved their productivity at an
annual rate of more than 5 percent in the third quarter, but other
businesses struggled to keep increases in their labor costs below
the rate of inflation.
   The Labor Department reported Monday that productivity on
assembly lines rose 5.2 percent in the period as output far outpaced
increases in employment and overtime.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks rose 3.6
percent in late November compared with last year, thanks to a
stronger-than-expected performance by General Motors Corp.
   Sales of imported vehicles dropped 10.1 percent, according to
reports released Monday by the automakers.
   GM reported a 17 percent increase in its late November car sales,
the only Big Three automaker to show a gain. Ford Motor Co. reported
an 18.7 percent drop and Chrysler Corp.'s sales fell 3.6 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel importers have given up on winning an end
to quotas on imported steel and will seek modifications to the
system instead.
   The American Institute for Imported Steel, the Texas Association
of Steel Importers and the West Coast Metal Importers Association
said Monday that the federal government should, among other things,
soften the strict product-by-product quotas that created shortages
over the last two years.
</TEXT>
