<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0558</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four major companies plan to offer their
shareholders a chance to exchange more than $5 billion in stock for
a new type of security that could be traded whole or broken into
three parts.
   The proposal was described Monday as giving high-quality American
companies a ``serious alternative'' to the heavy borrowing usually
associated with stock buybacks that have forced other companies to
sell off major assets, watch their debt ratings fall and cut
spending on items such as research.
   Shareholders who chose to do so would trade a common share for a
new security called an ``unbundled stock unit'' that would consist
of a 30-year bond, preferred stock and a stock appreciation
certificate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long Island Lighting Co. and a former executive
have been convicted of engaging in a pattern of lies to obtain rate
increases to help pay for the utility's Shoreham nuclear power plant.
   The verdict by a federal court jury Monday under the Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations law awarded $22.8 million in
damages to Suffolk County and could make Lilco liable for $1.8
billion if the trial judge certified the suit a class action on
behalf of all ratepayers.
   Lilco said it would seek to set the verdict aside or reverse it
on appeal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Cos. has nearly completed its $12.9
billion acquisition of Kraft Inc. and the creation of the world's
largest consumer products company.
   About 98 percent of Kraft's common stock, or more than 117
million shares, was tendered under Philip Morris' $106-a-share cash
offer that expired Friday, the tobacco and consumer products giant
said Monday.
   Philip Morris said it planned to complete the acquisition as soon
as possible, but offered no specific date.
   __
   FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) _ Zayre Corp. is spinning off its
wholesale division and merging with its TJX Cos. subsidiary in a
major restructuring that will end the company's association with the
59-year-old Zayre discount store chain name.
   Meanwhile, Ames Department Stores Inc., which bought 392 Zayre
stores from Zayre Corp. for $800 million in September, announced
Monday it would close 74 of the outlets.
   Zayre said it would pay a $3.50-a-share dividend to stockholders
after forming a separate company for its BJ's Wholesale Club and
HomeClub operations. After spinning off those operations, Zayre
would merge with TJX Cos., a subsidiary of which it owns 83 percent,
and change its name to TJX Cos.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc. is offering more than
800 employees early retirement in an effort to trim costs at the
textile company, which has grown through the acquisition of two
competitors and is fighting a takeover attempt.
   But Pepperell said Monday that the program was not connected to
its efforts to thwart a $1.4 billion takeover attempt by
Chicago-based Farley Inc.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose strongly Monday as the Dow Jones industrial
average jumped 31.48 points to 2,123.76.
   Bond prices edged higher after last week's sharp selloff.
   The dollar generally strengthened but fell against the British
pound.
   Grain and soybean futures prices fell sharply in a sell-off
apparently spurred by forecasts for rain in Brazil.
</TEXT>
