<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     12-06 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Productivity Gains, But Predictions Grow Bleak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturing productivity is still on the rise, but a new survey
finds the the nation's business economists growing pessimistic about
the economy's fate in 1989.
   The Labor Department said Monday that productivity in the
manufacturing sector improved at an annual rate of 5.2 percent in
the third quarter. A 7.2 percent jump in annual output was
accompanied by only a 1.8 percent jump in employment and overtime to
accomplish it.
   Businesses as a whole did not fare as well. Productivity among
non-farm businesses _ including the service sector that now accounts
for about half of the nation's economic activity _ improved by just
1.9 percent on 3.4 percent higher output and a 1.5 percent rise in
hours worked.
   ``It's pretty puny,'' said Michael Evans, who runs an economic
forecasting firm in Washington. ``The ability to raise our standard
of living is hardly improving at all. That's the real effect of the
budget deficits and these leveraged buyouts (of corporations).
   ``We're spending all these billions on interest payments instead
of capital improvements, research and development and
infrastructure,'' he said.
   Still, the 1.9 percent improvement in efficiency was better than
the 1.3 percent estimated earlier, before the government last week
revised the nation's gross national product upward for the third
quarter. It also nearly offset a 2.4 percent decline in productivity
in the second quarter.
   But the survey of 200 members of the National Association of
Business Economists predicted higher prices and interest rates next
year.
   An overwhelming majority of the economists, 88 percent, predicted
President-elect George Bush would have to deal with a recession in
his first two years in office; 40 percent forecast the country would
be in a downturn by this time next year.
   The group predicted that the overall economy, as measured by the
gross national product, would grow 2.2 percent next year, far below
the 3.5 percent forecast by the administration.
   The group said consumer prices, which have been rising at a 4.6
percent annual rate this year, would climb by 5 percent in 1989, and
interest rates would also continue upward.
   In other economic news Monday, a group of industrialized nations
agreed to lower barriers to imports of tropical products such as
coffee, cocoa and bananas, but wide gaps remained over the most
contentious issues in free-trade talks among more than 100 nations.
   Negotiators expressed pessimism about the outlook for accords on
such issues as farm subsidies, trade in services and international
protection of patents and copyrights.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
