<DOCNO> AP881206-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 0118EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryBills     12-06 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Mixed on Short-Term T-Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities were mixed in the latest auction, with rates on six-month
bills climbing to the highest level in more than three years.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills
Monday at an average discount rate of 8.04 percent, down from 8.05
percent last week. Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 8.25 percent, up from 8.13 percent
last week.
   The rates for six-month bills were the highest since April 15,
1985, when they averaged 8.27 percent. The rates for three-month
bills were the lowest since they averaged 7.97 percent on Nov. 21.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.32 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,796.80 and 8.73 percent for six-month bills selling for $9,582.90.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making
changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, rose to 8.75 percent last
week after averaging 8.71 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
