<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 0134EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SteelImports Bjt   12-06 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steel Imports, Bjt,0772</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Importers Brace For Renewed Steel Quotas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. steel import quotas have outlived their
purpose, but because American producers likely will win extended
protection, the restraints should be made less burdensome to
steel-using manufacturers, say steel traders and a former U.S. trade
official.
   ``Advocates of an efficient economy are set to lose one more
battle to champions of protection,'' said Gary Hufbauer, Georgetown
University professor of financial diplomacy and former deputy
assistant U.S. Treasury secretary for trade and investment policy.
   President-elect George Bush, in a letter written late in the
presidential campaign, offered to renew the 5-year Voluntary
Restraint Agreements instituted by President Reagan.
   Bush's offer came ``at a time when economic factors say enough is
enough. Domestic steel mills are running at 90 percent of capacity,
the industry should earn $2 billion in 1988, and many steel products
are scarce,'' Hufbauer said in a speech Monday night to members of
the American Institute for Imported Steel.
   Earlier Monday, AIIS officials said that if the VRAs must be
extended past their September expiration they should be modified to
prevent a repeat of the steel shortages and sharp price increases
that occurred with some products within the last two years.
   ``We're trying to be realistic,'' newly elected AIIS President
John Griffin said following a Monday morning news conference.
   The more than 30 product quotas prevented foreign producers from
shipping additional steel plate for factory floors and bridge decks,
for example, when U.S. producers could not meet demand, he said.
   ``We've seen projects where they leave holes in the deck because
you can't get plate,'' said Griffin, who is also president of the
Houston steel trader Maurice Pincoffs Co.
   Domestic steel companies contend they still need protection as
the U.S. industry restructures and they deny that natural market
forces, not the VRAs, caused modest price increases and temporary
tightness, not shortages, for some products.
   The VRAs have cost U.S. steel users $7 billion annually in higher
material costs and lost business due to shortages, Hufbauer said.
   ``Steel users have paid their dues for many years,'' he said,
referring to steel trade restraints employed in various forms since
the late 1960s.
   ``The industry has been insulated from imports for so long that
it has become thoroughly addicted,'' Hufbauer said.
   The U.S. companies say only a renewal of the quotas will check
predatory trade practices and allow time to continue the turnaround
that has brought the domestic industry profits of $3.25 billion in
the last seven quarters after losses of $12 billion over the
preceding five years. They accuse foreign producers of selling their
metal at prices set below production costs and of underwriting
operations with government grants.
   ``The fundamental problem in the steel industry has never been
unfair practices abroad,'' Hufbauer said. ``The fundamental problem
was that the U.S. industry became in the 1970s woefully
uncompetitive by comparison with efficient foreign producers. The
industry was overstaffed, and its technology was outmoded.''
   He said that during tough times U.S. producers use the same
pricing strategies they condemn in their foreign competitors.
   ``If U.S. steel producers were put to the test of U.S. trade
laws, most would be found guilty during bad times of unfair trade
practices right within the American market,'' Hufbauer said.
   Nonetheless, modified VRAs are preferable to the expense and
uncertainty of massive trade lawsuits from the U.S. industry, said
the New York-based importers association, the Texas Association of
Steel Importers and the West Coast Metal Importers Association.
   Fred Lamesch, a past president of the importers' association,
said none of the top steel-exporting nations have granted any steel
production subsidies for several years. The only subsidies still
available to European producers are those that help pay employee
benefits when plants close, he said.
   ``The French say America has the biggest subsidy by being able to
give pink slips to workers on Friday and say `Don't come back on
Monday,''' said Hans Mueller, an economics professor at Middle
Tennessee State University who is a consultant for the importers
group.
   ``Most of the subsidies are optical illusions,'' Mueller said.
``We see subsidies in anything different than what we do.''
   U.S. steel users already are complaining that the domestic steel
industry seems too prosperous to be demanding further trade
protection.
   Those demanding changes or abandonment of the quotas include the
Precision Metal Forming Association, the Steel Service Center
Institute, the Forging Industry Association, and heavy equipment
manufacturers Caterpillar Inc. and Deere & Co.

</TEXT>
