<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AutoSales Bjt   12-06 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Made Vehicles Up, Imports Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stronger-than-expected showing by General Motors
Corp. pushed late November sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks
up 3.6 percent this year compared with last year.
   U.S. automakers said Monday they sold 326,744 vehicles during the
Nov. 21-30 period, compared with 275,929 the same time last year.
   But sales of imported cars and light trucks fell 10.1 percent to
282,631 late last month, compared with 301,715 last year.
   Percentages are based on daily sales rates, rather than straight
comparisons of 1988 and 1987 figures. There were eight selling days
during the late November period this year and seven last year.
   GM paced U.S. automakers with a 17 percent rise in its late
November car sales, going to 103,137 this year from 77,118 during
the period last year. Ford Motor Co.'s car sales fell 18.7 percent
to 51,424 during late November from 55,374 last year.
   Chrysler Corp.'s car sales slipped 3.6 percent in late November,
based on a daily selling rate, going to 26,863, compared with 24,372
last year.
   The increase at GM and the decline at Ford came, in part, because
of sales patterns during late November last year.
   ``They (sales) were stronger than I expected in late November
only because of a surge in sales by GM,'' said analyst David Healy
of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   ``GM a year ago had an unusually low market share, so the 17
percent increase in their selling rate was helped by a unusually
large market share this year and an unusually small one last year,''
Healy said.
   ``This period last year was very weak for GM,'' agreed analyst
Jeannette Garretty of the Bank of America in San Francisco. ``And
this time was when people were making a lot of hay about Ford taking
market share (from GM).
   ``These kind of numbers are not too surprising. I don't think
this means that GM is the hot manufacturer this year and Ford is
not.''
   For the month, GM's car sales rose 14.1 percent, compared with
Ford's decline of 0.5 percent and Chrysler's 1.2 percent increase.
   Among the imports, trucks showed a 19.8 percent decrease in sales
during the month, and sales of cars fell 7.9 percent.
   ``Perhaps one of the real interesting things is that imports are
down so much,'' Garretty said, adding that the monetary exchange
rate and a shift of some manufacturing to the United States by
Japanese companies were among the reasons for the depressed sales
figures.
   ``There is a price effect and the other thing is that in this
model year, there isn't a whole lot that is rip-roaringly new (among
imports) out there,'' she added. ``Imports probably will continue to
stay down.''
</TEXT>
