<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Economy     12-06 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Economy,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Adjusted GNP Grows 9.3 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's economy grew at an annual rate of 9.3
percent in the July-September quarter due to strength in private
investment and exports, the government reported Tuesday.
   The Economic Planning Agency said the brisk growth in the gross
national product during the second fiscal quarter represents a
significant rebound of the country's economy from an annualized
3.9-percent fall in GNP the previous quarter.
   That decline had reflected sluggish external demand and sagging
housing investment.
   The unexpectedly high growth in exports, however, is raising
concern the direction of the country's economy may be turing once
again to a more export-dependent structure, said government
officials, requesting anonymity.
   The government had set a preliminary target of GNP growth at 3.8
percent for fiscal 1988 ending next March. Most economists
anticipated the growth of adjusted GNP will remain at between 6
percent and 8 percent for the third quarter.
   The annual rate of 9.3 percent, which translates into an adjusted
growth of 2.2 percent from the April-June quarter, suggests the
government's growth target is well within reach, the officials said.
   Officials said brisk personal spending, capital equipment and
housing investment spurred the brisk domestic demand.
   ``The domestic category is taking good form. They are hard
figures,'' said an EPA official.
   A strong 1.5-percent increase in quarter-to-quarter exports,
compared to a 0.7-percent decline in the last quarter, led to
0.4-percent increase in external demand, the officials said.
   Meanwhile, quarter-to-quarter imports declined by 1.1 percent
from the April-June period, largely due to the higher value of the
yen against the dollar.
   EPA officials said the unexpectely higher third quarter figures
seemed to be in part a reaction to the negative growth of the
previous quarter, but the nation's economic growth recovered to a
stable stage.
   ``A renewed increase in exports reflected worldwide economic
expansion, supported by robust private-sector capital spending
centering on the United States, Western Europe and Asian developing
countries,'' Kyodo News Service quoted a senior agency official as
saying.
   Takashi Saito, general managing director of Fuji Bank's research
division, described the annualized growth figure as ``a little
stronger than expected.''
   He said the figure confirms Japan's business conditions are
continuing to expand in the wake of contractions recorded in the
previous quarter.
   ``We feared a downturn in economic liveliness based on the last
quarterly numbers,'' he said.
   He also said the growth in exports raised concerns about the
direction of currency rates and U.S. efforts to reduce its trade
deficit with Japan.
</TEXT>
