<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Mixed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures were mixed in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting new optimism
about wheat exports and continuing concerns about the South American
soybean weather.
   After a lower opening across the board, wheat prices turned
higher while corn, oats and soybeans firmed slightly to trade near
Monday's settlement prices.
   The Agriculture Department said in a report issued late Monday
wheat export inspections last week totaled 28.9 million bushels,
considerably more than the 20 million to 24 million bushels the
trade had expected.
   Pressure on soybean prices stemmed from reports of rain in the
soybean-growing region of Argentina and forecasts for rain in
Brazil, where soybean planting also is under way.
   But Walter Spilka, an analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &
Co. in New York, said the weather forecasts were sketchy and soybean
trading activity was light.
   ``The market's really just treading water,'' he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents to 2\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.15} a bushel; corn was {
cent lower to 1 cent higher with December at $2.52 a bushel; oats
were { cent lower to } cent higher with March at $2.04{ a bushel;
soybeans were { cent lower to 5 cents higher with January unchanged
at $7.56} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent to .52 cent higher with December at
71.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .25 cent higher
with January at 82.77 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower to .25
cent higher with December at 41.02 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .10 cent lower to .38 cent higher with February at
45.60 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Monday while pork futures were
higher.
</TEXT>
