<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1154EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-RustyJones     12-06 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rusty Jones,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rusty Jones Seeks Protection from Creditors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rusty Jones Inc. has filed for protection from
creditors in U.S. Bankruptcy Court, saying its car-rustproofing
business had deteriorated as U.S. automakers extended their own
rust-through warranties.
   The filing Monday under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code
seeks time for the beleaguered Chicago-based company to reorganize.
   Rusty Jones' warranty program remains in effect for cars
initially treated before Aug. 1, but claims brought by car owners
will become part of the bankruptcy proceedings, said President
Charles Wortman.
   Claims by auto owners could reach $25 million, Wortman said.
   Since 1985, Rusty Jones has seen its distribution network dwindle
from 3,000 new-car dealerships in the Northeast, Midwest and Florida
to about 1,800, Wortman said in a telephone interview.
   Rusty Jones is a rustproofing product sold by new-car dealers.
The company guarantees treated cars against rust perforation for as
long as the original buyer owns the car.
   ``It ran into trouble basically when the major (car)
manufacturers went ahead and extended the rust protection they
offered consumers to 6-year, 60,000 miles; 7-year, 70,000 miles;
some even have 100,000-mile warranties,'' Wortman said.
   The extended manufacturer warranties discouraged consumers from
purchasing additional rust protection, Wortman said, ``and if he
didn't buy the rust protection, he wouldn't buy the (Rusty Jones)
gloss protection or fabric protection.''
   Rusty Jones announced on Aug. 1 it would no longer offer
warranties with its rustproofing product. Last week, the company
laid off about 90 employees, which represented nearly its entire
workforce.
   ``In our view, the company's viability can only be restored by a
complete reorganization in a Chapter 11 proceeding,'' Wortman said.
``Our goal is to preserve the value of the company and to protect
the interests of claimants and potential claimants.''
   Wortman is a shareholder in Rustco Inc., which purchased Rusty
Jones on Nov. 23 from BCI Consumer Products Corp. and Michael Mater,
former president of Rusty Jones. Rustco's other shareholder is
Renaissance Holdings Inc., a subsidiary of Renaissance Capital Ltd.,
which is headed by bankruptcy specialist Alexander Knopfler.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881206-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1226EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     12-06 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0303</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue-chip stocks extended Monday's gains today,
but the rest of the market lagged behind in a quiet session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 31.48 points on
Monday, rose another 6.40 to 2,130.16 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 8 to 7 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 578 up, 656 down and
583 unchanged.
   The market's latest upswing has been attributed partly to a new
restructuring tactic announced by four large companies Monday and
reported to be under consideration by several others.
   The deals involve the proposed swap of ``unbundled stock units,''
or packages of three different types of securities, for large
amounts of their outstanding common shares.
   The idea drew mixed reviews from analysts and accountants, some
of whom criticized it as a gimmick.
   However some investors evidently saw it as a potential boost to
the values put on companies by the marketplace.
   Long Island Lighting led the active list, down 1] at 12] on
turnover of more than 4.4 million shares. On Monday a jury found the
company guilty of fraud in the process of obtaining rate increases
relating to its Shoreham nuclear power plant.
   Rorer Group rose 1~ to 47. The company said it couldn't explain
the activity, and declined comment on a report that Beecham Group of
London might be interested in acquiring it.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up .11 to 154.59. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .01 at 296.76.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 64.15 million shares at noontime,
down from 73.39 million at the same point Monday.
</TEXT>
