<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1238EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-KellyServices Adv10-11   12-06 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kelly Services, Adv 10-11,0845</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 10</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 10-11 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Kelly Services Follows Slow, Steady Course</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGELA AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the age of megabuck mergers and massive
debt restructurings, Kelly Services Inc. thinks there's something to
be said for a healthy bottom line.
   While the 6-year-old economic recovery has produced a boom in
temporary services, Kelly has stuck with a low-key, fiscally
conservative style, achieving record sales and earnings all three
quarters this year.
   ``Conservatism makes Kelly stand out a little bit,'' said Sam
Sacco, executive vice president of the National Association of
Temporary Services, a trade association.
   ``The industry is filled with entrepreneurs and risk takers,''
Sacco said. ``Kelly's developed more on a careful, well-plotted
basis.''
   That conservative strategy has made the company a world leader in
temp services with more than 550,000 temporary and 3,800 full-time
employees on the global payroll.
   Net earnings for the third quarter this year jumped 19 percent
from the same period in 1987, to $18.3 million. That came on sales
of $336 million, an 11 percent increase from the year-ago period.
   The company reported 1987 earnings of $50.5 million on sales of
$1.16 billion.
   But despite its obvious success, Kelly's growth is actually
moderating, compared with other major players in the temp industry.
   The industry has grown 18 percent to 20 percent each of the last
two years, said industry analyst Jerry Levine of Merrill Lynch & Co.
in New York. Kelly's revenues, by comparison, have increased about
13 percent a year during that period.
   As in other industries, acquisitions are fueling much of the
growth among Kelly's competitors.
   Manpower Inc., which posted net earnings of $31.1 million on $2.5
billion in sales in 1987, was acquired in September 1987 by Blue
Arrow PLC, a London-based temporary services company.
   Other national temporary service companies, such as Adia
Personnel Services, Inc., and the Olsten Corp., have been expanding
through acquisitions.
   Not Kelly. The acquisition of four small companies in Australia
to establish Kelly branches there this year was a first, according
to Terence E. Adderly, Kelly's president and chief executive officer.
   Kelly also has branches in Canada, Puerto Rico, England, Ireland,
Scotland, Wales and France.
   The company's growth has been driven by the basic laws of supply
and demand.
   Strong growth in the economy during the long expansion has
boosted demand for temps and allowed Kelly to raise rates at a
faster pace than its payroll costs are increasing, a recent analysis
in the Value Line Investment Survey said.
   Cost containment measures also have helped by keeping operating
costs from growing as fast as sales.
   ``Their financial strength is the strongest in the industry,''
said analyst Levine of Merrill Lynch. ``They have an almost
unbelievable amount of cash. It's a most liquid company with cash
flow.''
   Kelly's 1987 annual report showed assets of $232 million, $68.4
million of that cash, and liabilities of $77.6 million.
   Value Line said the company's financial muscle could ``easily
support a large-scale acquisition, a stepped-up expansion program or
a share repurchase program.''
   But the company won't disclose its plans for all its capital.
William Russell Kelly, an industry pioneer who founded the business
in 1946, is chairman of the board and also owner of 80 percent of
the controlling stock.
   A slowdown in new job creation may be biggest threat to Kelly's
future growth. Value Line said the company is likely to achieve 13
percent growth this year, but weaker economic conditions could cut
the rate to 10 percent in 1989.
   Kelly is fighting back with aggressive training and recruiting
programs.
   In the office clerical area, the company believes it has been at
the forefront in adapting to changes brought about by office
automation.
   ``We've trained over 1 million people in the last 10 years on
word processing, and are currently training 250,000 people a year,''
Adderly said of the free service.
   ``We had to take on a training role because of the amount of
people needed to fill jobs,'' said P. Jeffrey Sheak, regional
manager in the Detroit area. ``We haven't been able to recruit them
all.''
   In addition to job fairs and visits to universities and shopping
malls, Kelly is recruiting older people in an effort to expand the
labor pool with experienced former workers.
   The company's Encore program, launched last year, targets workers
age 55 and older, and the age group now comprises 10 percent of
Kelly's temporary work force, compared with 7 percent to 8 percent
in 1987.
   Kelly's greatest asset of all may be its name recognition. Though
company officials say they think the term ``Kelly Girl'' is
outdated, it still appears in newspaper classified ads.
   ``They're like Kleenex of the tissue business. The name is
synonymous with temporary help,'' Sacco said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 10-11</NOTE>
