<DOCNO> AP881206-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1338EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MotorOil     12-06 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Motor Oil,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sun Canning The Can In Favor Of Bottle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sun Refining & Marketing Co. is bowing to
consumer desires and canning the can _ the one-quart can of motor
oil, that is.
   From now on, Sunoco brand oil in quart sizes will be available
only in resealable plastic bottles.
   B.D. Weaver, manager of packaging and warehousing for Sun in
Tulsa, said the bottles have almost entirely replaced the
once-familiar cardboard cans with the metal top and bottom.
   ``It's entirely consumer driven,'' he said. ``We're a company
which holds the customer to be a primary concern, and the plastic
resealable bottle is what the people want.''
   Sun blends and packages lubricants for several other companies in
addition to its Sunoco brand.
   The company reported it filled 11.2 million gallons of oil in the
traditional can in 1985. But the next year, that number was nearly
halved to 6.6 million gallons, while another 1.6 million gallons
went into bottles.
   Last year, Sun marketed 10.7 million gallons in bottles and 1.4
million gallons in cans. And in the first 10 months of 1988, Sun
packaged 9.1 million gallons in bottles and only 375,000 in cans.
   Quart bottles comprise about 50 percent of Sun's packaging
business. The other half is marketed in drums, five-gallon pails and
jugs of various sizes. It also ships lubricants by truck and rail
car.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
