<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1518EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-06 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grains, Soybeans Higher on Buying by Single Trading Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were sharply
higher Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as the markets finished
a roller-coaster ride on the upside in the wake of activity by a
single large trading company.
   Iowa Grain Co., a Chicago-based speculative trading firm,
triggered a sharp dip in grain and soybean prices just one day
earlier by leading a sell-off.
   But Tuesday, the company bought soybeans early, setting off a
rally as traders followed the move. Iowa Grain then turned around
and sold beans, but after prices broke, reversed positions again and
started buying.
   ``And away we went,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean
Witter Reynolds in Chicago.
   Iowa Grain also bought wheat, setting off a rally in that pit.
   ``Iowa was so active, it overshadowed (concerns about) the
weather in South America,'' Lespinasse added. ``What would otherwise
have been a dull market turned lively, and the traders followed Iowa
because they were calling the tune.''
   There had been pressure on soybean prices because of reports of
rain in the soybean-growing region of Argentina and forecasts for
rain in Brazil, where soybean planting also is under way.
   On the close, wheat was 4 cents to 8{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.19 a bushel; corn was 2{
cents to 5} cents higher with December at $2.58\ a bushel; oats were
3{ cents to 7\ cents higher with March at $1.98\ a bushel; soybeans
were 14 cents to 16 cents higher with January at $7.72 a bushel.
</TEXT>
