<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1950EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TruffleWater     12-06 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Truffle Water,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Truffle-Flavored Mineral Water Receives Mixed Reactions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ``Georg'' in last graf cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reactions ranged from ``terrible'' to
``fresh'' at the unveiling of a mineral water flavored with
truffles, the subterranean fungi famed as the world's most expensive
food ingredient.
   ``Very few connoisseurs know what truffles really taste like,''
commented restaurateur Fritz Castel as the Mendocino Beverage Co.
unveiled a limited marketing of mineral water flavored with the
highly aromatic essence of France's $500-a-pound perigord truffles.
   The main fame of the fungi, which are available only a few months
of the year, comes from the way they are harvested: by trained pigs
and dogs that sniff out the delicacy where it grows at the base of
certain trees in France and Italy, and lately in the Northern
California and Oregon forests.
   The 10-ounce bottle of flavored water is priced at $4 and is to
be sold, for now, only in the gourmet department of the Neiman
Marcus department store here. A three-liter bottle of the water was
auctioned for $950 last summer at the Sonoma Valley Wine Auction.
   Without the truffle juice, a 10-ounce bottle of the water costs
50 cents.
   ``That's terrible,'' a wine writer remarked at Friday's unveiling
to a food writer, who thought, ``Hmmm, it's very fresh and unusual.
I don't know if it will sell.''
   When a New York Times writer reviewed the drink, the headline on
the column said, ``Earthiness That Should Have Stayed In The Earth.''
   ``It has a certain earthiness,'' said one participant at the
tasting. Another thought it was an interesting way to find out what
all the truffle fuss is about.
   Chefs throughout the world fight each other each winter and
spring for a few ounces of truffles. They are used to flavor and
lend a distinctive aroma to the most special dishes. A single
truffle can flavor gallons of food.
   ``It's something special,'' said Mendocino Beverage's owner,
Georg Moller-Racke, who commissioned restaurateur John Ashe to
formulate the drink. Moller-Racke touted the truffle water as an
upscale alterative for people who don't drink alcohol but want a
special touch in their bottled water.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881206-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1953EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SummitChef     12-06 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit Chef,0440</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Reagan's Meeting Gorbachev? Where Are They Eating?
^By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When John Patrick Doherty first read about this
week's Reagan-Gorbachev meeting, his thoughts quickly shifted to one
major issue _ what were they doing for lunch?
   ``I was wondering if they planned to meet at the Waldorf,''
confessed Doherty, the head chef at the Manhattan luxury hotel and
creator of the meal the two world leaders will share Wednesday.
   ``Last Wednesday, they asked me if I would be interested. I
submitted three menus for approval. ... They chose one on Friday,''
said Doherty, a Waldorf chef for the past 11 years. ``It was great.
I was very happy.''
   Cooking for President Reagan and Mikhail Gorbachev is no
different from preparing any other meal _ except for the presence of
Secret Service agents in the kitchen, Doherty said Tuesday between
samples of the wild mushroom ravioli which will start the summit
lunch.
   ``As much attention and care as I'm giving this, you have to do
that with everything,'' said Doherty, who became head chef 3{ years
ago. ``You don't get a reputation for quality cooking, as a quality
chef, by being supercreative. The truly good chefs, the quality of
their preparation is top-notch.''
   Initially, the White House had declared the luncheon menu
off-limits to the news media until after the meal. But the
restrictions were eased enough for Doherty to provide some word on
what would be served.
   First will come a chicken consomme and the wild mushroom ravioli,
followed by tournedos or rounded filets of veal with smoked quail
and lobster sausage, braised cabbage and leeks, roesti potatoes that
are julienned and sauteed until crisp, and sauteed fresh leaf
spinach.
   Wine will be a California chardonnay. Dessert is a chocolate tart
with almond cream cheese, fresh fruit and raspberry sauce.
   Total preparation time for the lunch for 14 people will be about
four hours, said Doherty, who was being assisted by two other
Waldorf chefs. Final touches will be made at Governors Island, the
historic fort and Coast Guard complex in New York Harbor where the
luncheon will be held.
   Since Reagan generally stays at the Waldorf-Astoria when in New
York, it will not be the first time Doherty, 30, has prepared a
presidential repast. And Reagan has twice personally complimented
him on his cooking, the chef said.
   ``This style of cooking is what he prefers,'' Doherty said of the
president. ``There are some guidelines for keeping his health in
mind. ... But I've done this many times.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
