<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0236</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pushed ahead for the second straight
session today, following the lead of a very strong government bond
market.
   Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the opposite
direction from interest rates, climbed about $20 for each $1,000 in
face value today.
   Analysts said bonds were buoyed by hopes that Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev, who arrived in the United States this afternoon,
would make proposals that would allow cutbacks in defense spending.
   Under the reasoning that seemed to prevail in the markets, that
would in turn reduce inflationary pressures and help the United
States deal with its budget deficit.
   Most of the stock market's gains came late in the session on a
wave of computer program trading by professionals.
   The market's latest upswing has also been attributed partly to a
new restructuring tactic announced by four large companies Monday
and reported to be under consideration by several others.
   The deals involve the proposed swap of ``unbundled stock units,''
or packages of three different types of securities, for large
amounts of their outstanding common shares.
   The idea drew mixed reviews from analysts and accountants, some
of whom criticized it as a gimmick.
   However some investors evidently saw it as a potential boost to
the values put on companies by the marketplace.
