<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TradeTalks-Japan     12-06 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade Talks-Japan,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Keeps Low Profile In Trade Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan has been keeping a low profile in a
critical round of international trade talks here, in contrast with
its prowess as a global trader.
   Japan, which enjoys the biggest trade surplus in the world, is
one of 100 countries taking part in talks on liberalizing and
updating the 40-year-old General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   But among the dozens of position papers floating around the halls
of Montreal's convention center, few have been Japan's. And Japanese
officials have been elusive.
   Unlike the United States, the European Economic Community, host
nation Canada, and such countries as India, Japan has not briefed
reporters once on its positions over the past four days of talks.
   The only scheduled Japanese briefing was canceled, because the
person who was supposed to conduct the session was busy.
   In contrast to the growing leadership position Japan has been
assuming on the world monetary and financial front, it continues to
be highly sensitive on trade.
   On the most divisive point in the negotiations _ the battle
between the United States and the 12-nation EEC on agricultural
subsidies, Japan has been on the sidelines.
   As the chief EEC negotiator Willy de Clercq put it, ``the
Japanese have been sitting back and looking at this like a pingpong
game between us and the Americans.''
   The debate, which has divided the allegiances of other nations,
concerns a U.S. demand for eliminaton of trade-distorting farm
supports, which the Europeans reject out of hand.
   Although Japan is the world's biggest importer of agricultural
products, it appears more than happy to let the two slug it out.
   ``Our position is that there is no point in making decisions
until they settle,'' said Mutsuyoshi Nishimura, Japan's director of
foreign press relations.
   Nishimura said that whatever the outcome, Japan's prime concern
is the protection of its rice market against foreign imports.
   The United States, seeking support for its position in the GATT
talks, has promised to take into account the concerns of other
countries over ``food security.''
   Translated, this means allowing other countries to stockpile
emergency food supplies.
   But Nishimura said Japan was still not clear whether the U.S.
promise would guarantee Japan the right to limit imports of rice.
   ``We have a vulnerable sector of rice farmers, and they are a
very strong constituency,'' he said in an interview. ``We must step
gingerly.''
   Underscoring the political sensitivity of the issue, Japan's
ruling Liberal Democratic Party sent a delegation to the Montreal
talks to make sure the professional negotiators did not cave in to
pressure.
   Japan has been particularly concerned at threats that the United
States would use a new trade bill to retaliate against its closed
rice import policies.
   But the United States and Japan appear to have reached a tacit
understanding that the Americans would not push the rice issue in
Montreal if the Japanese agreed to leave it on the table for future
talks.
   Conscious of its international commitment to assume broader
leadership in the world commensurate with its economic power, Japan
adopted a package in Montreal that reduces tariffs on exports by
developing nations to the industrialized world.
   Under the agreement, Japan will reduce tariffs on the import of
some 180 tropical products, worth about $3 billion in annual
imports, Nishimura said.
   But rice was kept out of that package, much to Japan's relief.
   ``The Japanese aren't willing to stick their necks out like we
are or even the United States,'' said one European official.
   But Nishimura disagreed with that assessment, saying Japan's low
profile was a reflection of ``national character.''
   ``We may not be as articulate as some, but we are as assertive as
we need to be,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
