<DOCNO> AP881206-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1648EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RobinsAppeal     12-06 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robins Appeal,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Argues That Women Disenfranchised By Not Having Votes
Weighted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for Dalkon Shield claimants said
Tuesday that the process by which the A.H. Robins Co. Inc.
bankruptcy plan was approved effectively disenfranchised women with
the largest injury claims.
   A three-judge panel of the 4th Circuit Court of Appeals heard
arguments challenging the reorganization plan, which includes a $2.5
billion trust fund for women injured by the Robins-manufactured
Dalkon Shield birth control device. A ruling is not expected for
several months.
   Alan B. Morrison, a lawyer for the Public Citizen Litigation
Group in Washington, D.C., argued that confirmation of the plan was
invalid because claimants were not given a range of possible
monetary awards when they voted to approve it and because their
votes were not weighted.
   Morrison criticized the ``unexplained and unjustified refusal''
of U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige, who approved the plan in
July, to break down the $2.5 billion figure. Instead, he said,
claimants were simply told they would be paid in full, with no
explanation of what that meant.
   ``The only logical reason he didn't break out the numbers is
because they wouldn't stand up,'' Morrison told the judges.
   He said the vote, in which more than 95 percent of the claimants
returning ballots voted in favor of the plan, might have come out
differently if women with larger claims had been given weighted
votes. The bankruptcy code requires that creditors' votes be
weighted according to the size of their claims, Morrison said.
   ``That in effect disenfranchised those with large claims,''
Morrison said.
   But James C. Roberts, an attorney for Robins, said weighting the
votes would have been time-consuming and impractical. Merhige
``tried mightily'' to come up with a system of weighted voting, but
was unable to, Roberts said. If the value of claims had to be
estimated in advance so that votes could be weighted, ``the job
would never be done,'' he said.
   Roberts said Merhige based the $2.5 billion figure on expert
testimony at an estimation hearing last year. Claimants had ``more
information than the law required'' about possible award amounts, he
said.
   Morrison also challenged a provision of the bankruptcy plan that
prevents claimants from filing suit against doctors, Robins
officers, law firms and other third parties in the case. He said
third parties are not entitled to bankruptcy protection without
filing for bankruptcy, and claimants should be allowed to sue them
to recover full damages.
   The appellate panel also heard challenges to a settlement with
Aetna Casualty & Surety Co., Robins' insurer, and to Merhige's
authority over the claim fund trustees.
   Close to 200,000 women have filed claims of Dalkon Shield-related
injuries ranging from infections to sterility, miscarriage, and
children born with birth defects. The bulk of those claims cannot be
settled until appeals to the reorganization plan are exhausted.
   Robins filed for bankruptcy in August 1985 after thousands of
women filed suit against the company. The reorganization plan
provides for the Richmond pharmaceutical company to be acquired by
American Home Products Corp. of New York in a $700 million exchange
of stock. American Home can back out of the plan if appeals are not
settled by next July.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881206-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 1718EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-IMFReport     12-06 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IMF Report,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>G-7 Growth Highest Since Early '70s, IMF Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In what would be the fastest growth since the
early 1970s, the International Monetary Fund said it expects the
economies of the seven biggest industrial nations to expand 4.25
percent this year.
   Michel Camdessus, director general of the IMF, announced the
upward revision in the output of goods and services, from 4.0
percent, as he said the rapid growth created a ``golden
opportunity'' for the industrialized nations to open their markets
to each other and to developing nations.
   ``We are now in a good growth period,'' Camdessus told reporters
late Monday in advance of a speech Tuesday at free-trade talks under
auspices of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   The group of seven countries covered by the IMF forecast are the
United States, Japan, Britain, France, West Germany, Italy and
Canada.
   The IMF has steadily raised its forecast for growth in the seven
countries, from 3.25 percent to 3.8 percent to 4 percent and now
4.25 percent. The actual growth for this year will not be known
until sometime in 1989.
   On inflation, the IMF is keeping its most recent forecast of an
inflation rate of 3.2 percent in the seven countries this year,
Camdessus said.
   In spite of the healthy growth, Camdessus said he was concerned
by evidence of an increase in non-tariff barriers to world trade
among a broader range of industrialized nations.
   According to a new IMF report, the industrial countries made more
restrictive changes in trade policy last year than liberalizing
changes, 85 to 66.
   In contrast, the report said, developing countries made more
liberalizing changes than restrictive ones, 227 to 126.
   Protectionism in industrialized nations hampers the ability of
developing nations to grow through exports and deal with their
crushing debt burdens.
   The new IMF report has other ammunition for free traders. Quoting
from a United Nations report, it said 23 percent of the imports of
developed countries aside from fuel were subject to non-tariff
measures last year, up from 19 percent in 1981.
   Worldwide, farm supports cost consumers and taxpayers an average
of $185 billion a year in 1984 through 1986, the report said,
quoting the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.
   The International Monetary Fund was created after World War II to
tide over countries that faced short-term debt crises and to promote
world trade. It is now closely involved in the affairs of many
heavily indebted developing countries.
   Camdessus said he welcomed the plans of the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade to monitor more closely the adherence of all
nations to free-trade principles. That surveillance would parallel
the surveillance that the IMF already does of countries' debt
servicing and commitment to growth-oriented policies.
   Many developing nations, already irked by the IMF's involvement
in their domestic affairs, are concerned that the GATT will become
another meddling hand.
   The IMF report said that since free trade helps all countries
involved in it, ``it does not make economic sense to delay
unilateral measures to obtain multilateral liberalization.''
   In his briefing to reporters, Camdessus said it would be
``suicidal'' for nations to insist that progress in other areas of
free trade be linked to progress on their own particular issues.
   ``Unless we press forward, the risk is that we shall move
backward,'' he said in the text of his speech.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881206-0247 </DOCNO>
