<HEAD>Pork Bellies Limit-Down on Oversupply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pork futures prices plunged to limit-down levels Tuesday after a
late sell-off by traders worried that frozen pork bellies are piling
up at already overstocked warehouses.
   On other markets, treasury bond futures soared on rumors that
improving superpower relations _ exemplified by Soviet President
Mikhail Gorbachev's visit _ may ultimately mean lower U.S. defense
spending level and a meaningful cut in the budget deficit; grain and
soybeans futures prices finished sharply higher in the wake of one
trading firm's day-long trading machinations; and platinum futures
posted an impressive gain as gold and silver slipped slightly.
   ``We had quite a sell-off,'' said Chuck Levitt of Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc., Chicago. ``But then, the pork complex has been like
water running upstream the last couple of sessions.''
   Levitt said generally good underlying cash prices for the pork
bellies at this time of year led many traders to view the futures
market as undervalued.
   ``But every Tuesday we get a report on warehouse supplies ... on
how much product is actually pouring into storage and we get some
liquidation. In this situation,'' he added, ``no one was around to
stick up for the markets.''
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange's out-of-town warehouse report,
released after the close of trading Tuesday, was even more bearish
than most traders expected. Stocks in 48 approved warehouses, which
represent the majority of bellies in storage nationwide, showed a
net gain of 7.2 million pounds over the previous week.
   At the Merc, live cattle settled .08 cent lower to .05 cent
higher, with the contrtact for delivery in December at 71.37 cents a
pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .35 cent lower, with January
at 82.25 cents a pound; hogs were .55 cent lower to .05 cent higher,
with December at 40.62 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were
1.32 cents to a limit-down 2 cents lower, with February at 43.57
cents a pound.
   Treasury bond futures went in the opposite direction at the
Chicago Board of Trade, settling 1 22@32 to 1 23@32 higher, with
December at 89 22@32.
   ``The dollar strengthened, but that was an incredibly strong move
in T-bonds with no real economic news,'' said Rich Sandor of Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc., Chicago.
   ``The rumors have it that Gorbachev will propose a unilateral
troop reduction, that he didn't come a couple thousand miles just to
have lunch. The market read that to mean there's the real potential
for lowered defense spending ... and a real move on lowering the
deficit not that far down the road.''
   Grain and soybean futures prices finished a day-long
roller-coaster ride on the upside at the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Iowa Grain Co., a Chicago-based speculative trading firm,
triggered a sharp dip in grain and soybean prices just one day
earlier by leading a sell-off.
   But Tuesday, the company bought soybeans early, setting off a
rally as traders followed the move. Iowa Grain then turned around
and sold beans, but after prices broke, reversed positions again and
started buying.
   Iowa Grain also bought wheat, setting off a rally in that pit.
   ``What would otherwise have been a dull market turned lively, and
the traders followed Iowa because they were calling the tune,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds in Chicago.
   On the close, wheat was 4 cents to 8{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.19 a bushel; corn was 2{
cents to 5} cents higher with December at $2.58\ a bushel; oats were
3{ cents to 7\ cents higher with March at $1.98\ a bushel; soybeans
were 14 cents to 16 cents higher with January at $7.72 a bushel.
   Platinum closed 30 cents lower to $6.70 higher, with the December
contract at the New York Mercantile Exchange at $611.80 a troy
ounce. Gold, meanwhile, was $1.60 to $1.80 lower, with December at
$427.50 a troy ounce, and silver was 2 cents to 9 cents lower, with
the December conbtrract at the Comex at 616.1 cents a troy ounce.
   ``Gold and silver are retreating because of the strength of the
dollar and the bond market's performance,'' said Jack Barbanel,
director of futures trading for Gruntal & Co., New York.
   ``But platinum has a life of its own ... because of the demand
for the actual commodity.''
</TEXT>
