<2ND_LINE>AM-Manpower Execs,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fromstein Resigns as Manpower Inc. President, CEO</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Antony in 2nd graf is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue Arrow PLC said Tuesday that Mitchell S.
Fromstein had resigned by mutual consent as president and chief
executive of its Manpower Inc. subsidiary, the world's largest
employment services concern.
   The London-based company said the 60-year-old Fromstein would be
replaced as chief executive by Antony G. Berry, Blue Arrow's
chairman and chief executive, and as president by William F. Markey
Jr., who had been chief executive of Blue Arrow's non-Manpower
operations in the United States.
   Blue Arrow acquired the Milwaukee-based Manpower in September
1987 for $1.3 billion, and kept Fromstein on to lead the subsidiary.
   Fromstein had been president and chief executive of Manpower
since 1976.
   David E. Atkins, deputy chairman of Blue Arrow, said the Blue
Arrow board and Fromstein ``ended up having irreconcilable
differences over how the group should be run'' and came to a mutual
agreement that Fromstein should resign.
   Atkins said the board wanted to blend some of the back office
operations of the parent company with those of Manpower but said
Fromstein ``was resistant to those changes.''
   A call was placed to Fromstein at the Milwaukee office, but he
was said to be traveling and was unavailable for comment.
   Atkins said no layoffs were planned and that Blue Arrow intended
to maintain Manpower's headquarters in Milwaukee. ``It may well
benefit from additional functions,'' he said.
   Markey, 49, has previously been a marketing executive with
General Foods and later founded Positions Inc., an employment search
firm that Blue Arrow acquired in 1986.
   Blue Arrow has 1,900 branches serving more than 300,000 clients
in 33 different countries. It expects to place more than 1.4 million
people this year in temporary and permanent positions in offices,
industry and marketing services.
</TEXT>
