<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Gannett-Curley     12-06 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gannett-Curley,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Curley Succeeding Neuharth as Gannett Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John J. Curley, president and chief executive
officer of Gannett Co. Inc., will also take on the post of chairman
of the nationwide news and information company when Allen H.
Neuharth retires next March 31.
   Neuharth, who will be 65 on March 22, will continue as a member
of the Gannett board of directors and as chairman of the Gannett
Foundation, the company announced. He will continue his weekly
``Plain Talk'' column in USA Today and others of Gannett's 88 daily
newspapers.
   Neuharth has been a Gannett executive for 25 years, the last 18
as president, chief executive officer or chairman.
   Curley, 49, has been CEO of Gannett since May 1986 and president
and chief operating officer since March 1984. He has held news and
management executive position at Gannett for 19 years.
   The Gannett board's action was announced to a year-end meeting of
400 company executives.
   Curley became the first editor of USA Today in January 1982,
directing the newspaper's development before its launching in
September of that year. Before joining Gannett in 1969, Curley
worked on newspapers in Pennsylvania and New Jersey and for The
Associated Press in New York and New Jersey.
   In addition to its daily newspapers, Gannett publishes 35
non-dailies and USA Weekend, a newspaper magazine. It also operates
10 television stations, 16 radio stations, Gannett News Services and
the largest outdoor advertising company in North America.
</TEXT>
